00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:10.240
[Amit Varma]: What an investment Deepak, welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:16.000
[Guest]: Hi Amit, always glad to have a conversation with you and lovely to be unseen in the unseen.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, this is oddly strangely, you know, after 200 episodes, the first time you're

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:24.840
[Amit Varma]: on the scene in the unseen and the thing is over the years, I've, you know, got so much

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:28.840
[Amit Varma]: delight and insight in the many long conversations that we've had.

00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:31.960
[Amit Varma]: And the bizarre thing is, and I wonder what you think about this, that, you know, I was

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:36.480
[Amit Varma]: sitting down figuring out all the areas that I'm going to talk to you about.

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:40.280
[Amit Varma]: And then at one point, it struck me that, wait a minute, this guy has been a personal

00:03:40.280 --> 00:03:41.800
[Amit Varma]: friend for a long time.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:46.040
[Amit Varma]: But many of the personal questions that, you know, are almost standard for me to ask my

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:49.760
[Amit Varma]: guests, I don't actually know about him, you know, and this is weird, because a couple

00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:53.080
[Amit Varma]: of days after this, I'm recording with another person who's been a personal friend for a

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:54.580
[Amit Varma]: couple of decades.

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:57.120
[Amit Varma]: And I realized that I don't know that much about her either.

00:03:57.120 --> 00:04:01.460
[Amit Varma]: So it's like you build a friendship by just hanging around and talking about whatever,

00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:05.760
[Amit Varma]: but you don't actually know so much about, about each other, which was a bit weird.

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:09.640
[Guest]: Which is actually quite fascinating, because you don't generally have relationships like

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:12.160
[Guest]: that after like, say, college or something like that.

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:17.400
[Guest]: So it's almost, almost entirely based on the intellectual framework of what we talk rather

00:04:17.400 --> 00:04:22.400
[Guest]: than a families or where are you going and you know, what have you done in the past and

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:28.120
[Guest]: all that stuff, which is definitely like, I mean, it's, that's what I was telling someone

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:32.800
[Guest]: when I was somebody is telling me who is asked, I was telling them who Amit Verma is, I'm

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:35.120
[Guest]: like, dude, he's so many things, man.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:36.840
[Guest]: He's been a professional poker player.

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:41.560
[Guest]: He's been a writer, he has been a cricket, not just enthusiast, but you know, so deeply

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:42.560
[Guest]: into cricket.

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:46.520
[Guest]: He has held guns in Peshawar.

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:52.020
[Guest]: And and pretended to be non Indian for, you know, so you know, there are so many things

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:55.240
[Guest]: about you that I know, but there's obviously a lot of other things.

00:04:55.240 --> 00:05:00.120
[Guest]: Somebody asked me, where is he from, and I'm like, shit, I have no idea.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:08.000
[Guest]: I don't even know whether he's, whether the Verma that the VARME is a UP wala surname

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:14.920
[Guest]: or a Bengali surname or and whether he's related to Raja Ravi Verma.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:20.360
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, no, no, sadly, I don't have any royal lineage that way, though my father is

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:24.120
[Amit Varma]: Punjabi and he was born just outside Lahore, pre partition.

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:26.920
[Amit Varma]: So some could even say that I am anti-national.

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:29.680
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, for those of my listeners who for the first time are wondering what

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:33.980
[Amit Varma]: was Amit doing holding a gun in Peshawar, no, I was not carrying out a secret mission

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:34.980
[Amit Varma]: for the Indian government.

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:38.840
[Amit Varma]: I was covering the Indian cricket tour to Pakistan in 2006.

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And I happened to kind of, you know, go to Peshawar at one of the venues and a friend

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:48.440
[Amit Varma]: and I managed to get some people to take us to the gun market, where guns are sold openly.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:52.920
[Amit Varma]: The friend was a journalist called Fazal Sharif, at that time he used to write for Rediff.

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:58.520
[Amit Varma]: And together we posed with guns, which is the macho-est I have ever looked, I won't

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:00.520
[Amit Varma]: say felt because, you know.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.480
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing is, you know, as listeners would have guessed, Deepak and I know each

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.640
[Amit Varma]: other from our blogging days, basically, which is where we met.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:11.160
[Amit Varma]: And I've realized that so many of my friends, in fact, all my closest friends, without exception,

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:14.540
[Amit Varma]: are not people from I know from school or from college or whatever.

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:19.560
[Amit Varma]: But really from that time, people who we managed to connect with through the internet in those

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:24.680
[Amit Varma]: days, sort of like minded people doing similar things, and that kind of becomes the basis

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:26.480
[Amit Varma]: for forming this little community.

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:30.200
[Amit Varma]: And this is something we now take for granted, right, that we can just form a community of

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:32.200
[Amit Varma]: choice at any point in time.

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:35.820
[Amit Varma]: And it started with our generation, you know, the generation before us would not have been

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:40.280
[Amit Varma]: able to reach out, you're basically constrained by geography, constrained by accidents of

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:42.400
[Amit Varma]: birth, all of those things.

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And now we can actually, you know, reach out and form a community based on shared interests

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:51.560
[Amit Varma]: or whatever the case may be, and it's mind blowing when you think about it.

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:58.240
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, it's the Orkut and MySpace and now WhatsApp and perhaps tomorrow Signal of

00:06:58.240 --> 00:06:59.800
[Guest]: Real Life.

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:04.920
[Guest]: And that's connected us and you know, it's strange, I have, I think, in the process of

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:09.920
[Guest]: us, you know, knowing each other, I've met you in Bangalore, in Bombay, perhaps in Delhi

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:11.320
[Guest]: as well.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:13.960
[Guest]: And I have traveled and lived in each of these places.

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:18.120
[Guest]: And yet, you know, when we talk to each other again, it's almost like, you know, it's starting

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:20.400
[Guest]: from the same point where we left off the last time.

00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:25.680
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, yeah, it's like you just click into place, you don't have to kind of, you know,

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:27.440
[Amit Varma]: reconnect again, or figure each other out.

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, if I met someone from my college days, or whatever, there would be this process of

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:35.880
[Amit Varma]: reconnection, because you're meeting fundamentally a changed person and trying to kind of figure

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:36.880
[Amit Varma]: that out.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:38.720
[Amit Varma]: But that reminds me there is a lot I don't know about you.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:45.120
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, let's kind of get a little deeper into the history of Deepak Shannoy.

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:49.580
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I do want to spend a lot of this time talking about investing in your philosophy

00:07:49.580 --> 00:07:52.680
[Amit Varma]: towards money and life and all of those things.

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:57.680
[Amit Varma]: But before that, tell me a little bit about who the young Deepak Shannoy was like growing

00:07:57.680 --> 00:07:58.680
[Amit Varma]: up?

00:07:58.680 --> 00:07:59.680
[Amit Varma]: What kind of kid were you?

00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:01.680
[Amit Varma]: What did you want to be when you grew up?

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:03.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, what were the influences on you?

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:05.000
[Amit Varma]: What kind of books did you read?

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:07.600
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that part of your journey.

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:14.760
[Guest]: So you know, my youngest, perhaps as far as I can remember, my father was in a bank.

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:18.120
[Guest]: So transferable job moving around quite a bit.

00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:24.100
[Guest]: You know, I come from this little town in a village in the Western Ghats in Karnataka.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:27.040
[Guest]: But then since my father was in a bank, we travel everywhere.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:33.060
[Guest]: So I think my early days were in Udaipur and you know, Agra and a couple of other places.

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:39.040
[Guest]: But then since the time I actually remember things, I was in Bangalore till I think 1983

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:41.360
[Guest]: or 1982.

00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:44.940
[Guest]: And I actually studied in a girl's school.

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:49.200
[Guest]: What is a girl's school after fourth standard and boys were allowed till the fourth standard

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:53.920
[Guest]: because I don't know, there's some rule that you know, maybe boys are okay till they're

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.760
[Guest]: in the fourth standard and then they get really bad after that.

00:08:56.760 --> 00:09:03.720
[Guest]: So it was interesting because I still know people or reconnected with people from that

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:05.000
[Guest]: school.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.520
[Guest]: And they're fascinating personalities, you know, so it's almost like I wish I knew more

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:13.200
[Guest]: at that age that I could have remembered in terms of conversations.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.440
[Guest]: But that part of life was interesting.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.280
[Guest]: It was also the first time I started to learn about books.

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:20.840
[Guest]: This is probably early in my life.

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:22.200
[Guest]: I always liked reading.

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:28.800
[Guest]: I still do to the point where my mom used to literally give me a comic and I would walk

00:09:28.800 --> 00:09:32.840
[Guest]: with her through marketplaces when she had to go shopping and I would not complain even

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:37.240
[Guest]: a little bit because I'd read the book every chance I got.

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:41.680
[Guest]: And the books, of course, you know, the early days were Amar Chitra Katha and a bunch of

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:43.720
[Guest]: those things and all that.

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:50.080
[Guest]: But it evolved eventually, I moved to Delhi when I was about after my third standard.

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:52.640
[Guest]: So again, Delhi was very interesting.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:10:00.120
[Guest]: It was, we landed up in Delhi, I think the year or maybe the year before the Indira Gandhi

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:02.560
[Guest]: was assassinated.

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:07.680
[Guest]: And that was a learning thing for me because I was like probably 10 years old at the time.

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:10.120
[Guest]: And it was a few days before my birthday.

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:19.520
[Guest]: So I really did not, you know, find it very interesting to have spent the birthday at

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:20.520
[Guest]: home.

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:23.760
[Guest]: But then when I came out, it was a whole new world.

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:27.640
[Guest]: Bunch of things that you don't want to learn when you're 10 years old, you learn and, you

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:31.440
[Guest]: know, it kind of made a very different kind of impact in my life.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:36.560
[Guest]: Those are the years where you would go everywhere in Delhi and you would see soldiers sitting

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:41.920
[Guest]: in, you know, cages and behind sacks all over the place.

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:47.840
[Guest]: So and you, you know, we found out later that you're not allowed to approach them either.

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:50.120
[Guest]: So it was, it was dangerous to do so.

00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:52.920
[Guest]: But I mean, interesting times growing up.

00:10:52.920 --> 00:10:54.360
[Guest]: Those are the early days.

00:10:54.360 --> 00:11:00.680
[Guest]: I don't think I, I mean, till when after that we moved back to Bangalore, I wrote an exam,

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:03.800
[Guest]: probably the first exam I ever scored any reasonable marks in.

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:06.400
[Guest]: Luckily, that was the 12th standard exams.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest]: So I managed to go to this college called NIT, which is now called NIT Suratkal.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.120
[Guest]: Earlier it was to be REC Suratkal.

00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:22.440
[Guest]: And I still like the name REC Suratkal, it's Karnataka REC, so K-R-E-C, which was, I mean,

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:27.840
[Guest]: it has a zing to it, N-I-T-K does not sound as quite as zingy, but that's what the name

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:28.840
[Guest]: of the college is now.

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:33.640
[Guest]: It's a quaint little college in, well, it's not little, it's about 350 acres of campus

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:39.360
[Guest]: in near the beach, it actually has its own beach, but it's next to a beach.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:43.400
[Guest]: We did not appreciate it then and now I feel sorry I did not appreciate it then.

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:49.000
[Guest]: But that was a formative years because till, you know, when you're, till you're 18 years

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:55.200
[Guest]: old, sheltered, you're at home, do your thing, and you're suddenly thrown into college where

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:56.200
[Guest]: you're alone.

00:11:56.200 --> 00:12:02.000
[Guest]: I mean, that's okay, but you get ragged, you do your things, you have to, you know, fend

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
[Guest]: for yourself.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:10.480
[Guest]: But you also learn a few things about freedom, about doing stuff the way you want to do them.

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:15.800
[Guest]: And a couple of years in, you kind of realize that you'll never be able to live in a sheltered,

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:22.480
[Guest]: cloistered environment again, simply because you've, for all the good and bad that comes

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:26.760
[Guest]: of it, that you have to wash up notes and stuff like that.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:31.840
[Guest]: It's just far more acceptable to do that, rather than trade away the other freedoms

00:12:31.840 --> 00:12:32.840
[Guest]: that you have.

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:38.120
[Guest]: So college was eye opening for that, and from another perspective, because I finally discovered

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:44.040
[Guest]: what I thought I would do for the rest of my life, which is computer programming, because

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:48.200
[Guest]: somewhere in the, they used to call me LAN user, because, you know, in the first year,

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:53.800
[Guest]: you had these local area networks that were set up in the college, and everybody got the

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:55.240
[Guest]: same user ID.

00:12:55.240 --> 00:13:00.840
[Guest]: You had to log in with the user ID LAN user, and the password was LAN user, very creative,

00:13:00.840 --> 00:13:02.000
[Guest]: you know, thing.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:08.240
[Guest]: So I was, because I went then, first year, I discovered that I really like this stuff.

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:12.720
[Guest]: And maybe I wasn't very good at it, but I was just at it at the time.

00:13:12.720 --> 00:13:18.800
[Guest]: And I learned from a few other people that I went and I was initially in this branch

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:22.800
[Guest]: in mechanical engineering, and then I asked for a shift to computer engineering.

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:27.720
[Guest]: And that's when I discovered that I really like the subject, the concept of it, and relatively

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:30.760
[Guest]: knew that I was 1992, 1993.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:34.920
[Guest]: The interesting thing about this part of my life was that I was, I didn't know what I

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:35.920
[Guest]: wanted to do.

00:13:35.920 --> 00:13:36.920
[Guest]: I had no idea.

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:44.320
[Guest]: I'd worked with some computers in the earlier past, but I'd never actually seen, you know,

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:45.800
[Guest]: computers really work.

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:50.060
[Guest]: And they told us at one point that you're not allowed to play games.

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:52.880
[Guest]: So we said, okay, you know what, we're going to write our own game.

00:13:52.880 --> 00:14:01.280
[Guest]: So I wrote a very weird version of Pac-Man, and then, you know, nobody could say anything

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:03.320
[Guest]: because it was a game I programmed.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:07.080
[Guest]: So I was like, I'm testing it, it's perfectly legal to do.

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:13.520
[Guest]: And so the word LAN user, I was a nerd for all practical purposes, probably still am,

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:16.320
[Guest]: but finance makes you less nerdy, I guess.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:21.640
[Guest]: But interestingly, you know, that college actually opened it up because what happens

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:28.320
[Guest]: was there was, because of its relative distance from anything human, they allowed you a lot

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:29.320
[Guest]: of things.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:33.480
[Guest]: So for instance, I was given the permission to keep the LAN open until whatever time I

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:34.480
[Guest]: wanted.

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:37.160
[Guest]: I was given a key and said, you know, just shut it down when you're done.

00:14:37.160 --> 00:14:39.840
[Guest]: So we do these things and we'd learn a lot of these things.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:45.520
[Guest]: And then once I got into my second year, the first year is in my college was common across

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:46.520
[Guest]: all branches.

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:47.680
[Guest]: Everybody took the same subjects.

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:51.280
[Guest]: The second year onwards, you got your specific subjects.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:53.080
[Guest]: And then it carried on further.

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:58.520
[Guest]: We did very interesting things with stuff that you can do on your phone in five minutes.

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:02.460
[Guest]: Sometimes it would take us two or three days to do, so you had to prep for it.

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:05.560
[Guest]: So you had to think about the code that you'd write, and then you'd write it, and then you'd

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:09.640
[Guest]: hit the compile or render or whatever it was that you did.

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:14.120
[Guest]: And suddenly it would take two days for it to render something, which was like a little

00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:15.920
[Guest]: box coming out of something else.

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:21.440
[Guest]: And because I don't even ask because we, I mean, the first, this is all again, you know,

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:26.960
[Guest]: stuff that when our parents used to tell us things like, you know, Deepak, you don't know

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:29.840
[Guest]: the value of poverty.

00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:35.400
[Guest]: And you know, I used to, before I took my, went to school, I had to take water out of

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:41.240
[Guest]: the well and have the seven brothers and sisters I had, all of them had to have a bath.

00:15:41.240 --> 00:15:44.680
[Guest]: And then I would walk five miles to college, to school.

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:48.920
[Guest]: And then they would carry, I'd be like, dude, this is just like, this is just stuff that

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:54.240
[Guest]: I, I mean, I'll never do, I'll never be able to even see an op, I just turn the tap and

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:55.660
[Guest]: water comes.

00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:58.360
[Guest]: It's pretty much that effort.

00:15:58.360 --> 00:16:02.920
[Guest]: So my, when I tell my kids, you know, I used to operate in a time when you had 1.44 inch

00:16:02.920 --> 00:16:03.920
[Guest]: floppies.

00:16:03.920 --> 00:16:07.960
[Guest]: And I don't know, there was another one, three, some three and a quarter or five and a quarter

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:08.960
[Guest]: inch floppies.

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:13.800
[Guest]: And you didn't have hard disks, so one of the drives contained your basic compiler and

00:16:13.800 --> 00:16:17.600
[Guest]: the other one contained the place where your code was stored.

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:21.480
[Guest]: And if you had only one drive, you had to put one in, load the basic into memory, and

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:23.680
[Guest]: then put the second one in to store your program.

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest]: So it was like, crazy stuff that, you know, my kids look at me like, what's a floppy disk?

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:33.800
[Guest]: I'm like, it's the before, what's what came before CDs, like, what is, what's a CD?

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:36.080
[Guest]: And I'm like, okay, dude, I am done.

00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:43.160
[Guest]: I mean, this is at this point, it's like, you know, but I mean, I lived that life, which

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:49.440
[Guest]: I guess is exotic from today's perspective, but, you know, today would be exotic for them.

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:55.240
[Guest]: So you know, that makes us even, but, you know, all through this early days of well,

00:16:55.240 --> 00:17:02.440
[Guest]: I think the point was, while I liked reading a lot, I still do, most of it for at least

00:17:02.440 --> 00:17:05.160
[Guest]: the first 20, 20 odd years of my life was fiction.

00:17:05.160 --> 00:17:11.360
[Guest]: So nice, you know, from the Frederick Fawcett's to Arthur Haley's, and you know, the stuff

00:17:11.360 --> 00:17:16.640
[Guest]: that, you know, was probably exciting at the time, and the Asterix's and the Tintin's,

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:21.040
[Guest]: and later the Calvin and Hobbes, that became kind of a story of choice.

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:28.240
[Guest]: But then, soon after college, I mean, that was just the early part of my life, I'm rambling

00:17:28.240 --> 00:17:29.240
[Guest]: a little bit over there.

00:17:29.240 --> 00:17:35.800
[Guest]: So but I kind of finished college and joined this company, which is now Emphasis, that

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:40.240
[Guest]: time it was called BFL software, there was a bunch of mergers and all that.

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:47.520
[Guest]: And I was sent to the US in about three months, and at that time, things were very weird,

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:53.760
[Guest]: because I was sent as a qualified engineer to the US on a project where I literally did

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:57.800
[Guest]: not know more than maybe 20 lines of code.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:01.600
[Guest]: So I had to go there, I had to pretend that I, I mean, not pretend, but I told them I'm

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:02.600
[Guest]: new to this.

00:18:02.600 --> 00:18:11.640
[Guest]: And we figured out the code, mostly after we'd gone there, met a bunch of customers,

00:18:11.640 --> 00:18:15.160
[Guest]: you know, did a lot of crazy things, because your first time in the US, you have no idea

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:16.160
[Guest]: what to expect.

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:20.760
[Guest]: I remember I'd gone to this place called Omaha, I mean, now it's more famous because of Warren

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:24.520
[Guest]: Buffett, because at that time, it was famous for Jackal, I think.

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:28.320
[Guest]: But you know, at, at the time, I hadn't even heard of Omaha.

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:37.000
[Guest]: And I, nobody told me that when they say minus two degrees with a windchill of minus 20 degrees,

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.920
[Guest]: it actually means you're going to feel like it's minus 20 degrees.

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:46.760
[Guest]: So I went to the little jacket, which had absolutely no chance against, you know, even

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:49.880
[Guest]: minus two degrees, but then I was willing to risk it.

00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:53.440
[Guest]: But minus 20, I mean, it's like, oh, dude, I am dying.

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:58.320
[Guest]: So we went in, it was kind of embarrassing, because when we landed up there with that

00:18:58.320 --> 00:19:05.240
[Guest]: jacket, the customers looked at us, are you like, are you serious?

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:07.040
[Guest]: Because you're gonna die in that.

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:14.080
[Guest]: So we said, okay, and then we had to go pick up a jacket from one of the supermarkets.

00:19:14.080 --> 00:19:20.240
[Guest]: And you know, I think I use a jacket for literally all my cold, you know, adventures for at least

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:22.440
[Guest]: 20 years afterwards, it was pretty good.

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:26.600
[Guest]: But you could not even think of wearing that in India, it was just impossible.

00:19:26.600 --> 00:19:31.440
[Guest]: It's just one of those things that's, you know, but that taught me a lot about living

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:33.840
[Guest]: in America, different ways.

00:19:33.840 --> 00:19:35.800
[Guest]: You have a very fancy view of this, right?

00:19:35.800 --> 00:19:41.520
[Guest]: So you sit in India, and you read books about this and that, you go there and say, well,

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:45.600
[Guest]: these are the same people, just different accent, right?

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:53.800
[Guest]: It's not, in a way, superheroes kind of thought process that you started off with.

00:19:53.800 --> 00:19:58.360
[Guest]: And also the place, it's, I mean, it's developed, yes, but, you know, there is some kind of

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:00.600
[Guest]: wretched poverty is there as well.

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:06.000
[Guest]: And there is a kind of standard of living that you suddenly realize that life is very

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:11.000
[Guest]: limiting if you don't have a lot of money, very obvious in the US, later in my adventures

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:16.960
[Guest]: in Europe, I found that was not so much the case, but I mean, after I finished that, I

00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:21.160
[Guest]: think my only thing in college was that I want to start my own business.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest]: I didn't know why, but I really wanted to start my own business.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:30.920
[Guest]: And when I went to the US, I was applying to colleges to do my master's degree in science

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:31.920
[Guest]: there.

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:35.080
[Guest]: And then I decided I won't because I want to start my own business.

00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:39.600
[Guest]: But for some reason, I had a job offer from the company that I was visiting, and they

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:44.440
[Guest]: were kind of cutting off the contract with the emphasis at the time of BFL at the time.

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:47.400
[Guest]: And they said, we'd like to hire you guys.

00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:50.720
[Guest]: And we said, okay, we're okay with that.

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:57.400
[Guest]: And now, unfortunately, my father passed away in India at the time, 24, it was very complicated,

00:20:57.400 --> 00:21:03.600
[Guest]: because he was a banker, he had held the key to a lot of finances in the family.

00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:08.920
[Guest]: And I had no idea what any of that stuff was that he did.

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:17.440
[Guest]: So also, I mean, of course, grief was one that was very complicated, because, you know,

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:19.640
[Guest]: I always thought that I never spent enough time.

00:21:19.640 --> 00:21:24.560
[Guest]: And now I still regret that in the sense of, I went to college, I was doing my own thing.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:31.320
[Guest]: And I remember my mom, after I had gotten out of college, I was desperate to get started

00:21:31.320 --> 00:21:32.320
[Guest]: on my job.

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:36.160
[Guest]: And my mom said, you know, stay on for a couple of months more, you have another job offer

00:21:36.160 --> 00:21:38.880
[Guest]: that starts in November, why are you leaving now?

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:43.120
[Guest]: So I said, No, I am going because I want to start working early, as early as possible.

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:44.120
[Guest]: This was August.

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:47.360
[Guest]: Now, he passed away in February the next year.

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:54.000
[Guest]: So that two months would have been nice, but, you know, such is life.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:59.600
[Guest]: Unfortunately, I wasn't able to, you know, spend that much time with him.

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:05.000
[Guest]: When I was, you know, when I had the time, and you know, sometimes that that that old

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:10.520
[Guest]: saying of, you know, the cats in the cradle, the song kind of come to mind, you know, it's

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:14.000
[Guest]: strange, because that song was something I heard in college.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:17.080
[Guest]: And I said, Listen, this is deep, but I don't understand it.

00:22:17.080 --> 00:22:20.000
[Guest]: And I knew it was deep, but I didn't understand.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.560
[Guest]: And it's like Calvin and Hobbes, the first time when you read it, when you're a kid,

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:24.920
[Guest]: you don't, you know, there's something in there that's deeper.

00:22:24.920 --> 00:22:30.360
[Guest]: And as you go further in life, you say, that is like philosophy, it's not a cartoon.

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:34.720
[Guest]: But there's something in that song that that kind of talked to me that time.

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:39.160
[Guest]: And then when my father passed away, I had that, I heard the song again.

00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:42.840
[Guest]: And then I was like, this is real.

00:22:42.840 --> 00:22:46.800
[Guest]: And now when I have kids, it's just a different meaning altogether, you're dealing with it

00:22:46.800 --> 00:22:48.440
[Guest]: from three different angles.

00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:49.880
[Guest]: And you know, it's the same song.

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:51.240
[Guest]: And it's beautiful.

00:22:51.240 --> 00:22:55.680
[Guest]: So but since that time, and I came back to India, I said, Listen, I'm not taking the

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:59.680
[Guest]: job in the US, I have to figure out more stuff.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:03.840
[Guest]: And I think if my goal is to start a business, then I should do it here in India and the

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:09.160
[Guest]: US was, and this is what my dad told me before he passed away, like, if you want to start

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:14.960
[Guest]: a business, why are you locking yourself to a six year period in the US when you can't

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:16.360
[Guest]: start a business?

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:20.240
[Guest]: So like, what do you mean is then I looked it up and said, Yeah, I mean, if you're in

00:23:20.240 --> 00:23:24.800
[Guest]: an H1B visa, until you get yourself a green card, you can't start a business, you can

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:29.720
[Guest]: join a business that started, they can process your visa, but you can't really start a business.

00:23:29.720 --> 00:23:31.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's complicated at the time.

00:23:31.480 --> 00:23:35.800
[Guest]: So I said, Dude, I'm not doing this, I'm going back to India, I want to start my business.

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:41.280
[Guest]: So a couple of years down the line, started a business, we built a lot of things for people

00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:48.400
[Guest]: using a language called Delphi, pretty computer thing, but came into this finance thing at

00:23:48.400 --> 00:23:55.200
[Guest]: that time, because we started writing software for companies that wanted accounting as part

00:23:55.200 --> 00:23:56.200
[Guest]: of their application.

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:59.760
[Guest]: So I was like, what is this accounting business, let me read it.

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:05.480
[Guest]: And you know, my father, my uncle, everybody in the family were bankers, my surname kind

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:06.480
[Guest]: of gives it away.

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:08.800
[Guest]: But that's how, you know, the whole family was.

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:11.360
[Guest]: And I was this dude, I'm a computer engineer.

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:13.600
[Guest]: And I was different from everybody else.

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:17.240
[Guest]: So it's this accounting thing that kind of came by.

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:20.600
[Guest]: And through this process, I learned about accounting.

00:24:20.600 --> 00:24:25.260
[Guest]: I started my own business when I was 24, I think.

00:24:25.260 --> 00:24:28.760
[Guest]: And then I ran that till I was about 30 before I got married.

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:33.720
[Guest]: And in this process, we built accounting packages, we built something that was an Indian accounting

00:24:33.720 --> 00:24:34.920
[Guest]: package.

00:24:34.920 --> 00:24:39.840
[Guest]: And we got, so what we found interesting in this whole thing was that you could look at

00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:45.160
[Guest]: public companies, because they would give their accounts to the public every year and

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:46.600
[Guest]: every quarter.

00:24:46.600 --> 00:24:48.480
[Guest]: And you could actually download it from their websites.

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:52.000
[Guest]: Somewhere in the middle, we started looking at this and saying, okay, we could download

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:53.740
[Guest]: this account, we can get these.

00:24:53.740 --> 00:24:59.160
[Guest]: So got interested in public markets, started writing about it in 2005, worked a couple

00:24:59.160 --> 00:25:00.920
[Guest]: more companies.

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:07.480
[Guest]: I think I got, if I say I'm good at something, it's only because I was really bad at it.

00:25:07.480 --> 00:25:10.260
[Guest]: And I decided not to be through the process.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:14.680
[Guest]: So I think I was, when I look at my early posts, even now, I cringe and say, what kind

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:16.720
[Guest]: of thought process was that?

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:20.400
[Guest]: But it's good now, I mean, the blog came along.

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:25.360
[Guest]: And you know, here I am, I won't bore you with the further details of what else happened.

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:28.800
[Guest]: But I hope this has been, it's a very different part.

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:32.720
[Guest]: I think I met you in like 2007 or something.

00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:34.960
[Guest]: So since then, we've been in touch.

00:25:34.960 --> 00:25:40.720
[Guest]: I guess I came to Bombay, I did a bunch of things around algorithmic trading.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:44.280
[Guest]: Before and I found out to my chagrin, it was even legal.

00:25:44.280 --> 00:25:48.920
[Guest]: So it was, it was apparently not legal to auto trade.

00:25:48.920 --> 00:25:54.720
[Guest]: So we had to physically and hit the enter key whenever you actually enter a trade.

00:25:54.720 --> 00:26:03.520
[Guest]: So we did that so that you could hit, I mean, so a human being had to say okay on a trade

00:26:03.520 --> 00:26:05.880
[Guest]: before it was, it went to the exchange.

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:09.280
[Guest]: Now of course, things have changed and you can trade automatically, computers can work

00:26:09.280 --> 00:26:10.280
[Guest]: with each other.

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:16.040
[Guest]: But we wanted to build this stuff in 2008, fascinating because I helped in another hedge

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:20.920
[Guest]: fund which actually did this when SEBI finally legalized it.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:24.520
[Guest]: And now, you know, they're 30% of the volume of the exchange.

00:26:24.520 --> 00:26:32.040
[Guest]: So I'm saying algo trading as not just this firm, but algo trading as a whole is now a

00:26:32.040 --> 00:26:33.040
[Guest]: feature of the exchange.

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:38.120
[Guest]: They started Capital Mind, of course, when it was 2013.

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:41.760
[Guest]: That's kind of blossomed into a fairly decent business.

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:44.960
[Guest]: And I suppose you'll probably ask me a bunch around investing.

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:48.080
[Guest]: So I'll probably go into detail when we when we go through that.

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:53.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, before we get to sort of investing and Capital Mind and algo trading about which

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:56.480
[Amit Varma]: I also want to ask you, you know, the backstory is really fascinating.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:27:00.600
[Amit Varma]: And there are a bunch of threads from here that I want to pull, which actually come kind

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:01.600
[Amit Varma]: of to the same question.

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:05.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one, of course, is, you know, what you said about being really bad at it before

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:06.480
[Amit Varma]: you got good at it.

00:27:06.480 --> 00:27:10.800
[Amit Varma]: And that struck a chord with me, because I just came about this thread on Twitter by

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:14.600
[Amit Varma]: a random person I won't name, not an Indian, but basically which went viral.

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:19.560
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things he said in that thread was that, you know, I don't follow people

00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:24.720
[Amit Varma]: who post regularly, because you know, you can't get a great flash of insight every day.

00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:27.560
[Amit Varma]: So if you're posting too regularly, I don't follow you.

00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:30.380
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I prefer people who post just once in a while.

00:27:30.380 --> 00:27:33.480
[Amit Varma]: And I thought, wait a minute, that is completely the wrong way around.

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:36.200
[Amit Varma]: Because when you begin doing something, you're bad at it.

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:39.960
[Amit Varma]: What makes for excellence, repeated iteration makes for excellence.

00:27:39.960 --> 00:27:44.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, you do something repeatedly every freaking day, and you always begin something

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:48.680
[Amit Varma]: is bad, and then you get good at it, because you've done it again and again and again.

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:51.880
[Amit Varma]: And examples from the blogging world would be something like Marginal Revolution, for

00:27:51.880 --> 00:27:57.940
[Amit Varma]: example, or, and you know, literally anything, you know, Virat Kohli was not going to the

00:27:57.940 --> 00:28:01.800
[Amit Varma]: nets once a week, he was going there and spending seven hours a day every freaking day through

00:28:01.800 --> 00:28:07.080
[Amit Varma]: his childhood, till iteration, iteration, iteration, and you get to excellence.

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:12.440
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of that process of learning something that I want to delve deeper into.

