[Amit Varma]: nostalgic about the bad old days, I would say, when, you know, you couldn't do anything

00:28:20.400 --> 00:28:24.520
[Amit Varma]: on the computer, because you plug anything in, you've got to install 40 drivers, and

00:28:24.520 --> 00:28:26.440
[Amit Varma]: nothing works together and all of that.

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:30.920
[Amit Varma]: And we were just setting up our mics and stuff before this, and it was all relatively smooth.

00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:35.280
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me that we are sort of that, again, I'll say a unique generation, perhaps

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:41.280
[Amit Varma]: not in a good way, just in an interesting way, that one, we do a lot of our learning,

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:43.960
[Amit Varma]: our formative years are spent before the internet.

00:28:43.960 --> 00:28:48.080
[Amit Varma]: So we are restricted in terms of what we can learn by whatever we are privileged to have

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:51.480
[Amit Varma]: around us, which could be the books that we have, or whatever.

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:54.840
[Amit Varma]: And both of us are relatively privileged in Indian terms, in the sense we got to read

00:28:54.840 --> 00:28:57.600
[Amit Varma]: a lot when we were growing up and all of that.

00:28:57.600 --> 00:29:01.320
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, we don't really have access to most of the knowledge in the world.

00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:06.440
[Amit Varma]: And then at least in my case, another big part of my learning comes even growing up

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:11.840
[Amit Varma]: when the internet happens, and when I'm exposed to ideas and all of this from everywhere.

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:16.220
[Amit Varma]: And the question that I'm leading up to is, one, did this sort of process happen with

00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:17.280
[Amit Varma]: you as well?

00:29:17.280 --> 00:29:22.360
[Amit Varma]: And two, how does one build up mental frameworks to which we look at the world?

00:29:22.360 --> 00:29:27.040
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing that I've noticed about you is that while you're brilliant at investing,

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:32.280
[Amit Varma]: one of the reasons that makes you much more interesting than other investors I have met

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:38.520
[Amit Varma]: is that you are bringing to bear mental models, which have to do not just with investing alone,

00:29:38.520 --> 00:29:42.920
[Amit Varma]: which have to do with life, which have to do with human beings, with the way we behave.

00:29:42.920 --> 00:29:44.840
[Amit Varma]: And then you're applying a lot of it to investing.

00:29:44.840 --> 00:29:50.460
[Amit Varma]: And then obviously, you're getting a lot of specific domain specific insights as well.

00:29:50.460 --> 00:29:53.960
[Amit Varma]: But how did building these mental models kind of happen?

00:29:53.960 --> 00:29:59.980
[Amit Varma]: What was this process like of the formation of Deepak Shenoy as a person?

00:29:59.980 --> 00:30:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Because with most people, this would happen by the time you're 20 to 23, it has happened.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:09.000
[Amit Varma]: But for people who are in their mid 40s, like us, and I think our ages are not a secret

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:10.000
[Amit Varma]: to anyone.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:14.600
[Amit Varma]: It's been this complicated, almost staggered process, where the internet sort of causes

00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:15.760
[Amit Varma]: this explosion.

00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:18.200
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, you learn all over again.

00:30:18.200 --> 00:30:19.960
[Guest]: So what are sort of your thoughts on this?

00:30:19.960 --> 00:30:25.400
[Guest]: Yes, you know, I mean, if you think about the internet, it's actually changed one big

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:28.080
[Guest]: thing, which is opportunity for us.

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:33.440
[Guest]: You could not do this without a lot of the stuff that we're doing, including what we're

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:36.000
[Guest]: doing right now, without the internet.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:42.640
[Guest]: And one of the things that I realized is that the hunger for knowledge exists, and maybe

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:47.700
[Guest]: it was privilege, maybe it was whatever it was, that you could solve that hunger for

00:30:47.700 --> 00:30:51.240
[Guest]: knowledge in different ways when you're younger.

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:58.360
[Guest]: I always felt, for instance, I mean, I am a social person, but I'm actually quite introvertish

00:30:58.360 --> 00:31:01.700
[Guest]: when it comes to a lot of gatherings and all that stuff.

00:31:01.700 --> 00:31:07.640
[Guest]: So I prefer to sit and curl up and read and, you know, think and walk and all that stuff.

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:14.040
[Guest]: But somewhere, so this is where I think I credit my college for this, is that you got

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:20.680
[Guest]: long periods to yourself, long, very, really long, and then in this process was the discovery

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:22.540
[Guest]: of myself.

00:31:22.540 --> 00:31:24.560
[Guest]: Maybe it was in bits and pieces over time.

00:31:24.560 --> 00:31:29.960
[Guest]: But what I discovered is that there are a lot of things that I like, I mean, I like

00:31:29.960 --> 00:31:35.520
[Guest]: marginally and a little bit here and there, the stuff that and there is very clearly stuff

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:41.600
[Guest]: I don't like, Fourier transforms, I think that is one thing I can tell you categorically

00:31:41.600 --> 00:31:42.600
[Guest]: that I don't like.

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:49.080
[Guest]: I don't like to eat curd or cheese, something I discovered when I was young, so I was, I

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:50.080
[Guest]: cannot do it.

00:31:50.080 --> 00:31:54.240
[Guest]: And I, even in college mess, people would fight for a seat next to me because I would

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:59.080
[Guest]: give them my little ration of curd that you'd be like, dude, I don't want it in my plate.

00:31:59.080 --> 00:32:01.440
[Guest]: And people would swap that with like, even chicken.

00:32:01.440 --> 00:32:06.040
[Guest]: And I was like, dude, this is like a, I mean, you want to do this bargain every day, I'm

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:07.040
[Guest]: on for it.

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:11.520
[Guest]: But, but that was like, you know, a few things that I didn't like a few things that I liked

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:17.640
[Guest]: in mental models, when you're younger is like, you shouldn't not like something.

00:32:17.640 --> 00:32:22.200
[Guest]: And you shouldn't tell some, because when you as you grow up, you have to be polite,

00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:24.280
[Guest]: you have to try and learn stuff, right?

00:32:24.280 --> 00:32:28.480
[Guest]: You can't categorically say, I don't like this subject, and because you have to do it,

00:32:28.480 --> 00:32:33.760
[Guest]: it's part of, but somewhere along the lines, I found out that what I liked, I would pursue

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:39.240
[Guest]: and maybe it was the kind of college I was in, or maybe the kind of person I was in,

00:32:39.240 --> 00:32:47.720
[Guest]: I have no shame in losing, or, you know, it's like, when you crack a bad joke, and people

00:32:47.720 --> 00:32:49.160
[Guest]: like want to kill you.

00:32:49.160 --> 00:32:52.880
[Guest]: And then you don't crack bad jokes, because they want to kill you.

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:57.960
[Guest]: I was never the kind of guy who would stop at not, but I would not crack the bad joke.

00:32:57.960 --> 00:33:00.280
[Guest]: I'm like, dude, if you want to kill me, kill me, but I want to keep trying.

00:33:00.280 --> 00:33:04.080
[Guest]: So once once in a while, you get a good job, but mostly bad even now.

00:33:04.080 --> 00:33:10.760
[Guest]: So, but interestingly, that philosophy maintains itself even in.

00:33:10.760 --> 00:33:13.040
[Guest]: So it's like, you know, when you're doing something, you want to try it.

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:17.520
[Guest]: And the best thing about computers in the early stages was that you could do this, you

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:22.880
[Guest]: would hit compile, and then it would say error, then say, okay, it's an error, let me go back

00:33:22.880 --> 00:33:23.880
[Guest]: and fix it.

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:28.160
[Guest]: And somewhere along the line, you learn that this is the right way to do things.

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:33.040
[Guest]: And then even that right way to do things keeps changing over a long period of time.

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:37.360
[Guest]: And it's a learning process throughout there.

00:33:37.360 --> 00:33:42.760
[Guest]: From the time when I started, there was Visual Basic to start that then there was Pascal

00:33:42.760 --> 00:33:43.760
[Guest]: and C++.

00:33:43.760 --> 00:33:49.640
[Guest]: And now there are, you know, name the I mean, they have languages which don't have vowels

00:33:49.640 --> 00:33:52.240
[Guest]: and their languages with only vowels and no syllables.

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:57.040
[Guest]: And, you know, there's a guy who's made a YouTube video and all the different kinds

00:33:57.040 --> 00:34:01.120
[Guest]: of languages out there, which is like, it's an hour long, and he's like, I'm not even

00:34:01.120 --> 00:34:02.920
[Guest]: scratched the surface, and I believe him.

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:07.720
[Guest]: But at that time, my deal was, I want to learn all these programming languages, I want to

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:13.680
[Guest]: learn Fortran, I did, I learned COBOL, I taught COBOL in my final year, to other people and

00:34:13.680 --> 00:34:17.840
[Guest]: earn some money out of it, because they had a job which had a COBOL as an entrance this

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:19.600
[Guest]: thing, paper or something like that.

00:34:19.600 --> 00:34:24.760
[Guest]: So I learned COBOL, in order to be able to earn the money to do other things.

00:34:24.760 --> 00:34:29.520
[Guest]: So this process, this thought process has kind of continued since then, you're curious

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:34.960
[Guest]: about something, you'd learn it, find it interesting, delve into it some more, during the process

00:34:34.960 --> 00:34:36.920
[Guest]: of accounting, or learning accounting.

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:42.000
[Guest]: And by the way, accounting is this weird thing, I still don't think I get it.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:49.080
[Guest]: But it has these, you know, in English language, they'll say, Oh, you know what, in there are

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:51.320
[Guest]: some letters that are silent.

00:34:51.320 --> 00:34:52.600
[Guest]: And you're like, why?

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:56.920
[Guest]: And then you'll ask about this, and then they'll come to you with a letter like through, and

00:34:56.920 --> 00:35:04.040
[Guest]: then through has THR, which is fine, and then OUGH, which is like, excuse me, why?

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:06.640
[Guest]: Why do you have all those extra letters?

00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:11.880
[Guest]: And why is there an H and a G and you know, but obviously, there are some rules and you

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:15.160
[Guest]: kind of learn that these are rules and you can't violate these rules.

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:20.120
[Guest]: And the same way in accounting, there are some rules, some stuff which you don't understand,

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:22.520
[Guest]: which is not logical, but it's there.

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:24.000
[Guest]: That's the way they've decided things are.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:30.120
[Guest]: And then you look at this thing and say, well, you know what, this doesn't seem to add up

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:33.880
[Guest]: because you said these two add up to that, and it doesn't add up.

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:40.080
[Guest]: And then they tell you, well, that's because the company is bullshitting its way out here,

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:45.640
[Guest]: they've added somewhere else and something else is on, excuse me, company can do this.

00:35:45.640 --> 00:35:50.640
[Guest]: And then you find out that companies are this stuff that people use to cook their books

00:35:50.640 --> 00:35:53.560
[Guest]: and this stuff that's real.

00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:58.480
[Guest]: So over time, it's fascinating to try and find those little things, it's like these

00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:00.440
[Guest]: little puzzles that come around to you.

00:36:00.440 --> 00:36:05.760
[Guest]: So looking at stuff, looking at numbers, and my wife and my kids also now look at me and

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:08.920
[Guest]: say, dad, that's just like numbers.

00:36:08.920 --> 00:36:11.320
[Guest]: And I'm like, yeah, that's my job.

00:36:11.320 --> 00:36:14.880
[Guest]: But then I'll be looking at those numbers with this fascination that says, well, now

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:19.080
[Guest]: I can figure out that something isn't right.

00:36:19.080 --> 00:36:24.200
[Guest]: If I looked at those numbers, somewhere, some things start to throw themselves at you and

00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:26.840
[Guest]: saying, got to look here a little bit closer.

00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:32.160
[Guest]: It's the strangest thing because today, for instance, there was the results of an IT company.

00:36:32.160 --> 00:36:37.160
[Guest]: So the one number I looked for is how much they have in transportation charges.

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:43.160
[Guest]: I mean, because nobody's flying, you can't be spending a whole lot of money on transport

00:36:43.160 --> 00:36:44.160
[Guest]: at this point.

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:47.260
[Guest]: So it was, of course, in line with what I thought.

00:36:47.260 --> 00:36:51.700
[Guest]: But then I realized that when I was talking to you, I was like, why would I look at that?

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:56.120
[Guest]: It's not because Deepak Sinha knows that this is a problem, it's just that somewhere the

00:36:56.120 --> 00:37:00.320
[Guest]: mental models come in together and said, since COVID, you've got these issues.

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:03.040
[Guest]: Companies reveal this information on a quarterly basis.

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:07.920
[Guest]: This is one quarter where you might have seen the emergence of some travel recur.

00:37:07.920 --> 00:37:11.560
[Guest]: And yet you've, so you go in with that thought process.

00:37:11.560 --> 00:37:15.240
[Guest]: But if you ask a different person, you might not look at that number.

00:37:15.240 --> 00:37:17.480
[Guest]: You might look at a completely different number.

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:22.120
[Guest]: But it's just the way that these conditions, conditionings have happened.

00:37:22.120 --> 00:37:27.280
[Guest]: I think they've happened mostly because, you know, there's this Finding Nemo line I love

00:37:27.280 --> 00:37:28.280
[Guest]: to write about.

00:37:28.280 --> 00:37:29.280
[Guest]: I like it.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:30.600
[Guest]: I think I've done it multiple times.

00:37:30.600 --> 00:37:34.480
[Guest]: And Finding Nemo, apologies to everybody, I'm going to quote cartoon lines because I

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:39.480
[Guest]: have two kids and I have watched every cartoon that has ever not lived.

00:37:39.480 --> 00:37:49.600
[Guest]: But one of the lines in Finding Nemo is when this Dory and this Nemo's dad, Marlon.

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:54.800
[Guest]: So they're together and Marlon is really distraught because he can't seem to find his son.

00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:56.360
[Guest]: And Dory's like, what happened?

00:37:56.360 --> 00:38:01.680
[Guest]: It's like, you know, I told his mother, Nemo's mother, that I wouldn't let anything happen

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:02.680
[Guest]: to him.

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:07.840
[Guest]: So she's like, Dory's like, that's strange.

00:38:07.840 --> 00:38:15.080
[Guest]: If you don't let anything happen to him, then nothing will ever happen to him.

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:19.200
[Guest]: So I think all of us live in those protective cocoons of ourselves, not just our kids, but

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:20.200
[Guest]: ourselves.

00:38:20.200 --> 00:38:25.280
[Guest]: Saying, if I make mistakes, I'll screw up, I'll look bad, whatever it is.

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:28.880
[Guest]: But if you don't make mistakes, how do you eventually not make mistakes?

00:38:28.880 --> 00:38:34.560
[Guest]: You have to go out there and experiment and try these things.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:37.920
[Guest]: You don't know what will happen and yeah, you might be wrong.

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:42.440
[Guest]: And sometimes in stock markets, you actually pay a price.

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:44.360
[Guest]: In most other places, you don't.

00:38:44.360 --> 00:38:48.120
[Guest]: If you're not good at cooking, at best you'll ruin a meal and you'll call Swiggy, which

00:38:48.120 --> 00:38:51.240
[Guest]: is by the way, a new thing, earlier you had to cook again.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:58.600
[Guest]: But if you don't do that, nobody will trust that you know cooking.

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:04.160
[Guest]: I could read 500 cookbooks, but I'm still not going to be able to cook well if I haven't

00:39:04.160 --> 00:39:06.240
[Guest]: cooked and made a mess of myself before.

00:39:06.240 --> 00:39:10.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, this goes back to our earlier point of sort of endless iterations.

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:15.800
[Amit Varma]: Like I remember in my poker playing days, somebody once asked a question that, you know,

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:19.080
[Amit Varma]: what does it tell you about a player if his bluffs never get called?

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:22.400
[Amit Varma]: And the answer obviously is that he isn't bluffing enough.

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:24.680
[Amit Varma]: Because there are an optimal number of bluffs you have to make.

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:28.240
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, I would say that if you're someone who never makes mistakes, then you're

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:32.280
[Amit Varma]: not living life as it should, you're just way too safe to become good at anything.

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:34.440
[Amit Varma]: You have to make lots of mistakes at date.

00:39:34.440 --> 00:39:38.320
[Amit Varma]: And I was, you know, struck by sort of, you know, you spoke about making bad jokes.

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:42.080
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that is one of those things where repeated iterations don't really make one

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:44.200
[Amit Varma]: better, because I have the same problem.

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:47.480
[Amit Varma]: And I was just thinking, you know, the moment you said Fortran, I thought if I go to Gurgaon

00:39:47.480 --> 00:39:52.720
[Amit Varma]: and tell somebody that, hey, I have learned Fortran, he will say, I have learned Fivetran.

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:58.240
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, let us not iterate too much on this, we are not kind of going to get better.

00:39:58.240 --> 00:40:01.880
[Amit Varma]: And the most delightful thing about your answer, though, was the connection between Curd and

00:40:01.880 --> 00:40:07.120
[Amit Varma]: Fourier transforms, which, again, is possibly unique to you, no one else would use those

00:40:07.120 --> 00:40:09.840
[Amit Varma]: two in the same sort of sentence.

00:40:09.840 --> 00:40:14.080
[Amit Varma]: So you know, is it then fair to say from all of this that, and I don't know which way the

00:40:14.080 --> 00:40:18.840
[Amit Varma]: causation goes, is it fair to say that computer programming, learning computer programming,

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:24.720
[Amit Varma]: gives you sort of a systematic way of, you know, looking at, you know, how things function

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:26.280
[Amit Varma]: and therefore how the world functions.

00:40:26.280 --> 00:40:30.520
[Amit Varma]: And you can, you know, transplant that systematic way of thinking on to other things.

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:33.640
[Amit Varma]: Or, of course, the causation could be the other way around, and it might be the case

00:40:33.640 --> 00:40:38.320
[Amit Varma]: that people who become good at computer programming are possibly those who are drawn to that kind

00:40:38.320 --> 00:40:40.720
[Amit Varma]: of systematic thinking to begin with.

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Either ways, I mean, they can, one can reinforce the other.

00:40:43.880 --> 00:40:46.840
[Amit Varma]: But is there kind of a sort of a link between that?

00:40:46.840 --> 00:40:50.760
[Amit Varma]: Like when you talk about mental model, the one key point that you made was that if you're

00:40:50.760 --> 00:40:54.040
[Amit Varma]: interested in something, you kind of go down a rabbit hole, which is pretty much what I

00:40:54.040 --> 00:40:55.040
[Amit Varma]: do.

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:58.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, I can watch a random YouTube video and then watch all 400 videos in that channel

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:03.600
[Amit Varma]: by before the night is over, partly aided by the fact that I watch at double speed.

00:41:03.600 --> 00:41:06.560
[Amit Varma]: But is that kind of part of the process?

00:41:06.560 --> 00:41:10.920
[Amit Varma]: And also, I would imagine that, you know, learning accounting, for example, which I

00:41:10.920 --> 00:41:15.440
[Amit Varma]: imagine was sort of the bridge between computer software to actually getting into investing

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:18.520
[Amit Varma]: in all of that, because first you build this accounting software and you have to figure

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:19.520
[Amit Varma]: it out.

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:21.160
[Amit Varma]: And it must be really boring.

00:41:21.160 --> 00:41:25.760
[Amit Varma]: At what point does it begin to get interesting for you, where you say that, fuck, this is

00:41:25.760 --> 00:41:28.360
[Amit Varma]: fascinating, I need to learn more about this.

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:31.400
[Amit Varma]: And then how does that process of learning happen?

00:41:31.400 --> 00:41:35.160
[Amit Varma]: Like I know very little about investing, I know that there is, you know, Benjamin Graham's

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:39.680
[Amit Varma]: value investing school with, you know, which Warren Buffet follows, and there are the quants

00:41:39.680 --> 00:41:40.760
[Amit Varma]: who will do their things.

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:44.680
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, and today, of course, is machine learning and AI and algorithmic

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:45.880
[Amit Varma]: trading and all of that.

00:41:45.880 --> 00:41:48.440
[Amit Varma]: So at what point does it begin to fascinate you?

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:50.400
[Amit Varma]: Why does it begin to fascinate you?

00:41:50.400 --> 00:41:56.480
[Amit Varma]: And then how do you sort of teach yourself or learn that subject?

00:41:56.480 --> 00:42:03.280
[Guest]: I think, you know, this is actually, I think it's many iterations of what has happened.

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:06.120
[Guest]: And I'll come to the latest ones.

00:42:06.120 --> 00:42:11.560
[Guest]: You know, again, it's sometimes what helps me is to think of, again, another cartoon

00:42:11.560 --> 00:42:18.440
[Guest]: is Ratatouille is a movie, and this guy who says anyone can cook.

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:24.160
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that everyone can cook, it means that, you know, some the best cook can

00:42:24.160 --> 00:42:26.040
[Guest]: come out of, you know.

00:42:26.040 --> 00:42:30.200
[Guest]: So sometimes my biggest problems in life is this call to authority.

00:42:30.200 --> 00:42:34.480
[Guest]: People tell me this, oh, you know what this guy has said, so therefore it is, but it's

00:42:34.480 --> 00:42:35.560
[Guest]: not so many times.

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:43.840
[Guest]: So because I'm by nature irreverent, when I say I'm a rebellious, I don't like to just

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:46.360
[Guest]: take statements at face value, because they're given to me.

00:42:46.360 --> 00:42:53.040
[Guest]: But also, the curiosity of something drives a lot of the thinking.

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:57.520
[Guest]: And while I think it's the computer programming thought process, perhaps it's the way that's

00:42:57.520 --> 00:42:58.520
[Guest]: evolved for me.

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:04.320
[Guest]: It's up for somebody else with that curiosity model, it might have evolved differently.

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:08.120
[Guest]: The difference is that if you are, for instance, somebody told me this in college, if you're

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:15.240
[Guest]: in a computer lab, and you make an error, you just press Ctrl F9 and you can do it again.

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:19.360
[Guest]: If I'm in a chemical lab, I'm not going to make too many errors, right?

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:23.800
[Guest]: So I have to plan and think and do, you know, I don't know, I'd blow up the whole lab if

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:26.800
[Guest]: I screw up.

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:30.880
[Guest]: And people in the mechanical world, in the civil world, you can't experiment with creating

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:35.680
[Guest]: a building, because, you know, it's got to be structurally solid, so you want to think

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:38.040
[Guest]: about it, plan it somewhere else and all that stuff.

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:45.360
[Guest]: So we get afforded a little more on the mistake platform than people in other industries or

00:43:45.360 --> 00:43:48.240
[Guest]: engineering courses are.

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:51.400
[Guest]: And then in the humanities, there's no concept called an error, everything is an opinion

00:43:51.400 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest]: at some level.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest]: So it's nice.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:58.920
[Guest]: I wish I'd done that, because you'd have appreciated life is as an engineer sucks, because you'd

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:00.680
[Guest]: want rationality in everything.

00:44:00.680 --> 00:44:05.560
[Guest]: And then it takes your whole life to figure out that irrationality is the only thing that

00:44:05.560 --> 00:44:06.960
[Guest]: survives.

00:44:06.960 --> 00:44:13.040
[Guest]: Because you have today I mean, you know, the old adage was that there were two squirrels

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:18.040
[Guest]: and one of them stored its nuts for the winter and the other one just was having fun and

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:24.320
[Guest]: now, you know, how when winter came, the one nut, you know, starved to death and the other

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:27.400
[Guest]: one was okay, and that was supposed to be a moral lesson.

00:44:27.400 --> 00:44:31.560
[Guest]: And now they give you the same thing with a different two captions where the second

00:44:31.560 --> 00:44:37.040
[Guest]: one starving and then there's the whole list of, you know, people who are protesting saying,

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:41.960
[Guest]: how can one guy have all the nuts when the other fellow is starving and then therefore

00:44:41.960 --> 00:44:45.000
[Guest]: they take the nuts away from the first guy and then give it to the second guy and the

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:49.160
[Guest]: third guy like, look, why do you have to spend all that energy doing all those nuts saving

00:44:49.160 --> 00:44:50.960
[Guest]: when we could have had fun.

00:44:50.960 --> 00:44:57.960
[Guest]: But interestingly, those models are so I think I must have lost myself in this whole thing.

00:44:57.960 --> 00:45:02.440
[Guest]: But for me, the mental model started working saying, things have to be rational, things

00:45:02.440 --> 00:45:04.380
[Guest]: have to come one after the other.

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:06.760
[Guest]: And then you slowly build up on that.

00:45:06.760 --> 00:45:08.280
[Guest]: And even now, I think that's what happens.

00:45:08.280 --> 00:45:14.560
[Guest]: So for instance, that my latest, somewhere in the middle, and, you know, my wife remembers

00:45:14.560 --> 00:45:20.680
[Guest]: this because I was obsessed with it for like, I think, four weeks, I had to find out about

00:45:20.680 --> 00:45:21.680
[Guest]: nuclear power.

00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:24.000
[Guest]: Don't ask me why.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.960
[Guest]: And I didn't know anything about it.

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:33.720
[Guest]: So I had to find out how nuclear reactors were made, specifically because I was like,

00:45:33.720 --> 00:45:36.320
[Guest]: I'm curious about this whole subject and I want to find out.

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:42.400
[Guest]: So I spent like days and days looking into nuclear power and reactors and what specifically

00:45:42.400 --> 00:45:46.520
[Guest]: thorium played as a part in that process.

00:45:46.520 --> 00:45:53.480
[Guest]: So in the end, I was left with a lot of information, almost completely useless.

00:45:53.480 --> 00:45:55.400
[Guest]: I hope it will be useful at some point in the future.

00:45:55.400 --> 00:46:01.000
[Guest]: But I mean, it's just like I wanted to get a feel of the subject, I understood what the

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:06.960
[Guest]: thorium cycle was the fact that India was at that time, the forefront of thorium based

00:46:06.960 --> 00:46:13.720
[Guest]: nuclear technology, perhaps is one of the furthest down that line, even today, India

00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:18.400
[Guest]: has the second largest reserves of thorium in the world, we could produce we have had

00:46:18.400 --> 00:46:27.480
[Guest]: a functioning reactor for the last 25 years, 25, yeah, this year, it will be 25 in Bombay,

00:46:27.480 --> 00:46:34.280
[Guest]: which is an experimental reactor that can actually produce its own fuel as a byproduct

00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:35.280
[Guest]: of this process.

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:41.880
[Guest]: One of the first and earliest, you know, users of this technology, and it uses thorium as

00:46:41.880 --> 00:46:42.880
[Guest]: one of the fuels.

00:46:42.880 --> 00:46:46.600
[Guest]: And the other thing that it actually produces uranium, which is so rare in the world.

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:49.920
[Guest]: So why this actually happened, I don't know.

00:46:49.920 --> 00:46:54.200
[Guest]: But somewhere down this process, I said, okay, there's got to be a reason why people think

00:46:54.200 --> 00:46:57.520
[Guest]: this is bad nuclear stuff.

00:46:57.520 --> 00:46:59.440
[Guest]: And eventually I found, okay, nuclear is not bad.

00:46:59.440 --> 00:47:03.640
[Guest]: I mean, I know people may disagree and say, okay, no, no, it's not environmentally friendly.

00:47:03.640 --> 00:47:10.200
[Guest]: But in the scale of environment friendliness as a whole, the nuclear power generation process

00:47:10.200 --> 00:47:19.240
[Guest]: is the most environmentally friendly in less people have died in all of the nuclear accidents

00:47:19.240 --> 00:47:25.880
[Guest]: all over the world, even considering effects downstream and so on, than in probably any

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:29.840
[Guest]: other form of power generation in the world.

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:35.200
[Guest]: And I don't say this because, you know, I'm just quoting a magazine or anything like that.

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:40.360
[Guest]: But because I've gone through the data, I've combed through it and seen how this stuff

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:41.360
[Guest]: functions.

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:45.120
[Guest]: And even though we have movies like Chernobyl, which comes along and talks about a lot of

00:47:45.120 --> 00:47:49.840
[Guest]: things and how nuclear holocausts and all that stuff happen, I don't, I mean, I think

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:52.440
[Guest]: now, I mean, I'm comfortable in understanding that.

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:56.840
[Guest]: The reason why I'm saying this is because the mental model that caused me to go down

00:47:56.840 --> 00:48:01.880
[Guest]: this hole was because perhaps somewhere someone had commented that this stuff is unsafe.

00:48:01.880 --> 00:48:05.160
[Guest]: In order to find out for myself, it got fascinating.

00:48:05.160 --> 00:48:09.400
[Guest]: And why it got fascinating was something in the middle that triggered and said, oh, shit,

00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:10.680
[Guest]: wait, wait, what about that?

00:48:10.680 --> 00:48:14.560
[Guest]: And one of the factors that did that for me was that India had the second largest thorium

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:15.560
[Guest]: reserves in the world.

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:19.640
[Guest]: I'm like, but we don't have that many nuclear reactors, do we?

00:48:19.640 --> 00:48:25.400
[Guest]: And then it turns out we do have a fair number, but nowhere close to what is eventually required.

00:48:25.400 --> 00:48:30.040
[Guest]: And thorium has, thorium is on the beaches of Kerala.

00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:32.680
[Guest]: Fascinating fact, but it's strewn around.

00:48:32.680 --> 00:48:35.240
[Guest]: It's one of the largest things out there.

00:48:35.240 --> 00:48:37.120
[Guest]: It's probably lesser now than it used to be then.

00:48:37.120 --> 00:48:46.000
[Guest]: But so when you think about how your philosophy evolves over time, I've learned that you can

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.760
[Guest]: somehow latch on to philosophies or mental models, even when you're doing the stranger

00:48:49.760 --> 00:48:52.400
[Guest]: things, playing solitaire.

00:48:52.400 --> 00:48:53.920
[Guest]: You could play solitaire.

00:48:53.920 --> 00:48:54.920
[Guest]: You could lose.

00:48:54.920 --> 00:48:57.080
[Guest]: You could come back and win again.

00:48:57.080 --> 00:48:58.280
[Guest]: And you've seen this in poker.

00:48:58.280 --> 00:49:04.280
[Guest]: You can either keep playing poker endlessly without learning, and a lot of people do that.

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:06.480
[Guest]: And you could do this with bridge as well.

00:49:06.480 --> 00:49:10.160
[Guest]: And you could play contract bridge forever and not learn.

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:14.400
[Guest]: Or you could go down a little bit further and said, dude, this is a game of probabilities.

00:49:14.400 --> 00:49:19.240
[Guest]: You're going to play the probability game, but you have to understand how the probabilities

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:20.240
[Guest]: work.

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:21.680
[Guest]: You have to figure out how they're arranged.

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:26.480
[Guest]: And if you know how they're arranged, you instantly start to make mental models about

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:27.480
[Guest]: poker or bridge.

00:49:27.480 --> 00:49:31.040
[Guest]: In bridge, for instance, if the bidding happens in a certain way, you get a certain clue on

00:49:31.040 --> 00:49:32.040
[Guest]: the lie of the table.

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:35.760
[Guest]: And then you start making immediate eliminations in your mind.

00:49:35.760 --> 00:49:37.240
[Guest]: I am not a very good chess player.

00:49:37.240 --> 00:49:39.080
[Guest]: I'm probably a terrible chess player.

00:49:39.080 --> 00:49:44.320
[Guest]: But in chess, you do this like probably 100 times more than you do in bridge.

00:49:44.320 --> 00:49:49.000
[Guest]: But you eliminate possibilities more than you include them.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:55.440
[Guest]: And over time, what you're doing when you're playing is that you're finding a better way

00:49:55.440 --> 00:50:00.240
[Guest]: to do the same thing that you were doing, brute force methods.

00:50:00.240 --> 00:50:06.000
[Guest]: So somebody tells you that in blackjack you count, and there's a reason you count.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:09.520
[Guest]: But if you played blackjack enough, even if you didn't read the books and read the literature

00:50:09.520 --> 00:50:16.360
[Guest]: around it, you know that if there have been enough face cards that have already come,

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:22.160
[Guest]: after some time you learn this, that you don't want to bet anymore.

00:50:22.160 --> 00:50:26.880
[Guest]: If the more number of face cards have come in, your chances of getting a face card, of

00:50:26.880 --> 00:50:32.920
[Guest]: the dealer getting hit and going out later, reduces somewhat.

00:50:32.920 --> 00:50:39.680
[Guest]: So this kind of mental modeling comes to you after some time, and it's just sometimes that

00:50:39.680 --> 00:50:42.160
[Guest]: it clicks, and sometimes it doesn't.

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:43.880
[Guest]: So for me, it has never clicked in Sudoku.

00:50:43.880 --> 00:50:50.960
[Guest]: I have been playing it for a long time, and I somehow have never found it useful enough

00:50:50.960 --> 00:50:59.480
[Guest]: to go down and try and figure out how I could play this a lot better than I do right now.

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:05.520
[Guest]: But I've done this with, say, a bridge or some of the other games that I play.

00:51:05.520 --> 00:51:08.720
[Guest]: But what I think is fascinating is that it's about interest.

00:51:08.720 --> 00:51:13.520
[Guest]: If I was not interested in accounting, and I don't know how I got interested in accounting,

00:51:13.520 --> 00:51:17.760
[Guest]: it was a pleasure in finding out the interesting things about it.

00:51:17.760 --> 00:51:21.520
[Guest]: So even today, I look at accounts, and I marvel at some things.

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:26.640
[Guest]: Like for instance, they say that the three things that you can never figure out is death,

00:51:26.640 --> 00:51:30.160
[Guest]: taxes, and how Reliance makes profits.

00:51:30.160 --> 00:51:39.000
[Guest]: But how Reliance makes profits is a book by itself, because for every era, there's a nice

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.240
[Guest]: little accounting technique that they use.

00:51:41.240 --> 00:51:46.080
[Guest]: And it's very nerdy accounting stuff, but you're like, dude, I like this, man.

00:51:46.080 --> 00:51:47.560
[Guest]: This is cool.

00:51:47.560 --> 00:51:55.880
[Guest]: So it's fascinating to get that aha when you find out that they've removed all the chinks

00:51:55.880 --> 00:52:00.160
[Guest]: in what would otherwise be like, why is anybody doing this?

00:52:00.160 --> 00:52:02.280
[Guest]: And now it's like, oh, yeah, this is why they're doing it.

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:05.920
[Guest]: So fascinating because of that, perhaps.

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, there's a lot to unpack here.

00:52:08.400 --> 00:52:11.880
[Amit Varma]: But firstly, I'll say that I'm delighted that you brought up that nuclear digression because

00:52:11.880 --> 00:52:16.080
[Amit Varma]: something that I have been planning to write about, or maybe find an expert and do an episode

00:52:16.080 --> 00:52:21.560
[Amit Varma]: about is that, you know, nuclear power could literally be the solution to climate change,

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:25.640
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that it is so incredibly safe, obviously, I don't have your level of knowledge

00:52:25.640 --> 00:52:30.120
[Amit Varma]: about thorium deposits in India, which is a kind of geeky thing I'd expect you to know.

00:52:30.120 --> 00:52:33.680
[Amit Varma]: But you know, I did do a lot of reading on this at one point in time.

00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:39.080
[Amit Varma]: And it is, you know, all the data comprehensively shows that it is by far the safest form of

00:52:39.080 --> 00:52:43.200
[Amit Varma]: energy 10s of 1000s of people die every year from fossil fuels.

00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:47.880
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of them are unseen deaths, which we, you know, don't necessarily directly attribute.

00:52:47.880 --> 00:52:50.560
[Amit Varma]: But people will bring up this bogey of Chernobyl or whatever.

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:54.840
[Amit Varma]: And the thing with Chernobyl is that look, that was not something that you know, necessarily

00:52:54.840 --> 00:52:56.680
[Amit Varma]: was a failure of nuclear power.

00:52:56.680 --> 00:53:01.960
[Amit Varma]: It was a failure of a certain system of governance, which was really the Soviet system.

00:53:01.960 --> 00:53:03.480
[Amit Varma]: And that's how you should see it.

00:53:03.480 --> 00:53:08.480
[Amit Varma]: And while the web series is fabulous, I'd recommend a book by Adam Higginbotham on Chernobyl,

00:53:08.480 --> 00:53:12.360
[Amit Varma]: which I linked from the show notes, which is a wonderful, wonderful book on that subject.

00:53:12.360 --> 00:53:15.560
[Amit Varma]: I also sort of loved your answer on mental models, because you know, you brought up all

00:53:15.560 --> 00:53:20.560
[Amit Varma]: these different sports, and I'll kind of mention them briefly, because it seems that the one

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:26.120
[Amit Varma]: way in which my years as a poker player changed my thinking or sharpened my thinking was that

00:53:26.120 --> 00:53:28.980
[Amit Varma]: it made me think about the world in a probabilistic way.

00:53:28.980 --> 00:53:34.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, not look and not connect results to outcomes all the time, not be results oriented,

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:37.960
[Amit Varma]: focus more on process and doing the right thing and realize that the role of luck in

00:53:37.960 --> 00:53:40.280
[Amit Varma]: our lives is, you know, much greater.

00:53:40.280 --> 00:53:45.320
[Amit Varma]: And that is, of course, that kind of probabilistic thinking is a framework that applies to everything,

00:53:45.320 --> 00:53:46.320
[Amit Varma]: including investing.

00:53:46.320 --> 00:53:50.480
[Amit Varma]: I did an episode with Mohit Satyananda, mutual friend, who's also an amazing investor, where

00:53:50.480 --> 00:53:55.600
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about the similarities between investing and poker in terms of the kind of different

00:53:55.600 --> 00:53:57.760
[Amit Varma]: mental models that go in.

00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:01.240
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, you sort of mentioned chess.

00:54:01.240 --> 00:54:05.480
[Amit Varma]: Now that's also relevant, because what you do as a chess player is that there was a study

00:54:05.480 --> 00:54:10.160
[Amit Varma]: we showed, which compared top chess players with beginning chess players, and tried to

00:54:10.160 --> 00:54:12.520
[Amit Varma]: figure out how many moves ahead do they see.

00:54:12.520 --> 00:54:15.600
[Amit Varma]: And the beginning chess players see as many moves ahead as the best grandmaster in the

00:54:15.600 --> 00:54:16.600
[Amit Varma]: world.

00:54:16.600 --> 00:54:18.520
[Amit Varma]: But the top player will see the right moves.

00:54:18.520 --> 00:54:20.860
[Amit Varma]: And that is because of pattern recognition.

00:54:20.860 --> 00:54:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Because they are not going by, I will do this, he will do that, and then this will happen,

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:26.000
[Amit Varma]: and then this will happen.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:27.000
[Amit Varma]: That's not how they are thinking.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:30.920
[Amit Varma]: They are looking at certain patterns of how the pieces are placed on the board.

00:54:30.920 --> 00:54:34.520
[Amit Varma]: And from that, they know certain patterns of how things move.

00:54:34.520 --> 00:54:38.920
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you become better at chess by just by recognizing more and more patterns

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:39.920
[Amit Varma]: and using them.

00:54:39.920 --> 00:54:45.080
[Amit Varma]: So you're thinking at a higher level, which might be a reason, by the way, that, you know,

00:54:45.080 --> 00:54:46.840
[Amit Varma]: Sudoku is frustrating to you.

00:54:46.840 --> 00:54:49.360
[Amit Varma]: Because in Sudoku, there are no higher patterns.

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Everything is move by move, everything is concrete.

00:54:51.560 --> 00:54:54.840
[Amit Varma]: You're figuring out, okay, there is no such number in this line, there is no such number

00:54:54.840 --> 00:54:59.280
[Amit Varma]: in here, therefore, there are no higher patterns to see, I'm just kind of speculating and thinking

00:54:59.280 --> 00:55:00.280
[Amit Varma]: aloud.

00:55:00.280 --> 00:55:03.840
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, I'm now hooked on to this new form of chess on chess.com called fog

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:05.800
[Amit Varma]: of war, which is beautiful.

00:55:05.800 --> 00:55:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And what fog of war is that, you know, if anyone has played chess, they should really

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:11.000
[Amit Varma]: try it out.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.800
[Amit Varma]: Is that you can only see your own pieces at the beginning of the game, you can't see your

00:55:13.800 --> 00:55:15.160
[Amit Varma]: opponent's pieces.

00:55:15.160 --> 00:55:20.780
[Amit Varma]: And as you play, you can only see those parts of the board, which your pieces can attack.

00:55:20.780 --> 00:55:24.080
[Amit Varma]: So if you put your bishop on a long diagonal, you can see everything on that diagonal till

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:26.760
[Amit Varma]: the point, you know, it's blocked by something.

00:55:26.760 --> 00:55:30.520
[Amit Varma]: So it is, you know, the difference between chess and poker is that chess is a game of

00:55:30.520 --> 00:55:34.200
[Amit Varma]: perfect information, while poker obviously is imperfect information.

00:55:34.200 --> 00:55:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And this brings that element of imperfect information into chess, where you're not just

00:55:38.880 --> 00:55:42.640
[Amit Varma]: trying to kind of, you know, all the information isn't out there.

00:55:42.640 --> 00:55:47.340
[Amit Varma]: So part of your task is to figure out how do I get more information?

00:55:47.340 --> 00:55:50.880
[Amit Varma]: And how do I protect, you know, information from getting out?

00:55:50.880 --> 00:55:55.520
[Amit Varma]: So it's really, it's like a fascinating mix, and I've kind of gone down that rabbit hole

00:55:55.520 --> 00:55:59.240
[Amit Varma]: in recent days, I'm probably one of the highest ranked players on chess.com right now in that

00:55:59.240 --> 00:56:00.240
[Amit Varma]: form of the game.

00:56:00.240 --> 00:56:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Though that is obviously not the case in any other form, because I play all other forms

00:56:04.440 --> 00:56:08.720
[Amit Varma]: for time pass, I do not try to improve, I do not want to improve, like what poker players

00:56:08.720 --> 00:56:10.200
[Amit Varma]: would call a fish.

00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:11.480
[Amit Varma]: But that's what I try to do here.

00:56:11.480 --> 00:56:15.480
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that's part of it that if you, you form these mental models doing various

00:56:15.480 --> 00:56:17.680
[Amit Varma]: things, and then you can apply them to everything.

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:20.800
[Amit Varma]: And pattern seeking is not something that you do only in chess.

00:56:20.800 --> 00:56:26.440
[Amit Varma]: We are pattern seeking creatures, we are sort of evolved to do that, which is why we kind

00:56:26.440 --> 00:56:29.640
[Amit Varma]: of look for patterns in everything that I do.

00:56:29.640 --> 00:56:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, my next question about sort of investing in markets is this.

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:40.080
[Amit Varma]: And this is possibly a prescriptive question, how should we think about markets?

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:43.720
[Amit Varma]: Because from an outsider, someone who doesn't invest, someone who hasn't thought about it

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:49.360
[Amit Varma]: at a higher philosophical level, markets can be either, you know, at the very basic level

00:56:49.360 --> 00:56:52.680
[Amit Varma]: that you're buying into a company, and they're using your money and doing something with

00:56:52.680 --> 00:56:53.680
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:56:53.680 --> 00:56:54.680
[Amit Varma]: And that's a system.

00:56:54.680 --> 00:56:58.280
[Amit Varma]: Or it can be like this grand casino, which is completely disconnected from the real world,

00:56:58.280 --> 00:57:02.320
[Amit Varma]: kuch connection hi nahi hai, economy is going down, markets are going up, which of course,

00:57:02.320 --> 00:57:06.120
[Amit Varma]: you wrote about in this wonderful column in June, which I'll, again, link from the show

00:57:06.120 --> 00:57:11.640
[Amit Varma]: notes and possibly quote from, but people have these very simplistic conceptions of

00:57:11.640 --> 00:57:12.640
[Amit Varma]: markets.

00:57:12.640 --> 00:57:16.000
[Amit Varma]: So, and I presume at some point, obviously, you begin with these simplistic notions as

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:19.840
[Amit Varma]: well, and then you begin to find out more about it.

00:57:19.840 --> 00:57:22.280
[Amit Varma]: So how should we think of markets?

00:57:22.280 --> 00:57:24.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, why should we invest in markets?

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:29.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, how has your thinking kind of how did your thinking rather evolve on the subject?

00:57:29.360 --> 00:57:34.880
[Guest]: You know, the problem with markets is that there's always more than one right answer

00:57:34.880 --> 00:57:36.760
[Guest]: to almost everything.

00:57:36.760 --> 00:57:42.040
[Guest]: And this is something that a lot of people find extremely uncomfortable.

00:57:42.040 --> 00:57:47.880
[Guest]: They may be accounting fraud, or snafus that are happening, and yet it may still be a great

00:57:47.880 --> 00:57:49.560
[Guest]: company to invest in.

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:54.160
[Guest]: And so this is the one of the things that people always find fascinating.

00:57:54.160 --> 00:57:56.000
[Guest]: But there's a lot of stuff like that.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:00.640
[Guest]: So let me start off with the basic simple assumption.

00:58:00.640 --> 00:58:05.160
[Guest]: And perhaps I should, I should paraphrase this with saying this is not advice.

00:58:05.160 --> 00:58:11.240
[Guest]: This is, you know, this is just storytelling more than anything else.

00:58:11.240 --> 00:58:17.560
[Guest]: So if you think about the most simple advice, pieces of advice that people can give you,

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:22.600
[Guest]: it's just, you know, keep investing and you'll make money.

00:58:22.600 --> 00:58:24.280
[Guest]: That's as simple as it sounds, right?

00:58:24.280 --> 00:58:31.600
[Guest]: And if you just took that one piece of advice, and nothing else, I think, you know, you do

00:58:31.600 --> 00:58:33.880
[Guest]: really well in life.

00:58:33.880 --> 00:58:38.820
[Guest]: Because with the hows and the whys and all that stuff can come later.

00:58:38.820 --> 00:58:40.640
[Guest]: But this is a really simple piece of advice.

00:58:40.640 --> 00:58:44.360
[Guest]: Now things start to get complicated, because you're going to ask me where are you going

00:58:44.360 --> 00:58:45.360
[Guest]: to invest?

00:58:45.360 --> 00:58:48.800
[Guest]: So I can tell you, oh, well, you can invest in these stocks, these mutual funds, and you

00:58:48.800 --> 00:58:52.560
[Guest]: know, out of every 10 people, you'll find one or two people who said, dude, I invested

00:58:52.560 --> 00:58:53.560
[Guest]: in that shit.

00:58:53.560 --> 00:58:55.800
[Guest]: And then it was really good for a while.

00:58:55.800 --> 00:59:01.400
[Guest]: And then all those stocks went to shit, and I lost all my money, and then I'm done.

00:59:01.400 --> 00:59:03.340
[Guest]: Okay, that sounds like it.

00:59:03.340 --> 00:59:06.800
[Guest]: But that one person is going to influence 10 or 15 other people to say don't invest

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:08.440
[Guest]: in markets, because this is what it is.

00:59:08.440 --> 00:59:10.680
[Guest]: And now the confusion starts to creep in.

00:59:10.680 --> 00:59:12.760
[Guest]: Now, how do I start off the same way?

00:59:12.760 --> 00:59:17.200
[Guest]: I didn't have any money, to be fair, I'll tell you my first experience with stocks.

00:59:17.200 --> 00:59:21.000
[Guest]: And I had seen my father make money out of stocks.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:25.680
[Guest]: He bought Hero Motocorp, Hero Honda at the time, when it was in its IPO, he never sold

00:59:25.680 --> 00:59:26.680
[Guest]: it.

00:59:26.680 --> 00:59:30.560
[Guest]: He never sold it for one reason, because he pledged it to take a loan to build his house.

00:59:30.560 --> 00:59:31.920
[Guest]: So he couldn't sell it.

00:59:31.920 --> 00:59:39.800
[Guest]: So he took that, those shares are worth, I don't know, 4000 times what they were at the

00:59:39.800 --> 00:59:41.640
[Guest]: IPO today.

00:59:41.640 --> 00:59:46.720
[Guest]: But the interesting thing about the thing was, although I'd seen this money being made

00:59:46.720 --> 00:59:54.000
[Guest]: in stocks, I was like, God, so I, in 2000, February, after looking at stock markets going

00:59:54.000 --> 01:00:00.400
[Guest]: up every single day, I decided to venture into markets myself and I stood in line that

01:00:00.400 --> 01:00:05.120
[Guest]: time you had to fill paper forms, go in line, so you stood in line and went and invested

01:00:05.120 --> 01:00:11.360
[Guest]: in ICICI Prudential Mutual Fund, Technology Fund, something like that.

01:00:11.360 --> 01:00:15.360
[Guest]: And it was a 10 rupees and promptly in three months, it was a 2 rupees.

01:00:15.360 --> 01:00:19.120
[Guest]: And I said, this is the only money I had ever saved.

01:00:19.120 --> 01:00:21.480
[Guest]: I'm running my own business, so all my money is there.

01:00:21.480 --> 01:00:25.960
[Guest]: I had 10,000 rupees and I put it into this and it became 2000 rupees and I swore off

01:00:25.960 --> 01:00:31.360
[Guest]: markets saying, I don't know how anybody has ever made money off this thing, but once you

01:00:31.360 --> 01:00:34.160
[Guest]: go into this accounting thing, I suddenly realized there's a pattern.

01:00:34.160 --> 01:00:35.640
[Guest]: There's a way to make money.

01:00:35.640 --> 01:00:39.760
[Guest]: And if you think about it in a very basic way, and maybe this realization took me years

01:00:39.760 --> 01:00:42.800
[Guest]: to get, but I'm just going to go back in here.

01:00:42.800 --> 01:00:49.200
[Guest]: You're making money off the fact that someone else is making money.

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:51.160
[Guest]: You're not going to make money by yourself.

01:00:51.160 --> 01:00:56.800
[Guest]: And since I'm not selling the pipes, I'm buying the company's shares, then that company sells

01:00:56.800 --> 01:00:57.800
[Guest]: pipes.

01:00:57.800 --> 01:01:01.080
[Guest]: The guy who's selling the pipes knows how to sell pipes.

01:01:01.080 --> 01:01:03.160
[Guest]: I don't know how to figure that out.

01:01:03.160 --> 01:01:07.920
[Guest]: All I need to know is that he's selling pipes and he can continue to sell pipes in the future.

01:01:07.920 --> 01:01:12.400
[Guest]: And I think pipes is a great market, so that's all I need to care about.

01:01:12.400 --> 01:01:23.640
[Guest]: You think of the markets as in poker or in a game where you're playing in a casino.

01:01:23.640 --> 01:01:29.200
[Guest]: The odds are always a little bit against, a little bit.

01:01:29.200 --> 01:01:30.200
[Guest]: In poker, it's not.

01:01:30.200 --> 01:01:33.520
[Guest]: Of course, poker, when you're playing in a team, you're probably someone with the odds

01:01:33.520 --> 01:01:34.920
[Guest]: if you're smart.

01:01:34.920 --> 01:01:39.000
[Guest]: And when I say odds, I mean, you can try over and over again.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:47.200
[Guest]: And if you've got the right kind of process, if all you have is a slight edge, over time

01:01:47.200 --> 01:01:48.200
[Guest]: you will win.

01:01:48.200 --> 01:01:53.820
[Guest]: There are two reasons why, two things that are very important for this concept to work.

01:01:53.820 --> 01:01:58.460
[Guest]: One is that you need to be able to play many times.

01:01:58.460 --> 01:02:00.160
[Guest]: That means they shouldn't stop you.

01:02:00.160 --> 01:02:03.800
[Guest]: You can give your 12th standard exams only so many times, and that's it.

01:02:03.800 --> 01:02:07.340
[Guest]: You can't give it for more than those many times, so you have to win in that short timeframe.

01:02:07.340 --> 01:02:13.160
[Guest]: So you need a different approach to it, which is also why it's knowledge-based, rules-based.

01:02:13.160 --> 01:02:14.160
[Guest]: Life is not rules-based.

01:02:14.160 --> 01:02:17.560
[Guest]: Life is very random to a certain extent.

01:02:17.560 --> 01:02:25.100
[Guest]: And therefore, to win in investing, you have to be able to try many times.

01:02:25.100 --> 01:02:30.840
[Guest]: What happens to a lot of people is they get taken in by this Rakesh Jhunjhunwala bet some

01:02:30.840 --> 01:02:33.840
[Guest]: money on Titan, and that made him 800 crore.

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:34.840
[Guest]: Ek share nahi.

01:02:34.840 --> 01:02:38.480
[Guest]: Mereko bhi wo aisa ek share nikal ke do.

01:02:38.480 --> 01:02:40.600
[Guest]: To unlearn this took me 10 years.

01:02:40.600 --> 01:02:46.160
[Guest]: To unlearn the philosophy that said, boss, bet everything on one thing.

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:47.160
[Guest]: I've done this.

01:02:47.160 --> 01:02:48.160
[Guest]: I'm an entrepreneur.

01:02:48.160 --> 01:02:53.400
[Guest]: I've bet all my money on my company, and I've had four of them, you know, some different

01:02:53.400 --> 01:03:00.160
[Guest]: kinds of success, but I don't think this is great investing advice, that you bet a lot

01:03:00.160 --> 01:03:02.680
[Guest]: of money on a single thing.

01:03:02.680 --> 01:03:04.020
[Guest]: I don't think it works for me.

01:03:04.020 --> 01:03:09.080
[Guest]: And I've realized that over time, investing is about who you are.

01:03:09.080 --> 01:03:13.080
[Guest]: If you're this crazy, and you see this in poker a lot, people will come in and say,

01:03:13.080 --> 01:03:14.880
[Guest]: boss, iss hand mein toh banayega.

01:03:14.880 --> 01:03:15.880
[Guest]: Kuch bhi karega.

01:03:15.880 --> 01:03:17.200
[Guest]: Because that hand could be a throwaway hand.

01:03:17.200 --> 01:03:18.200
[Guest]: You had to go.

01:03:18.200 --> 01:03:19.480
[Guest]: You had to fold.

01:03:19.480 --> 01:03:21.640
[Guest]: The guy's going to play on it because of his ego.

01:03:21.640 --> 01:03:27.000
[Guest]: So people do this with shares, saying, Suzlon kharidega, and Suzlon mein hi paisa banayega.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:31.040
[Guest]: Even though he's lost 80% in Suzlon, he's putting more money into it, saying, average

01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:32.480
[Guest]: down, average down.

01:03:32.480 --> 01:03:39.400
[Guest]: Stock that falls 90% is a stock that first fell 80% and then fell by half.

01:03:39.400 --> 01:03:43.640
[Guest]: So if you are thinking it's 80% down, it has nowhere else to go but up.

01:03:43.640 --> 01:03:50.040
[Guest]: It's going to fall only another 10% in the overall scheme of things, but 50% for you.

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:55.280
[Guest]: So this is something that I think it takes time for one to learn.

01:03:55.280 --> 01:04:00.720
[Guest]: But what is fascinating is the building of why you invest or how you invest.

01:04:00.720 --> 01:04:07.400
[Guest]: For me, that learning came in over time, saying, OK, I look at accounts, I look at stock prices,

01:04:07.400 --> 01:04:08.600
[Guest]: and they don't make sense.

01:04:08.600 --> 01:04:12.840
[Guest]: There's a company that's growing at 10% and you're valuing it at some obscene number.

01:04:12.840 --> 01:04:16.320
[Guest]: OK, it doesn't make sense.

01:04:16.320 --> 01:04:21.440
[Guest]: Over time, you realize that this is a lot of luck, and luck plays a huge role because

01:04:21.440 --> 01:04:24.560
[Guest]: sometimes it's a crappy company.

01:04:24.560 --> 01:04:29.760
[Guest]: It gets its share price up to a point where it can raise capital at a very high valuation.

01:04:29.760 --> 01:04:34.560
[Guest]: It raises that capital at a very high valuation, and now because that capital is strengthened

01:04:34.560 --> 01:04:39.440
[Guest]: because of this capital raise, it suddenly becomes a good company.

01:04:39.440 --> 01:04:44.680
[Guest]: I mean, it's still overvalued, but it's a good company that can actually withstand a

01:04:44.680 --> 01:04:45.680
[Guest]: fall.

01:04:45.680 --> 01:04:49.840
[Guest]: So when there is a fall because it has this capital cushion, it's able to withstand it.

01:04:49.840 --> 01:04:55.840
[Guest]: Its competitors are not, which were relatively less priced but did not have the kind of capital

01:04:55.840 --> 01:04:57.160
[Guest]: buffers that this guy does.

01:04:57.160 --> 01:05:04.200
[Guest]: So it suddenly has those capital buffers, and the increase in stock price made a company

01:05:04.200 --> 01:05:06.680
[Guest]: that could ride out a really big downturn.

01:05:06.680 --> 01:05:10.160
[Guest]: So this concept never struck me.

01:05:10.160 --> 01:05:13.120
[Guest]: I mean, it still astounds me that that happens.

01:05:13.120 --> 01:05:17.360
[Guest]: And what you suddenly realize is that when a company starts to raise capital when it's

01:05:17.360 --> 01:05:22.360
[Guest]: extremely overvalued, it's actually a good company.

01:05:22.360 --> 01:05:28.040
[Guest]: And you need a company to do that, to make for a better thing.

01:05:28.040 --> 01:05:32.040
[Guest]: That's very esoteric from an original sphere of things, because you want to look at a company

01:05:32.040 --> 01:05:34.040
[Guest]: and say, oh, no debt is good.

01:05:34.040 --> 01:05:36.360
[Guest]: No debt companies are good.

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:38.840
[Guest]: In India, they tell you that a company should not have debt.

01:05:38.840 --> 01:05:42.440
[Guest]: Yes, there are a lot of no-debt companies, and lots of debt-based companies which are

01:05:42.440 --> 01:05:43.960
[Guest]: still good.

01:05:43.960 --> 01:05:49.360
[Guest]: And you realize that over time, that it's the judicious use of terms and terminologies

01:05:49.360 --> 01:05:51.040
[Guest]: and things that you learn.

01:05:51.040 --> 01:05:58.360
[Guest]: And so somebody told you this, probably, and it's underappreciated.

01:05:58.360 --> 01:06:00.280
[Guest]: Follow the rules.

01:06:00.280 --> 01:06:02.600
[Guest]: And second, figure out when to break the rules.

01:06:02.600 --> 01:06:07.680
[Guest]: It's the worst advice you can ever give someone new, because they would have no idea what

01:06:07.680 --> 01:06:09.040
[Guest]: that means.

01:06:09.040 --> 01:06:12.200
[Guest]: Because first, they have to figure out why those rules work, and then they have to figure

01:06:12.200 --> 01:06:16.280
[Guest]: out why those rules don't work, or when those rules don't work.

01:06:16.280 --> 01:06:23.320
[Guest]: But the art of investing, if there is an art in it, it is the process of figuring out what

01:06:23.320 --> 01:06:28.520
[Guest]: works and what doesn't, and why sometimes some things are different, and sometimes some

01:06:28.520 --> 01:06:30.760
[Guest]: things are exactly the same.

01:06:30.760 --> 01:06:36.920
[Guest]: And many times in this process, you'll find out that, OK, so let me start with the basics.

01:06:36.920 --> 01:06:42.640
[Guest]: You say, OK, the basic advice is invest on a regular basis, and you'll make money.

01:06:42.640 --> 01:06:46.320
[Guest]: And then you're doing this for a while, and then suddenly you realize, oh, shit, you know

01:06:46.320 --> 01:06:47.320
[Guest]: what?

01:06:47.320 --> 01:06:48.320
[Guest]: The market's going up.

01:06:48.320 --> 01:06:52.080
[Guest]: Instead of me doing this every month, why don't I just double down every time, just

01:06:52.080 --> 01:06:53.080
[Guest]: add more money?

01:06:53.080 --> 01:06:56.880
[Guest]: I add more money, and the market keeps going up, and I feel like I'm a genius.

01:06:56.880 --> 01:07:01.200
[Guest]: This is happening right now with a lot of people who started six months ago, but it's

01:07:01.200 --> 01:07:05.280
[Guest]: happened on every bull cycle in the past.

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:09.240
[Guest]: So when you become a genius, the first thing you do is start telling your friends that

01:07:09.240 --> 01:07:14.240
[Guest]: you're a genius, and nowadays it's the WhatsApps and the signals and whatever it is.

01:07:14.240 --> 01:07:17.960
[Guest]: And then you form a following of that sort.

01:07:17.960 --> 01:07:22.800
[Guest]: And over time, there's a crash at some point, and then you realize you're not a genius and

01:07:22.800 --> 01:07:27.800
[Guest]: that this market's going to beat you up, because you'll make the same mistakes that other people

01:07:27.800 --> 01:07:30.080
[Guest]: are writing that you're making.

01:07:30.080 --> 01:07:34.040
[Guest]: The other people are telling you, listen, don't double down on a stock that's got corporate

01:07:34.040 --> 01:07:35.040
[Guest]: governance issues.

01:07:35.040 --> 01:07:37.640
[Guest]: And you're like, no, no, no, it's temporary.

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:42.040
[Guest]: The promoter is not really looking to siphon out cash, but he needs money right now.

01:07:42.040 --> 01:07:48.640
[Guest]: So that statement is just the worst, most horrible statement ever, because if he's siphoning

01:07:48.640 --> 01:07:51.280
[Guest]: out cash, it's probably real.

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:59.080
[Guest]: So then you break it down and say, dude, I won't invest in these stocks at all, ever.

01:07:59.080 --> 01:08:01.960
[Guest]: And then somebody comes and tells you, no, there's something called technical analysis,

01:08:01.960 --> 01:08:04.680
[Guest]: where you look only at prices.

01:08:04.680 --> 01:08:06.280
[Guest]: Forget what the fundament, what the company does.

01:08:06.280 --> 01:08:07.280
[Guest]: It doesn't matter.

01:08:07.280 --> 01:08:08.520
[Guest]: The price is going up.

01:08:08.520 --> 01:08:09.520
[Guest]: You buy it.

01:08:09.520 --> 01:08:11.760
[Guest]: If the price is coming down, you sell it.

01:08:11.760 --> 01:08:17.400
[Guest]: So there's this famous investor called Sameer Arora, who's pretty active on Twitter, a very

01:08:17.400 --> 01:08:18.400
[Guest]: witty saying.

01:08:18.400 --> 01:08:22.840
[Guest]: So one of the things is that they tell you the advice is that buy stocks that go up.

01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:28.080
[Guest]: If you ask them, what about if it goes down, then don't buy it.

01:08:28.080 --> 01:08:33.400
[Guest]: So basically, it's hindsight bias and all that stuff.

01:08:33.400 --> 01:08:38.520
[Guest]: But all the logical biases we see in debates and reasoning, the same kind of biases exist

01:08:38.520 --> 01:08:41.200
[Guest]: in investing, which is you have hindsight bias.

01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:43.760
[Guest]: You look at survivorship.

01:08:43.760 --> 01:08:47.560
[Guest]: You say that this strategy worked, because you look back and say, well, if I had done

01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:49.360
[Guest]: this to Bajaj Finance, it would have been great.

01:08:49.360 --> 01:08:50.360
[Guest]: But you know what?

01:08:50.360 --> 01:08:54.640
[Guest]: At the same time that Bajaj Finance was there, the same rule set you used qualified a Suzlon

01:08:54.640 --> 01:08:55.640
[Guest]: as well.

01:08:55.640 --> 01:08:58.840
[Guest]: So if you put your money half and half in both, well, you might still have made out

01:08:58.840 --> 01:09:03.080
[Guest]: like a bandit, but it'll be like a smaller bandit, a bandit without a bandana.

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:08.720
[Guest]: But I mean, these are the things that you learn over time, that these rules that they

01:09:08.720 --> 01:09:16.240
[Guest]: quote you are selective, sometimes designed to impress rather than actually be true.

01:09:16.240 --> 01:09:22.400
[Guest]: And nobody is entitled, perhaps, to correct advice.

01:09:22.400 --> 01:09:27.400
[Guest]: But nobody gives you that, because everybody is colored by their own biases.

01:09:27.400 --> 01:09:34.600
[Guest]: The richest of investors today, people whom we admire or see, have to some extent been

01:09:34.600 --> 01:09:36.200
[Guest]: shaped by luck.

01:09:36.200 --> 01:09:41.840
[Guest]: And the few people that don't recognize that, you should be so wary of them, because giving

01:09:41.840 --> 01:09:43.160
[Guest]: gyan is easy, man.

01:09:43.160 --> 01:09:49.880
[Guest]: But not recognizing the role of luck in your investing life is a sin.

01:09:49.880 --> 01:09:58.560
[Guest]: We're all children of an extremely lucky regime, you know, and in the markets, there's more

01:09:58.560 --> 01:10:00.520
[Guest]: luck than anything else.

01:10:00.520 --> 01:10:06.640
[Guest]: And to attribute most of it to skill is, you know, like you said, they haven't bluffed

