[Amit Varma]: who delve deep into one thing.

01:11:48.880 --> 01:11:52.040
[Amit Varma]: But if you have the right models, you can be both a fox and a hedgehog, you can know

01:11:52.040 --> 01:11:53.800
[Amit Varma]: a lot about different things.

01:11:53.800 --> 01:11:58.080
[Amit Varma]: So I sort of designed this episode not just to talk about investing, which of course Deepak

01:11:58.080 --> 01:12:02.240
[Amit Varma]: is the ideal person to speak about that, but also a bunch of other things.

01:12:02.240 --> 01:12:07.320
[Amit Varma]: But before I do that, I'll go off on a sort of a little bit of a tangent and come up with

01:12:07.320 --> 01:12:11.400
[Amit Varma]: a thought experiment of cricket, which is and I'll explain why it is relevant to my

01:12:11.400 --> 01:12:15.680
[Amit Varma]: listeners right after this, which is that let's say that, you know, in a universe where

01:12:15.680 --> 01:12:20.240
[Amit Varma]: betting on matches is illegal, let's say there is a series between India and Australia, and

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:23.120
[Amit Varma]: they are going to play say five one day matches, right?

01:12:23.120 --> 01:12:30.080
[Amit Varma]: So what you do is you have the database of 1000 punters, and you write to the 1000 punters,

01:12:30.080 --> 01:12:33.800
[Amit Varma]: and you say, listen, here's the thing, all these matches are fixed, I know what is going

01:12:33.800 --> 01:12:38.800
[Amit Varma]: to happen, I will tell you the result, and you don't need to pay me anything, you can

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:42.600
[Amit Varma]: either choose to bet or not to bet, but I will give you the result in advance you track

01:12:42.600 --> 01:12:44.280
[Amit Varma]: what happens, right?

01:12:44.280 --> 01:12:47.660
[Amit Varma]: And then you write to 500 of those 1000 guys and say India will win.

01:12:47.660 --> 01:12:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And you tell the other half that Australia will win.

01:12:50.240 --> 01:12:54.240
[Amit Varma]: So now what will happen is that one of those two sides will win.

01:12:54.240 --> 01:12:58.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, 500 people have just seen that you got the first prediction right.

01:12:58.480 --> 01:13:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Then you write to 250 of them and say India will win the second one 250, and so on and

01:13:02.520 --> 01:13:03.520
[Amit Varma]: so forth.

01:13:03.520 --> 01:13:08.360
[Amit Varma]: And in the end, you will have a bunch of people who will see that you got all five predictions

01:13:08.360 --> 01:13:09.360
[Amit Varma]: right.

01:13:09.360 --> 01:13:14.780
[Amit Varma]: And what simply happened here, that that particular line of predictions which took you there is

01:13:14.780 --> 01:13:17.680
[Amit Varma]: what you can call survivorship bias.

01:13:17.680 --> 01:13:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And that also illustrates the role of luck in life that the market is full of many, many

01:13:22.480 --> 01:13:27.160
[Amit Varma]: people and many, many funds and, you know, trying all kinds of different strategies.

01:13:27.160 --> 01:13:32.760
[Amit Varma]: And the guy who got those five hits, you know, right in a row, obviously, the odds against

01:13:32.760 --> 01:13:36.960
[Amit Varma]: anybody getting those five hits in a row are it's incredibly unlikely.

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:41.200
[Amit Varma]: But if everybody's trying all kinds of things, a bunch of people will get those five hits

01:13:41.200 --> 01:13:46.200
[Amit Varma]: right in a row just by accident or just by luck, which is not to say that all successful

01:13:46.200 --> 01:13:50.860
[Amit Varma]: firms are all successful investors are beneficiaries of the survivorship bias.

01:13:50.860 --> 01:13:56.720
[Amit Varma]: But it is a possibility to consider that luck also played a big role in whatever they did.

01:13:56.720 --> 01:13:59.260
[Amit Varma]: And this is, of course, one of the biases that you mentioned.

01:13:59.260 --> 01:14:04.040
[Amit Varma]: So this sort of thought experiment kind of came to mind because whichever smart punter

01:14:04.040 --> 01:14:07.360
[Amit Varma]: tried this, you know, the guys who've seen him get all five right are going to pay him

01:14:07.360 --> 01:14:11.760
[Amit Varma]: big money to, you know, for his next prediction.

01:14:11.760 --> 01:14:15.680
[Amit Varma]: And even if he gets it wrong, they'll rationalize that because now they're kind of invested

01:14:15.680 --> 01:14:18.720
[Amit Varma]: and sunk cost fallacy and all of that rubbish comes into play.

01:14:18.720 --> 01:14:23.140
[Amit Varma]: As far as sort of since you had bought a poker, poker is different from other kinds of gambling

01:14:23.140 --> 01:14:25.680
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that you're not playing against a house.

01:14:25.680 --> 01:14:27.440
[Amit Varma]: You're playing against other players.

01:14:27.440 --> 01:14:30.240
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, it is a game of skill.

01:14:30.240 --> 01:14:33.660
[Amit Varma]: But it's a zero sum game when there is no house involved, when the house takes a little

01:14:33.660 --> 01:14:35.560
[Amit Varma]: bit of rake out of every pot.

01:14:35.560 --> 01:14:37.520
[Amit Varma]: It's a negative sum game.

01:14:37.520 --> 01:14:40.800
[Amit Varma]: But the key point that you mentioned there was bankroll management, like in one of your

01:14:40.800 --> 01:14:46.200
[Amit Varma]: other interviews, I saw about how, you know, after your early investing foray, which you

01:14:46.200 --> 01:14:52.280
[Amit Varma]: mentioned, you actually put all your savings into VSNL, I think it was, right?

01:14:52.280 --> 01:14:58.680
[Guest]: It was, yes, I mean, the first stock that I bought was VSNL, I think, which is actually,

01:14:58.680 --> 01:15:03.400
[Guest]: by the way, as I find out very recently, probably a good thing to have done.

01:15:03.400 --> 01:15:04.400
[Guest]: But yes.

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:05.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:09.860
[Amit Varma]: So the point being there is that bankroll management is incredibly important.

01:15:09.860 --> 01:15:14.820
[Amit Varma]: Even proper bankroll management can see you go closer and closer towards getting broke.

01:15:14.820 --> 01:15:20.120
[Amit Varma]: So you also have to, in a sense, it would help if you don't have human emotions, if

01:15:20.120 --> 01:15:23.960
[Amit Varma]: you can just focus on doing the right thing, because we are also wired with something called

01:15:23.960 --> 01:15:28.760
[Amit Varma]: loss aversion, we react more negatively to losses than we do to profits.

01:15:28.760 --> 01:15:32.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, which is, again, a sort of a problematic thing to control.

01:15:32.720 --> 01:15:37.400
[Amit Varma]: But the big question that I want to kind of ask you is, oh, by the way, another of these

01:15:37.400 --> 01:15:41.100
[Amit Varma]: sort of biases that you mentioned is, you know, and you've mentioned this in previous

01:15:41.100 --> 01:15:46.120
[Amit Varma]: interviews also, that what beginning investors will tend to do is if a stock goes down, they

01:15:46.120 --> 01:15:49.220
[Amit Varma]: will want to hold on to it because they want to recoup their losses.

01:15:49.220 --> 01:15:52.360
[Amit Varma]: But if it goes up a little bit, they'll sell it immediately because oh man, I took profit

01:15:52.360 --> 01:15:55.480
[Amit Varma]: banal here, which is entirely the wrong thing to do in poker.

01:15:55.480 --> 01:16:00.760
[Amit Varma]: The phrase we use for it is called eating like a bird shitting like an elephant.

01:16:00.760 --> 01:16:03.040
[Amit Varma]: So that's kind of what it amounts to.

01:16:03.040 --> 01:16:04.320
[Amit Varma]: So a lot of similarities.

01:16:04.320 --> 01:16:08.240
[Amit Varma]: But the question that I have for you is this that on the one hand, you could say that in

01:16:08.240 --> 01:16:12.920
[Amit Varma]: an ideal world, the sort of you look at the fundamentals of a company, the sort of the

01:16:12.920 --> 01:16:16.880
[Amit Varma]: Benjamin Graham, Warren Buffett kind of way you look at the fundamentals, you look at

01:16:16.880 --> 01:16:21.480
[Amit Varma]: the balance sheet, you make projections into the future and the stock prices based on that.

01:16:21.480 --> 01:16:26.040
[Amit Varma]: But then as we know, in the real world, prices are based on supply and demand.

01:16:26.040 --> 01:16:32.080
[Amit Varma]: And when it comes to the stock market, it seems to me that they are based a lot on perception.

01:16:32.080 --> 01:16:34.860
[Amit Varma]: And it's not just a perception of how the company is doing.

01:16:34.860 --> 01:16:37.960
[Amit Varma]: Even if you know the company is shit, you see the stock price going up and you're playing

01:16:37.960 --> 01:16:42.280
[Amit Varma]: the greater fool theory that, you know, I might buy it at a high price, but somebody

01:16:42.280 --> 01:16:46.500
[Amit Varma]: will buy it at a higher price because hey, after all, it's moving up as Chuck Prince

01:16:46.500 --> 01:16:50.100
[Amit Varma]: of Citigroup once said, when the music's playing, you got to keep on dancing.

01:16:50.100 --> 01:16:54.400
[Amit Varma]: Even if you know you're in a bubble, it could be profitable for you to remain in the bubble.

01:16:54.400 --> 01:16:59.040
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, it could be rational for you to pay irrational prices if you believe that

01:16:59.040 --> 01:17:01.620
[Amit Varma]: those prices are going to keep going up.

01:17:01.620 --> 01:17:05.040
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that becomes a game which is not related to the real world.

01:17:05.040 --> 01:17:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Although, you know, George Soros has had once coined the term reflexivity, we're talking

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:13.440
[Amit Varma]: about how perceptions can affect reality and your example of our company with a high share

01:17:13.440 --> 01:17:17.680
[Amit Varma]: price can raise capital, which can actually make it a good company and can justify the

01:17:17.680 --> 01:17:21.720
[Amit Varma]: share price, which is, you know, seems to me to be a classic example of how perception

01:17:21.720 --> 01:17:24.280
[Amit Varma]: can actually sort of change reality.

01:17:24.280 --> 01:17:28.520
[Amit Varma]: So it seems to me at one level that one, that's a game.

01:17:28.520 --> 01:17:34.400
[Amit Varma]: That's a game where it's not so much anymore about what companies may or may not do.

01:17:34.400 --> 01:17:38.140
[Amit Varma]: That's just one factor in it, how our company is doing, how solid are there.

01:17:38.140 --> 01:17:43.640
[Amit Varma]: But the other bigger factor is the perceptions of all the other players in the game.

01:17:43.640 --> 01:17:48.960
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you are, you know, understanding human behavior is as big a skill, if not a

01:17:48.960 --> 01:17:52.720
[Amit Varma]: greater skill than understanding balance sheets, for example.

01:17:52.720 --> 01:17:54.880
[Amit Varma]: And so how do you approach this?

01:17:54.880 --> 01:17:57.200
[Amit Varma]: Do you take this as something that is a given?

01:17:57.200 --> 01:18:02.420
[Amit Varma]: And then say that, yes, within this given, there can be different sort of systems to

01:18:02.420 --> 01:18:03.680
[Amit Varma]: approach investing?

01:18:03.680 --> 01:18:06.440
[Amit Varma]: How has your thinking on this kind of evolved?

01:18:06.440 --> 01:18:11.640
[Guest]: So I think this is a very interesting topic, because this comes back to the thing I said,

01:18:11.640 --> 01:18:15.160
[Guest]: there is no one right answer, there's many right answers.

01:18:15.160 --> 01:18:20.920
[Guest]: And when you start off, you become increasingly militant about your own thought process.

01:18:20.920 --> 01:18:23.720
[Guest]: I like value investing, everything else is shit.

01:18:23.720 --> 01:18:28.560
[Guest]: You guys don't know what a company is supposed to be worth, you're paying, overpaying for

01:18:28.560 --> 01:18:30.160
[Guest]: this and underpaying for that.

01:18:30.160 --> 01:18:38.240
[Guest]: And then you realize the most horrible way that perhaps somebody else, you know, grows

01:18:38.240 --> 01:18:43.240
[Guest]: richer and richer, despite following the exact opposite strategy that you have.

01:18:43.240 --> 01:18:47.560
[Guest]: And you suddenly realize that that's, after some time, you come to realize that many ways

01:18:47.560 --> 01:18:52.760
[Guest]: to play the, there are many ways to skin, I don't know who skins cats, but assuming

01:18:52.760 --> 01:18:55.680
[Guest]: that some people do, there are many ways to do it.

01:18:55.680 --> 01:19:00.520
[Guest]: But here's the thing that you start.

01:19:00.520 --> 01:19:06.040
[Guest]: You think of companies as a result of metrics, or they make profits, they should be worth

01:19:06.040 --> 01:19:07.920
[Guest]: X amount of profits.

01:19:07.920 --> 01:19:12.120
[Guest]: Maybe if I had my money, I could put it in a fixed deposit, it gives me four and a half,

01:19:12.120 --> 01:19:13.120
[Guest]: 5% a year.

01:19:13.120 --> 01:19:17.080
[Guest]: Therefore, if I put 100 rupees into a fixed deposit, it gives me 5 rupees a year.

01:19:17.080 --> 01:19:22.720
[Guest]: Can I find a company that earns 5 rupees if I gave it 100 rupees?

01:19:22.720 --> 01:19:26.120
[Guest]: So you look at something called a return on equity, which is a similar metric, and you

01:19:26.120 --> 01:19:30.360
[Guest]: say, okay, well, this company earns 20 rupees for every 100 rupees that it has.

01:19:30.360 --> 01:19:34.200
[Guest]: It's a fantastic company, better than my fixed deposit, there's some risk, so I'll ask it

01:19:34.200 --> 01:19:37.160
[Guest]: to earn 20% or 10%, more than 10.

01:19:37.160 --> 01:19:38.960
[Guest]: So it's 20, so it's good.

01:19:38.960 --> 01:19:41.840
[Guest]: Then you find out that this company is worth something else.

01:19:41.840 --> 01:19:46.640
[Guest]: Now in the 70s, there were these companies called the Nifty 50.

01:19:46.640 --> 01:19:51.840
[Guest]: This is not related to our Nifty in India, but they were called the Nifty 50, among them

01:19:51.840 --> 01:19:57.680
[Guest]: were very interesting companies, including McDonald's, and at the time, Kodak.

01:19:57.680 --> 01:20:03.440
[Guest]: Now Kodak eventually went bankrupt, but you paid a huge amount of money for these extremely

01:20:03.440 --> 01:20:04.440
[Guest]: good businesses.

01:20:04.440 --> 01:20:06.360
[Guest]: McDonald's is not a bad business at all.

01:20:06.360 --> 01:20:12.760
[Guest]: Except 10 years later, the McDonald's price was 70% lower than it was in the 70s when

01:20:12.760 --> 01:20:14.160
[Guest]: I talk about this.

01:20:14.160 --> 01:20:20.320
[Guest]: So sometimes you overpay for a business, believing that it's a good business, and you will not

01:20:20.320 --> 01:20:22.240
[Guest]: make any money on that.

01:20:22.240 --> 01:20:26.720
[Guest]: It's like if you paid the price of a Mercedes for a Maruti, you're not going to get a Mercedes

01:20:26.720 --> 01:20:27.720
[Guest]: in performance.

01:20:27.720 --> 01:20:28.720
[Guest]: You're going to get a Maruti.

01:20:28.720 --> 01:20:33.120
[Guest]: And not to, I own Maruti, so I shouldn't say too much, many bad things about it, and don't

01:20:33.120 --> 01:20:34.280
[Guest]: own Mercedes.

01:20:34.280 --> 01:20:41.400
[Guest]: But here is where the point is that you have to now be a judge of whether what you're paying

01:20:41.400 --> 01:20:43.240
[Guest]: is worth it or not.

01:20:43.240 --> 01:20:47.320
[Guest]: So valuation and business analysis are two slightly different things.

01:20:47.320 --> 01:20:50.480
[Guest]: You come to the conclusion that, okay, I'll pay a certain value for this kind of business.

01:20:50.480 --> 01:20:53.600
[Guest]: Then you find out there are certain businesses where you can't value them.

01:20:53.600 --> 01:20:58.560
[Guest]: You simply cannot, because you couldn't have imagined the power of an iPhone when the iPhone

01:20:58.560 --> 01:20:59.560
[Guest]: came out.

01:20:59.560 --> 01:21:02.560
[Guest]: A very few people really thought, they thought it was a bigger iPod.

01:21:02.560 --> 01:21:07.160
[Guest]: Oh, you put the internet and the iPod together in one thing, huh, okay, whatever.

01:21:07.160 --> 01:21:13.080
[Guest]: But you didn't realize there was a revolution that changed things, and it killed Nokia in

01:21:13.080 --> 01:21:16.800
[Guest]: a way that even Nokia couldn't have imagined.

01:21:16.800 --> 01:21:22.160
[Guest]: But something fundamental changed about the world, and what's happening now is doing that.

01:21:22.160 --> 01:21:27.560
[Guest]: What we don't realize is that in the last, say, 12 to 24 months, we've slowly seen a

01:21:27.560 --> 01:21:31.080
[Guest]: change happening, and we have not even acknowledged it.

01:21:31.080 --> 01:21:32.080
[Guest]: Restaurants used to deliver.

01:21:32.080 --> 01:21:34.720
[Guest]: Now, restaurants in India don't deliver.

01:21:34.720 --> 01:21:40.160
[Guest]: You always use Swiggy or Zomato or one of these things for delivery.

01:21:40.160 --> 01:21:43.840
[Guest]: And the restaurants themselves don't employ delivery people at all.

01:21:43.840 --> 01:21:49.720
[Guest]: The whole delivery workforce of hotels or restaurants, which was perhaps sometimes earlier

01:21:49.720 --> 01:21:55.920
[Guest]: part-time postgraduate people, students, and all that stuff, is gone.

01:21:55.920 --> 01:21:56.920
[Guest]: That's complete.

01:21:56.920 --> 01:21:58.120
[Guest]: That entire model has gone bust.

01:21:58.120 --> 01:22:04.680
[Guest]: In the late 90s, there was these things called STD and ISD booths.

01:22:04.680 --> 01:22:09.280
[Guest]: If you lose your phone today, there is no way you can make a phone call by paying someone

01:22:09.280 --> 01:22:10.280
[Guest]: for it.

01:22:10.280 --> 01:22:13.320
[Guest]: You literally have to beg someone for a phone and ask them to give it to you free, and most

01:22:13.320 --> 01:22:17.000
[Guest]: of them will because they don't pay anything for the phone call anyways.

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:24.040
[Guest]: But it stuns me that the whole STD, ISD model went to zero, and we didn't even notice when.

01:22:24.040 --> 01:22:29.960
[Guest]: And when you see these changes coming in an industry that you could invest in, you might

01:22:29.960 --> 01:22:33.960
[Guest]: actually see these nonlinear gains simply because they're not available on those balance

01:22:33.960 --> 01:22:34.960
[Guest]: sheets anyway.

01:22:34.960 --> 01:22:35.960
[Guest]: They're not available.

01:22:35.960 --> 01:22:38.240
[Guest]: They're a function of the future, not of the past.

01:22:38.240 --> 01:22:42.400
[Guest]: They're a function of new technology that's coming in and that's going to break everything.

01:22:42.400 --> 01:22:43.400
[Guest]: Electric vehicles, for instance.

01:22:43.400 --> 01:22:48.840
[Guest]: People say, oh, Tesla is expensive and this, but when you go down to the wire, you actually

01:22:48.840 --> 01:22:56.040
[Guest]: find out the electric cars will not sell because they're environmentally friendly.

01:22:56.040 --> 01:22:58.800
[Guest]: I don't think many people care.

01:22:58.800 --> 01:23:03.040
[Guest]: They will sell because they're cheaper and faster, period.

01:23:03.040 --> 01:23:10.240
[Guest]: And that change, if you tell a person, yeah, you know what, I'm going to keep these motorcycle

01:23:10.240 --> 01:23:15.600
[Guest]: and stock, these companies, even though they continue to sell gas-based bikes and they

01:23:15.600 --> 01:23:19.520
[Guest]: don't have a strategy for electric, because you know what, nobody's going to buy these

01:23:19.520 --> 01:23:20.520
[Guest]: environmentally.

01:23:20.520 --> 01:23:21.520
[Guest]: This is just a fad.

01:23:21.520 --> 01:23:22.520
[Guest]: It's not.

01:23:22.520 --> 01:23:24.320
[Guest]: It's actually economically better.

01:23:24.320 --> 01:23:27.960
[Guest]: And if you see this as a model, you could have said this four years ago, it would have

01:23:27.960 --> 01:23:28.960
[Guest]: been right.

01:23:28.960 --> 01:23:32.480
[Guest]: But the last four years, electric hasn't taken off in India in any meaningful way.

01:23:32.480 --> 01:23:34.480
[Guest]: You can't see that for the next four.

01:23:34.480 --> 01:23:38.360
[Guest]: It's about now trying to judge whether that model comes.

01:23:38.360 --> 01:23:42.320
[Guest]: And then if you're involved in a company that does not have an electric footprint of any

01:23:42.320 --> 01:23:46.720
[Guest]: sort, then you may be on the losing side of things.

01:23:46.720 --> 01:23:52.200
[Guest]: So you have a great balance sheet, Maruti has no debt, it has a lot of cash on the balance

01:23:52.200 --> 01:23:56.320
[Guest]: sheet, it has so many cars that are selling, it sells half the number of cars that India

01:23:56.320 --> 01:23:58.000
[Guest]: sells every month.

01:23:58.000 --> 01:24:04.720
[Guest]: And yet, if it doesn't have a strategy for electric cars, it might just not survive the

01:24:04.720 --> 01:24:05.980
[Guest]: next decade.

01:24:05.980 --> 01:24:08.440
[Guest]: So things could happen that fast.

01:24:08.440 --> 01:24:11.960
[Guest]: So when you're investing, your problem is now no longer like, oh, I can look at the

01:24:11.960 --> 01:24:13.560
[Guest]: accounts and figure out what's doing well.

01:24:13.560 --> 01:24:16.880
[Guest]: It's also, I have to guess the future and see what's doing well.

01:24:16.880 --> 01:24:21.720
[Guest]: And I can't guess what, one of the alternatives to what you talked about in the cricketing

01:24:21.720 --> 01:24:25.040
[Guest]: term is happens every day in stocks.

01:24:25.040 --> 01:24:30.480
[Guest]: People send you five stocks, saying these five stocks will do well.

01:24:30.480 --> 01:24:33.200
[Guest]: Invariably one of them does.

01:24:33.200 --> 01:24:36.640
[Guest]: The next day I said, I told you about this stock.

01:24:36.640 --> 01:24:40.880
[Guest]: Now I don't even have to wait for that 1000 to trickle down to 20, I can do this to you

01:24:40.880 --> 01:24:44.800
[Guest]: every single day and give you five stocks and you'll be thinking, dude, this guy is

01:24:44.800 --> 01:24:45.800
[Guest]: a genius.

01:24:45.800 --> 01:24:48.320
[Guest]: Every day he identifies a good stock.

01:24:48.320 --> 01:24:51.400
[Guest]: But you aren't looking at the fact that I've lost on four of them.

01:24:51.400 --> 01:24:54.040
[Guest]: And it's very rare that you are lost on all five.

01:24:54.040 --> 01:24:57.200
[Guest]: In those days, you know, I'll stop talking to you, I'll go to the next guy.

01:24:57.200 --> 01:25:02.480
[Guest]: But this is how the tips market has been working in India for the longest time.

01:25:02.480 --> 01:25:08.920
[Guest]: In times like these when the markets are really hot, you find that, you know, relative newcomers

01:25:08.920 --> 01:25:13.000
[Guest]: will come and tell you, listen, I just did this and you know what, the stock's up 45%

01:25:13.000 --> 01:25:14.280
[Guest]: in a month.

01:25:14.280 --> 01:25:18.360
[Guest]: And this is where, you know, they haven't bluffed enough, they haven't played enough

01:25:18.360 --> 01:25:23.340
[Guest]: because they haven't seen the downturn because they're highlighting the wins.

01:25:23.340 --> 01:25:28.840
[Guest]: You meet a guy who highlights his losers, that's the guy you want to talk to about investing.

01:25:28.840 --> 01:25:31.240
[Guest]: Because he's going to tell you the real lessons that are learned.

01:25:31.240 --> 01:25:34.000
[Guest]: Investing is for everyone.

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:40.600
[Guest]: So the mental model that you start moving to when you start investing is this other

01:25:40.600 --> 01:25:43.920
[Guest]: part of this philosophy where you say, listen, it's not just the accounts.

01:25:43.920 --> 01:25:45.920
[Guest]: It's not just the future bets.

01:25:45.920 --> 01:25:47.880
[Guest]: It's also now a role of luck.

01:25:47.880 --> 01:25:54.240
[Guest]: Because out of those five things that I pick, which had great accounts and a fantastic future,

01:25:54.240 --> 01:25:55.240
[Guest]: only one did well.

01:25:55.240 --> 01:25:56.240
[Guest]: Why?

01:25:56.240 --> 01:25:58.760
[Guest]: You go back and there's no reason for it.

01:25:58.760 --> 01:26:03.480
[Guest]: And then you say, okay, dude, you know what, I have to play the luck cycle, which means

01:26:03.480 --> 01:26:09.760
[Guest]: I have to have enough of doors so that opportunity will knock on at least one of them.

01:26:09.760 --> 01:26:13.680
[Guest]: Because if you keep just one door, then they could skip it, just look good, I didn't like

01:26:13.680 --> 01:26:14.880
[Guest]: the color or whatever.

01:26:14.880 --> 01:26:20.000
[Guest]: And you know, so the problem with investing as a whole is that you have to imbibe this

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:23.040
[Guest]: philosophy saying, listen, you're not going to know everything.

01:26:23.040 --> 01:26:24.680
[Guest]: And most of the times you'll know nothing.

01:26:24.680 --> 01:26:31.600
[Guest]: So it's good to know a lot of little things about a lot of industry sometimes, and a lot

01:26:31.600 --> 01:26:32.600
[Guest]: about one industry.

01:26:32.600 --> 01:26:35.320
[Guest]: But whatever it is, you got to place multiple bets.

01:26:35.320 --> 01:26:41.160
[Guest]: There's a rule by this guy called Larry Hite, famous trader, he says, the two rules.

01:26:41.160 --> 01:26:45.320
[Guest]: If you don't bet, you won't win.

01:26:45.320 --> 01:26:49.440
[Guest]: Simply means you got to put your money down on something.

01:26:49.440 --> 01:26:53.440
[Guest]: But if you lose all your chips, you can't bet.

01:26:53.440 --> 01:26:57.720
[Guest]: The idea is you got to play to the extent that you don't lose all your chips.

01:26:57.720 --> 01:27:03.160
[Guest]: In poker, you can, because people go all in, and then you either have to bet all in or

01:27:03.160 --> 01:27:04.160
[Guest]: walk away.

01:27:04.160 --> 01:27:07.920
[Guest]: And at some point, if they keep betting all in, you're going to lose all your chips.

01:27:07.920 --> 01:27:10.800
[Guest]: But in markets, you don't have to bet all your chips.

01:27:10.800 --> 01:27:14.480
[Guest]: There is no fear in walking away in the middle.

01:27:14.480 --> 01:27:19.840
[Guest]: And you know, you can take part profits away from the market at all points in time.

01:27:19.840 --> 01:27:23.840
[Guest]: From this, the framework slightly starts to change, saying, look, now you've got to diversify.

01:27:23.840 --> 01:27:29.360
[Guest]: You've got to take a bunch of industries that you think will do well, and a bunch of industries

01:27:29.360 --> 01:27:31.720
[Guest]: that perhaps have done well.

01:27:31.720 --> 01:27:36.600
[Guest]: So I want to look at, say, a cement company, and say, you know what, cement is the most

01:27:36.600 --> 01:27:41.920
[Guest]: boring thing in the world, because you take a bunch of limestone and something else and

01:27:41.920 --> 01:27:45.680
[Guest]: make something out of it that you can't even import, because by the time you ship it from

01:27:45.680 --> 01:27:49.320
[Guest]: China, it turns into stone because of the sea.

01:27:49.320 --> 01:27:52.160
[Guest]: So it's got this little local market in India.

01:27:52.160 --> 01:27:56.040
[Guest]: So I'm going to bet on the cement player, because you can't, it doesn't have competition

01:27:56.040 --> 01:27:57.040
[Guest]: from abroad.

01:27:57.040 --> 01:27:58.680
[Guest]: And in India, everybody's a cartel.

01:27:58.680 --> 01:27:59.680
[Guest]: We all know that.

01:27:59.680 --> 01:28:02.720
[Guest]: But we love it, because we are invested in their shares.

01:28:02.720 --> 01:28:05.320
[Guest]: And cement companies will do well.

01:28:05.320 --> 01:28:07.960
[Guest]: There's no reason why this same argument doesn't apply to the US.

01:28:07.960 --> 01:28:13.080
[Guest]: It's just that in the US, there are a lot more cement companies, perhaps, but they also

01:28:13.080 --> 01:28:18.720
[Guest]: don't have these supernormal profit regimes that the current Indian ones do.

01:28:18.720 --> 01:28:22.260
[Guest]: So you're going to bet on, say, cement and a couple of players in the cement industry.

01:28:22.260 --> 01:28:25.920
[Guest]: But I can't stick to cement, because that may not be the only thing that works.

01:28:25.920 --> 01:28:29.060
[Guest]: So I'll buy some steel, and I'll buy some technology, and I'll buy some.

01:28:29.060 --> 01:28:32.800
[Guest]: So you're going to now start diversifying into all of this.

01:28:32.800 --> 01:28:35.200
[Guest]: Somewhere along the way, you say, dude, I've got, like, 40 companies.

01:28:35.200 --> 01:28:36.200
[Guest]: What am I doing?

01:28:36.200 --> 01:28:37.840
[Guest]: I don't have time to analyze all of these companies.

01:28:37.840 --> 01:28:41.760
[Guest]: And every day, somebody or the other buys a small stake, and then I have to go and figure

01:28:41.760 --> 01:28:45.800
[Guest]: out who this guy is, and why is he buying, and why is someone selling to him.

01:28:45.800 --> 01:28:51.080
[Guest]: And some news or press release comes saying, we have been awarded a prize.

01:28:51.080 --> 01:28:57.600
[Guest]: Now, it's time to even figure out if this is valuable news.

01:28:57.600 --> 01:29:02.760
[Guest]: Sometimes it is completely useless, and sometimes it's the news that makes or breaks a company.

01:29:02.760 --> 01:29:07.200
[Guest]: When you spend more and more time on a per-company basis, you have diversified too much.

01:29:07.200 --> 01:29:08.200
[Guest]: You have 40 or 50 companies.

01:29:08.200 --> 01:29:11.800
[Guest]: You say, well, you know what, this doesn't work for me.

01:29:11.800 --> 01:29:16.120
[Guest]: Somebody has created something called an index, it's called a Sensex or a Nifty.

01:29:16.120 --> 01:29:21.320
[Guest]: They've found the 50 most valuable companies, put it into a bunch, and they've said, listen,

01:29:21.320 --> 01:29:22.320
[Guest]: this is the index.

01:29:22.320 --> 01:29:23.560
[Guest]: This is what the market is about.

01:29:23.560 --> 01:29:28.280
[Guest]: And I'll say, listen, I know that whatever is today's Nifty is not tomorrow's, because

01:29:28.280 --> 01:29:31.640
[Guest]: tomorrow some other company may come in.

01:29:31.640 --> 01:29:34.400
[Guest]: Why don't I just buy whatever you call the Nifty?

01:29:34.400 --> 01:29:38.840
[Guest]: And if you change one company, and Yes Bank goes out, and some new bank comes in, I'm

01:29:38.840 --> 01:29:43.240
[Guest]: going to just sell that Yes Bank and buy the new bank, and I'm done.

01:29:43.240 --> 01:29:48.160
[Guest]: If I did that, I would reduce my effort of tracking which company to buy.

01:29:48.160 --> 01:29:55.000
[Guest]: I don't care if you have cement, steel, technology, cigarettes, anything.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:29:59.360
[Guest]: But as long as you have those companies in this index, I own them if they don't.

01:29:59.360 --> 01:30:01.160
[Guest]: So that became one philosophy.

01:30:01.160 --> 01:30:05.760
[Guest]: And then you take this out, and then you say, why are you buying those 50 companies?

01:30:05.760 --> 01:30:07.160
[Guest]: Let us buy it for you.

01:30:07.160 --> 01:30:09.360
[Guest]: Just buy one share of me.

01:30:09.360 --> 01:30:14.240
[Guest]: And that became the mutual fund that said, oh, I'll pay the mutual fund manager to figure

01:30:14.240 --> 01:30:15.920
[Guest]: out which companies are good.

01:30:15.920 --> 01:30:18.160
[Guest]: Some of them will just buy an index.

01:30:18.160 --> 01:30:20.400
[Guest]: Some of them will say, I'll go beyond the index.

01:30:20.400 --> 01:30:24.560
[Guest]: I'll find companies that are great and geniuses, and I am this guy who breathes, lives, and

01:30:24.560 --> 01:30:25.560
[Guest]: eats stocks.

01:30:25.560 --> 01:30:26.560
[Guest]: I'm this genius.

01:30:26.560 --> 01:30:29.480
[Guest]: And I have five stocks, and one of them will do well every day.

01:30:29.480 --> 01:30:32.480
[Guest]: And so some people give their money to these tips people.

01:30:32.480 --> 01:30:35.040
[Guest]: Some people give money to the mutual funds.

01:30:35.040 --> 01:30:38.640
[Guest]: Some people give money to an index fund, they call it.

01:30:38.640 --> 01:30:42.240
[Guest]: This is how your training evolves.

01:30:42.240 --> 01:30:45.480
[Guest]: Then pretty much after this is the phase where you start getting frustrated, saying, my mutual

01:30:45.480 --> 01:30:46.720
[Guest]: funds are crap.

01:30:46.720 --> 01:30:50.040
[Guest]: And then somebody tells you that, listen, they're charging too high a fee.

01:30:50.040 --> 01:30:51.040
[Guest]: That's why they're bad.

01:30:51.040 --> 01:30:52.920
[Guest]: And you're like, why am I paying them so much fees?

01:30:52.920 --> 01:30:53.920
[Guest]: Let me do this myself.

01:30:53.920 --> 01:30:54.920
[Guest]: I'd go back.

01:30:54.920 --> 01:30:55.920
[Guest]: I'd do it myself.

01:30:55.920 --> 01:30:58.160
[Guest]: I win a few days.

01:30:58.160 --> 01:31:06.260
[Guest]: And like in poker, there is a point at which a sucker is written on your forehead, right?

01:31:06.260 --> 01:31:09.840
[Guest]: And everybody goes through that phase once in their life, hopefully only once, many people

01:31:09.840 --> 01:31:11.480
[Guest]: many times.

01:31:11.480 --> 01:31:19.520
[Guest]: And those people get beaten up by things like, oh, this guy, I've heard a rumor that this

01:31:19.520 --> 01:31:22.920
[Guest]: company is going to partner with Tesla, and Tesla has just come to India.

01:31:22.920 --> 01:31:24.520
[Guest]: You have to buy this company.

01:31:24.520 --> 01:31:26.240
[Guest]: It goes up 9% on one day.

01:31:26.240 --> 01:31:29.360
[Guest]: This happened today, so I'm not going to name the stock.

01:31:29.360 --> 01:31:34.920
[Guest]: But this company went up 9% in like 10 minutes.

01:31:34.920 --> 01:31:37.540
[Guest]: It ended the day down for the day.

01:31:37.540 --> 01:31:41.320
[Guest]: So if you went in and said, dude, this is like Tesla, come on, and then you find out

01:31:41.320 --> 01:31:44.640
[Guest]: that the news was bullshit, it was rumors and all that stuff.

01:31:44.640 --> 01:31:48.560
[Guest]: And so this process then evolves, and you go and give it back to mutual funds, or sometimes

01:31:48.560 --> 01:31:53.040
[Guest]: you go find what you're really good at and invest it on your own.

01:31:53.040 --> 01:31:56.360
[Guest]: This philosophy, I think, emerges over time.

01:31:56.360 --> 01:32:02.800
[Guest]: It's fascinating for me to watch even myself go through this over time.

01:32:02.800 --> 01:32:07.120
[Guest]: And I see many people drop off somewhere in the line.

01:32:07.120 --> 01:32:08.120
[Guest]: You can see them.

01:32:08.120 --> 01:32:09.120
[Guest]: You've gone in.

01:32:09.120 --> 01:32:11.520
[Guest]: Like, for instance, right now, you've got a lot of people saying, I have to participate

01:32:11.520 --> 01:32:13.280
[Guest]: in the markets.

01:32:13.280 --> 01:32:19.120
[Guest]: And after, this is the third time when I'm seeing a crazy raging bull market in front

01:32:19.120 --> 01:32:20.120
[Guest]: of my eyes.

01:32:20.120 --> 01:32:24.880
[Guest]: And I can tell you that a lot of these people are not coming back when this market tanks

01:32:24.880 --> 01:32:25.880
[Guest]: eventually.

01:32:25.880 --> 01:32:26.880
[Guest]: It will at some point.

01:32:26.880 --> 01:32:27.880
[Guest]: I don't know where it is.

01:32:27.880 --> 01:32:34.680
[Guest]: But again, this is, again, a friendly piece of advice is to not listen to bad news, like

01:32:34.680 --> 01:32:37.720
[Guest]: this is a bubble, and think of it as a bad thing.

01:32:37.720 --> 01:32:38.720
[Guest]: Bubbles are good.

01:32:38.720 --> 01:32:39.880
[Guest]: Bubbles make things happen.

01:32:39.880 --> 01:32:46.820
[Guest]: Bubbles is what gave us an Uber, and eventually a Swiggy and a Zomato and all of that stuff.

01:32:46.820 --> 01:32:49.680
[Guest]: So I thank bubbles for all their work.

01:32:49.680 --> 01:32:54.560
[Guest]: And really, it gave us what Indian stock markets are eventually fascinating, a lot to unpack

01:32:54.560 --> 01:32:55.560
[Amit Varma]: that.

01:32:55.560 --> 01:32:59.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the one reason I have never, I've stayed away from investing is that, you

01:32:59.560 --> 01:33:04.160
[Amit Varma]: know, I try not to get too deep into something about which I don't have too much knowledge.

01:33:04.160 --> 01:33:07.200
[Amit Varma]: So my point is, you know, before I got into poker, study it a lot.

01:33:07.200 --> 01:33:09.160
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you learn along the way.

01:33:09.160 --> 01:33:12.600
[Amit Varma]: For investing, I just thought that I'm not going to invest my money in stock markets,

01:33:12.600 --> 01:33:13.600
[Amit Varma]: because I simply don't know enough.

01:33:13.600 --> 01:33:17.400
[Amit Varma]: And also, for most of my life, I haven't even had the money to invest, but that's a different

01:33:17.400 --> 01:33:18.400
[Amit Varma]: matter.

01:33:18.400 --> 01:33:19.920
[Amit Varma]: So I don't want to do it.

01:33:19.920 --> 01:33:24.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, obviously, a lot of what you said kind of underscores that because there are so many

01:33:24.040 --> 01:33:26.560
[Amit Varma]: factors that goes into how a stock is priced.

01:33:26.560 --> 01:33:30.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, first of all, there's no correct or wrong price, it's all there's a, you know,

01:33:30.760 --> 01:33:34.200
[Amit Varma]: it's an interplay between the real world, how things actually are, and how companies

01:33:34.200 --> 01:33:35.200
[Amit Varma]: are doing.

01:33:35.200 --> 01:33:38.840
[Amit Varma]: It's an interplay between the future, which is full of, you know, unknown unknowns, and

01:33:38.840 --> 01:33:43.360
[Amit Varma]: also with how people perceive the real world and how people perceive the future.

01:33:43.360 --> 01:33:49.080
[Amit Varma]: And it's all dreadfully complex, which is why a point that you have also made earlier

01:33:49.080 --> 01:33:53.000
[Amit Varma]: is that, you know, never mock another system, you might have one system for investing, there

01:33:53.000 --> 01:33:57.440
[Amit Varma]: might be another system which is doing well, have the epistemic humility that, you know,

01:33:57.440 --> 01:33:59.260
[Amit Varma]: there are all kinds of things going around.

01:33:59.260 --> 01:34:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And if what works for you works for you, that's great.

01:34:01.920 --> 01:34:05.640
[Amit Varma]: But don't go too much into, you know, don't diss other ways.

01:34:05.640 --> 01:34:09.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I think of you could, it also goes back to the parable of different blind people

01:34:09.760 --> 01:34:12.400
[Amit Varma]: feeling different parts of an elephant in describing it.

01:34:12.400 --> 01:34:17.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, from this complexity, and the humility within us that it should lead to, there are

01:34:17.640 --> 01:34:20.800
[Amit Varma]: three broad directions I want to kind of go in.

01:34:20.800 --> 01:34:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And the first of those directions is the role of machine learning, or, you know, algorithmic

01:34:28.000 --> 01:34:33.640
[Amit Varma]: trading, which you did at a point in time, where, you know, it like, the one thing that

01:34:33.640 --> 01:34:38.120
[Amit Varma]: strikes me is that the market is too complex, and all the movements and everything are too

01:34:38.120 --> 01:34:43.280
[Amit Varma]: complex for humans to figure out with our primitive brains, which are very advanced

01:34:43.280 --> 01:34:46.180
[Amit Varma]: in other ways, but in certain ways are very primitive.

01:34:46.180 --> 01:34:47.600
[Amit Varma]: And machines can do that better.

01:34:47.600 --> 01:34:52.760
[Amit Varma]: Like, I had Professor Vasant Dhar on this episode recently, he teaches in Stern School

01:34:52.760 --> 01:34:54.340
[Amit Varma]: of Business in New York.

01:34:54.340 --> 01:34:57.640
[Amit Varma]: So I had an episode with him called Brave New World, I'm also producing a podcast for

01:34:57.640 --> 01:35:02.160
[Amit Varma]: him called Brave New World, I think, episode four should be out this week.

01:35:02.160 --> 01:35:07.060
[Amit Varma]: And he started an algorithmic trading firm in New York in the 1990s.

01:35:07.060 --> 01:35:11.760
[Amit Varma]: And he was talking about how, you know, it would come up with all kinds of counterintuitive

01:35:11.760 --> 01:35:14.560
[Amit Varma]: things, insights, which they would not understand.

01:35:14.560 --> 01:35:19.640
[Amit Varma]: But when they tried to sort of run simulations, where they will use their own judgment, and

01:35:19.640 --> 01:35:22.640
[Amit Varma]: the machine will do something they always lost to the machine.

01:35:22.640 --> 01:35:25.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, I wanted to kind of explore this with you.

01:35:25.600 --> 01:35:30.880
[Amit Varma]: Because initially, whenever we deal with machines in any way, we think that, okay, we are the

01:35:30.880 --> 01:35:35.440
[Amit Varma]: masters, we will program the machine, the machine will do what it does, but we know

01:35:35.440 --> 01:35:36.440
[Amit Varma]: better.

01:35:36.440 --> 01:35:39.960
[Amit Varma]: And at some point, we realized that, you know, good machine learning is just way ahead, like

01:35:39.960 --> 01:35:45.000
[Amit Varma]: I did an episode with a mutual friend, Devanshu Dutta, two or three years ago on AlphaZero,

01:35:45.000 --> 01:35:46.620
[Amit Varma]: the chess program that came out.

01:35:46.620 --> 01:35:51.080
[Amit Varma]: And the reason it was so mind blowing, what AlphaZero basically did was that you didn't

01:35:51.080 --> 01:35:57.280
[Amit Varma]: need to program it like other chess computers with heuristics and with judgments and openings

01:35:57.280 --> 01:35:58.280
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

01:35:58.280 --> 01:36:04.800
[Amit Varma]: It just played against itself a few million times and learned the game and created its

01:36:04.800 --> 01:36:08.560
[Amit Varma]: own heuristics and then destroyed the best computer in the world, which was way stronger

01:36:08.560 --> 01:36:11.480
[Amit Varma]: than the best player in the world, simply destroyed it.

01:36:11.480 --> 01:36:17.440
[Amit Varma]: And it destroyed it, not by brute force, like Stockfish, which was a machine that it beat,

01:36:17.440 --> 01:36:23.120
[Amit Varma]: was doing millions of simulations, you know, per minute, and this was maybe doing 100,000.

01:36:23.120 --> 01:36:27.760
[Amit Varma]: But it by playing itself endlessly, it figured out heuristics, which were often contrary

01:36:27.760 --> 01:36:32.840
[Amit Varma]: to what human chess players had figured out over 300 years of the game, you know, in the

01:36:32.840 --> 01:36:37.760
[Amit Varma]: ways that we value initiative vis-a-vis material and so on and so forth.

01:36:37.760 --> 01:36:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that, you know, so in your, what was your process like of getting into

01:36:42.440 --> 01:36:44.160
[Amit Varma]: algorithmic trading?

01:36:44.160 --> 01:36:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, were there times where, you know, you would reflexively react against

01:36:50.240 --> 01:36:56.200
[Amit Varma]: a counterintuitive kind of inputs coming at you from the machine or from the software,

01:36:56.200 --> 01:37:01.160
[Amit Varma]: but then realizing that there was something it was doing right, which you couldn't fathom.

01:37:01.160 --> 01:37:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And also is, tell me a little bit about momentum trading, because that's something that, you

01:37:06.000 --> 01:37:11.120
[Amit Varma]: know, you worked in for a while, and I would assume that that would be something that,

01:37:11.120 --> 01:37:16.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, emerges out of using AI like this, because the AI is much better place to process

01:37:16.560 --> 01:37:19.480
[Amit Varma]: all the data that you need to for that.

01:37:19.480 --> 01:37:23.160
[Guest]: It's interesting that you bring both these things up, because I think there's a little

01:37:23.160 --> 01:37:25.120
[Guest]: bit of a difference between that.

01:37:25.120 --> 01:37:31.140
[Guest]: So algorithmic trading is, let's say, there's two areas to it.

01:37:31.140 --> 01:37:36.640
[Guest]: So one is, I want to find opportunities to invest in the market.

01:37:36.640 --> 01:37:39.960
[Guest]: And one of the reasons why I want to find opportunities, because, okay, I mean, I want

01:37:39.960 --> 01:37:41.680
[Guest]: a rule-based system.

01:37:41.680 --> 01:37:46.140
[Guest]: And give me a set of data, I'll find the rules that pattern match that data.

01:37:46.140 --> 01:37:49.040
[Guest]: And then I will say, okay, when this happens, I'm going to do this.

01:37:49.040 --> 01:37:56.240
[Guest]: So a simple thought process is if I take an average, a 10-day average of prices, and let

01:37:56.240 --> 01:38:02.160
[Guest]: me do a simple heuristic rule that says when the price crosses from below that 10-day average,

01:38:02.160 --> 01:38:06.560
[Guest]: because my price could have gone down and below, and it goes back up, I'm going to buy

01:38:06.560 --> 01:38:09.280
[Guest]: the stock, because I expect it to go further up.

01:38:09.280 --> 01:38:13.080
[Guest]: And then maybe at some point when it crosses down below its average again, I'm going to

01:38:13.080 --> 01:38:14.080
[Guest]: sell it.

01:38:14.080 --> 01:38:17.320
[Guest]: This is called a moving average crossover strategy.

01:38:17.320 --> 01:38:21.400
[Guest]: So it's an algorithmic strategy that you can say is a rule.

01:38:21.400 --> 01:38:25.920
[Guest]: And now because it doesn't matter which company this is, it could be this company, it could

01:38:25.920 --> 01:38:28.760
[Guest]: be a hundred other companies, all of them have a price.

01:38:28.760 --> 01:38:31.840
[Guest]: Like aloo has a price, onion has a price, aloo will be different from onion, but both

01:38:31.840 --> 01:38:33.160
[Guest]: prices are prices.

01:38:33.160 --> 01:38:36.400
[Guest]: Over time, you have prices going up or prices going down.

01:38:36.400 --> 01:38:43.360
[Guest]: If I map the prices, I can tell you when this aloo price is likely to go up, and again probabilistically.

01:38:43.360 --> 01:38:49.640
[Guest]: So the algorithmic trading sometimes says, listen, use the price itself or some objective

01:38:49.640 --> 01:38:55.000
[Guest]: factor, not subjective factor, to determine what will come next.

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:57.660
[Guest]: So in a way, it's a short-term prediction.

01:38:57.660 --> 01:39:01.640
[Guest]: But the difference between the prediction is you don't have to be right all the time.

01:39:01.640 --> 01:39:04.640
[Guest]: You don't even have to be right like 80% of the time.

01:39:04.640 --> 01:39:11.240
[Guest]: If you're right 51% of the time and you do enough, you will win.

01:39:11.240 --> 01:39:14.040
[Guest]: Sometimes you have to be right only 10% of the time, and you can be enough.

01:39:14.040 --> 01:39:18.120
[Guest]: And I'll tell you, that's the venture capital model, where they say we'll put our money

01:39:18.120 --> 01:39:23.640
[Guest]: into 10 different companies, and nine of them can go bust, but that one will give me a hundred

01:39:23.640 --> 01:39:25.360
[Guest]: x return.

01:39:25.360 --> 01:39:30.640
[Guest]: And if that one gives me a hundred x return, I earn 10 x on my fund.

01:39:30.640 --> 01:39:32.440
[Guest]: And all I need to find is enough bets.

01:39:32.440 --> 01:39:35.840
[Guest]: So I have a 10% win rate.

01:39:35.840 --> 01:39:42.840
[Guest]: But the odds for me are 100 is to 1 when I win, and 0 when I lose.

01:39:42.840 --> 01:39:49.160
[Guest]: So technically, even a 0.1% bet edge is enough.

01:39:49.160 --> 01:39:50.160
[Guest]: Not 0.1.

01:39:50.160 --> 01:39:54.840
[Guest]: It's 0.1 into 100 times is 10.

01:39:54.840 --> 01:40:01.120
[Guest]: So if I had 100 rupees, I put 10 rupees on each of the 100, on 10 companies.

01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:07.120
[Guest]: And every time I won, it was 100 times what I invested.

01:40:07.120 --> 01:40:08.560
[Guest]: So my 10 would become 1,000.

01:40:08.560 --> 01:40:11.360
[Guest]: So I'd get more than the 100 I invested.

01:40:11.360 --> 01:40:14.600
[Guest]: What if I invested in 100 different companies?

01:40:14.600 --> 01:40:19.640
[Guest]: If I invested in 100 different companies, I would then break even if even one of them

01:40:19.640 --> 01:40:21.560
[Guest]: gave me 100 x.

01:40:21.560 --> 01:40:25.760
[Guest]: So then you find the situation where your edge works for you.

01:40:25.760 --> 01:40:26.760
[Guest]: This is the edge, right?

01:40:26.760 --> 01:40:28.640
[Guest]: So you can program this.

01:40:28.640 --> 01:40:32.760
[Guest]: You could call this an algorithmic strategy where now you're using heuristics, moving

01:40:32.760 --> 01:40:33.760
[Guest]: average.

01:40:33.760 --> 01:40:34.760
[Guest]: I want to try which.

01:40:34.760 --> 01:40:35.760
[Guest]: So which moving average should I use?

01:40:35.760 --> 01:40:39.240
[Guest]: Should I use a 10-day, a 10-hour, a 40-hour?

01:40:39.240 --> 01:40:42.000
[Guest]: Let the computer go figure it out.

01:40:42.000 --> 01:40:44.600
[Guest]: I will tell you that I'm going to use a moving average strategy.

01:40:44.600 --> 01:40:49.200
[Guest]: So do you find out which moving average actually works in the data that I've given you?

01:40:49.200 --> 01:40:53.000
[Guest]: Now you could have something called a curve-fitting process where you say, I've given you three

01:40:53.000 --> 01:40:54.000
[Guest]: years of data.

01:40:54.000 --> 01:40:59.480
[Guest]: Please tell me that the 37th day average is the best, or if you told me that the 37-day

01:40:59.480 --> 01:41:00.480
[Guest]: average is the best.

01:41:00.480 --> 01:41:04.640
[Guest]: But now it could be that the next three years, I see horrible results on this strategy when

01:41:04.640 --> 01:41:06.400
[Guest]: I actually run it with money.

01:41:06.400 --> 01:41:10.400
[Guest]: There's a reason for that is because I've used the data that was best on a certain time

01:41:10.400 --> 01:41:12.720
[Guest]: frame, but not perhaps best overall.

01:41:12.720 --> 01:41:17.800
[Guest]: So I'll test this in other time frames, saying for the last three years, this has done well.

01:41:17.800 --> 01:41:22.120
[Guest]: But maybe three years before that, had I used 37, what would I have got?

01:41:22.120 --> 01:41:24.840
[Guest]: And that was something slightly different.

01:41:24.840 --> 01:41:29.040
[Guest]: And then do I lose too much when that happens, or is my winnings very different?

01:41:29.040 --> 01:41:31.600
[Guest]: So if the answer is no, then I can use that model.

01:41:31.600 --> 01:41:35.060
[Guest]: If the answer is yes, that means I have got something called overfitting.

01:41:35.060 --> 01:41:38.040
[Guest]: So I have to use a different strategy.

01:41:38.040 --> 01:41:40.760
[Guest]: Sometimes this strategy completely fails because it becomes public.

01:41:40.760 --> 01:41:43.120
[Guest]: There was a public experiment called the turtles.

01:41:43.120 --> 01:41:44.300
[Guest]: They're very interesting.

01:41:44.300 --> 01:41:48.440
[Guest]: This is from the movie Trading Places, which originally was Eddie Murphy and a bunch of

01:41:48.440 --> 01:41:49.440
[Guest]: guys.

01:41:49.440 --> 01:41:50.440
[Guest]: There were two guys.

01:41:50.440 --> 01:41:51.440
[Guest]: I forget the other guy's name.

01:41:51.440 --> 01:41:55.680
[Guest]: One guy was called Richard Dennis, very famous guy, he was a Republican supporter at the

01:41:55.680 --> 01:41:56.680
[Guest]: time.

01:41:56.680 --> 01:42:01.360
[Guest]: Nowadays, it's a bad thing to be called a Republican supporter, I guess.

01:42:01.360 --> 01:42:07.040
[Guest]: But interestingly, what happened that time was he had an argument with his friend.

01:42:07.040 --> 01:42:12.120
[Guest]: He said, that guy said, listen, it takes art to invest well.

01:42:12.120 --> 01:42:15.200
[Guest]: So this guy said, no, it's skill.

01:42:15.200 --> 01:42:16.520
[Guest]: Richard Dennis said, it's skill.

01:42:16.520 --> 01:42:17.520
[Guest]: It's not art.

01:42:17.520 --> 01:42:19.600
[Guest]: It is a rule-based game.

01:42:19.600 --> 01:42:20.600
[Guest]: So they disagreed.

01:42:20.600 --> 01:42:22.360
[Guest]: They said, listen, let's do a bet.

01:42:22.360 --> 01:42:25.280
[Guest]: And he says, yes, I'll do you this bet.

01:42:25.280 --> 01:42:31.040
[Guest]: I will train traders like they breed turtles in Singapore, which is in a farm.

01:42:31.040 --> 01:42:35.440
[Guest]: You just put them into a cage and then they breed them.

01:42:35.440 --> 01:42:40.480
[Guest]: So he put out an advertisement saying, listen, if you don't have a trading or a finance background,

01:42:40.480 --> 01:42:41.480
[Guest]: that's even better.

01:42:41.480 --> 01:42:45.800
[Guest]: I want you to come and I'll train you and I'll help you learn how to trade.

01:42:45.800 --> 01:42:48.800
[Guest]: And you're going to trade my money.

01:42:48.800 --> 01:42:54.080
[Guest]: So he called these people, literally picked them off the street, gave them a set of rules

01:42:54.080 --> 01:42:57.400
[Guest]: and said, this is all you're going to do.

01:42:57.400 --> 01:43:00.080
[Guest]: Those rules made a lot of money.

01:43:00.080 --> 01:43:05.920
[Guest]: Until I think from 1980 something to 1992, these people made truckloads of money for

01:43:05.920 --> 01:43:06.920
[Guest]: him.

01:43:06.920 --> 01:43:09.860
[Guest]: They went around, some of them became very famous traders by themselves.

01:43:09.860 --> 01:43:15.640
[Guest]: One of them is writing books and a bunch of things now and also has been a successful

01:43:15.640 --> 01:43:16.640
[Guest]: trader.

01:43:16.640 --> 01:43:22.740
[Guest]: So interestingly, after 92, they actually published this in a book.

01:43:22.740 --> 01:43:27.400
[Guest]: And since then, the rules stopped working because enough people had figured out that

01:43:27.400 --> 01:43:29.040
[Guest]: you could put this into an algorithm.

01:43:29.040 --> 01:43:33.880
[Guest]: And then once you have enough people playing the game, then you don't have enough money

01:43:33.880 --> 01:43:34.880
[Guest]: left in the game.

01:43:34.880 --> 01:43:39.080
[Guest]: So sometimes the rules will change because people have either figured them out, the markets

01:43:39.080 --> 01:43:41.400
[Guest]: have figured them out, things are changing.

01:43:41.400 --> 01:43:44.960
[Guest]: So when you write a program in algorithmic trading, you're going to have to incorporate

01:43:44.960 --> 01:43:48.360
[Guest]: all of these curve fitting, backtesting, how you're going to test, how you're going to

01:43:48.360 --> 01:43:53.240
[Guest]: get real data because a company's price can be 50 today, it can suddenly fall to 10 rupees

01:43:53.240 --> 01:43:54.240
[Guest]: tomorrow.

01:43:54.240 --> 01:43:59.000
[Guest]: So do you know that it's actually fallen 80% or is it a stock split of one is to five that's

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:00.720
[Guest]: caused the price to fall?

01:44:00.720 --> 01:44:05.200
[Guest]: So you need somebody to go and adjust that data and make sure that the data is clean.

01:44:05.200 --> 01:44:07.160
[Guest]: This part of this process is another part.

01:44:07.160 --> 01:44:13.440
[Guest]: So we figured over through the school of hard knocks, perhaps, that things aren't exactly

01:44:13.440 --> 01:44:14.440
[Guest]: the way they seem.

01:44:14.440 --> 01:44:17.920
[Guest]: So you have to fix the data, you have to write the algorithm, you have to ensure that you're

01:44:17.920 --> 01:44:22.760
[Guest]: not doing survivorship bias, curve fitting.

01:44:22.760 --> 01:44:26.040
[Guest]: You also have these loss aversion problems in algorithmic systems.

01:44:26.040 --> 01:44:30.480
[Guest]: So you can design a system that's great, like this concept of VCs, where you lose on nine

01:44:30.480 --> 01:44:35.280
[Guest]: companies but win on only one, it takes a different mentality.

01:44:35.280 --> 01:44:40.120
[Guest]: Imagine losing nine consecutive times before that one big winner, you'd have given lost

01:44:40.120 --> 01:44:41.920
[Guest]: hearts somewhere.

01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:47.800
[Guest]: And if you have this concept, the loss aversion might end up saying, because in the stock

01:44:47.800 --> 01:44:52.560
[Guest]: market, you can get out anytime you want, right, you just put a sell order in your own.

01:44:52.560 --> 01:44:55.240
[Guest]: That's equivalent to folding your hand and taking your chips and walking away.

01:44:55.240 --> 01:45:02.040
[Guest]: So you could quit just before the stock just breaks out and gives you 100 bucks, 100x return,

01:45:02.040 --> 01:45:03.920
[Guest]: and you'd have missed all of it.

01:45:03.920 --> 01:45:09.400
[Guest]: So you have to build that algorithm in a way that does not give you nine consecutive losses,

01:45:09.400 --> 01:45:12.280
[Guest]: unless that's the kind of person you are and you can handle it.

01:45:12.280 --> 01:45:16.600
[Guest]: So you find out what somebody calls their uncle point.

01:45:16.600 --> 01:45:20.600
[Guest]: It's the point at which you call your uncle for help.

01:45:20.600 --> 01:45:26.760
[Guest]: So you find out what your uncle point is, like if I've lost 30% of my money, is that

01:45:26.760 --> 01:45:27.760
[Guest]: my uncle point?

01:45:27.760 --> 01:45:29.680
[Guest]: And then I don't want to lose 30%.

01:45:29.680 --> 01:45:35.360
[Guest]: So find anything that corresponds to a less than 30% loss on my overall portfolio.

01:45:35.360 --> 01:45:40.120
[Guest]: And so I'm going to find systems that work, but that work with a less than 30% loss in

01:45:40.120 --> 01:45:43.360
[Guest]: the interim, before I started to make money.

01:45:43.360 --> 01:45:46.520
[Guest]: So I'm going to make these bets based on these programs.

01:45:46.520 --> 01:45:51.440
[Guest]: But this is still a heuristic based logic, you may use computers to do back tests, you

01:45:51.440 --> 01:45:55.960
[Guest]: may use, but still heuristic based, you're giving it the rules, and it's kind of testing

01:45:55.960 --> 01:45:59.760
[Guest]: the rules and implementing them and then saying, listen, you're running this rule, I'm going

01:45:59.760 --> 01:46:01.720
[Guest]: to run according to this rule set.

01:46:01.720 --> 01:46:05.720
[Guest]: What if you went one step ahead and said, I don't know the rules.

01:46:05.720 --> 01:46:10.000
[Guest]: Dear computer, please go and figure out what rules work.

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:15.840
[Guest]: And then you might find that the computer throws out some very strange things at you.

01:46:15.840 --> 01:46:17.480
[Guest]: And this has happened to me a lot.

01:46:17.480 --> 01:46:22.960
[Guest]: So for instance, the natural tendency that when people see a stock hitting a new high

01:46:22.960 --> 01:46:30.360
[Guest]: has been always and this is regardless of, it's going to fall, because it's run up too

01:46:30.360 --> 01:46:31.360
[Guest]: much.

01:46:31.360 --> 01:46:33.560
[Guest]: How can you buy at this price?

01:46:33.560 --> 01:46:39.840
[Guest]: And I've come to the point where my mind now says, if it's going up, okay, think of it

01:46:39.840 --> 01:46:44.440
[Guest]: in a way you buy a stock because its stock price will go up.

01:46:44.440 --> 01:46:48.300
[Guest]: This is precisely what it has done.

01:46:48.300 --> 01:46:54.720
[Guest]: And so why are you penalizing it by not buying any more of it or by selling it or by not

01:46:54.720 --> 01:46:58.040
[Guest]: buying a stock that's making a new high because it's doing exactly what it's supposed to do.

01:46:58.040 --> 01:47:03.360
[Guest]: It's supposed to go where no man has gone before and or woman for that matter.

01:47:03.360 --> 01:47:05.920
[Guest]: And you know, if it's there, why aren't you buying it?

01:47:05.920 --> 01:47:11.120
[Guest]: The answer usually is counterintuitive because we don't, this is where momentum also comes

01:47:11.120 --> 01:47:12.120
[Guest]: in.

01:47:12.120 --> 01:47:16.780
[Guest]: But I come to momentum at a later point, talk about ML, machine learning, the machine can

01:47:16.780 --> 01:47:22.240
[Guest]: go in and figure out what actually made sense was to buy stocks, which are making new highs

01:47:22.240 --> 01:47:23.240
[Guest]: and buy a lot of these stocks.

01:47:23.240 --> 01:47:25.640
[Guest]: And you might look at this and say, this is so counterintuitive.

01:47:25.640 --> 01:47:27.160
[Guest]: Why would I buy these stocks?

01:47:27.160 --> 01:47:30.200
[Guest]: The answer seems to be that yes, new high.

01:47:30.200 --> 01:47:32.440
[Guest]: Now you can go back and justify it.

01:47:32.440 --> 01:47:37.520
[Guest]: I can tell you that if a stock is making new highs, you know what's happening is that,

01:47:37.520 --> 01:47:40.400
[Guest]: you know, it probably made a high at some point, then it fell.

01:47:40.400 --> 01:47:43.960
[Guest]: There are people who bought at that high who have that same loss aversion problem.

01:47:43.960 --> 01:47:48.320
[Guest]: They don't want to sell on the way down, but their mind is, when it comes back to this

01:47:48.320 --> 01:47:50.800
[Guest]: price, I'll get out and I'll get it even.

01:47:50.800 --> 01:47:54.240
[Guest]: So the price goes back there, they sell, the price maybe corrects a little more and then

01:47:54.240 --> 01:47:55.440
[Guest]: comes back further up.

01:47:55.440 --> 01:48:01.960
[Guest]: So it has gone beyond the point where the last guys who bought at the last high have,

01:48:01.960 --> 01:48:05.480
[Guest]: you know, kind of decided to sell and get out at even.

01:48:05.480 --> 01:48:09.040
[Guest]: When it crosses that level, you have uncharted territory.

01:48:09.040 --> 01:48:12.840
[Guest]: You have people who are buying, who literally are saying the price is going even further

01:48:12.840 --> 01:48:16.720
[Guest]: from this because it's never even, and it's never even been here before.

01:48:16.720 --> 01:48:23.240
[Guest]: So the logic here is that only stocks that are making new great things tend to be here

01:48:23.240 --> 01:48:27.660
[Guest]: at a point where nobody has bought it earlier.

01:48:27.660 --> 01:48:31.720
[Guest]: And if you build a portfolio of such stocks, the odds that you will make much more than

01:48:31.720 --> 01:48:32.720
[Guest]: you lose.

01:48:32.720 --> 01:48:33.720
[Guest]: And when do you lose?

01:48:33.720 --> 01:48:39.340
[Guest]: You lose when perhaps when a stock kind of corrects more than 10%.

01:48:39.340 --> 01:48:44.960
[Guest]: So if you went and did an ML algorithm, you might find that this is one of the counterintuitive

01:48:44.960 --> 01:48:51.160
[Guest]: things that it does, or you could discover a completely new thing where you don't even

01:48:51.160 --> 01:48:56.820
[Guest]: know what it is using to decide because the intermediate structure that it has figured

01:48:56.820 --> 01:49:03.440
[Guest]: out of what makes or breaks stock is in a format that is incomprehensible to you.

01:49:03.440 --> 01:49:08.120
[Guest]: Now, it's like saying, if I wanted to, okay, this is probably more true than anything else,

01:49:08.120 --> 01:49:12.760
[Guest]: but apparently recently there has been an attempt to make a translator, a universal

01:49:12.760 --> 01:49:13.760
[Guest]: translator.

01:49:13.760 --> 01:49:17.800
[Guest]: A universal translator would be where you could give in a lot of languages and it would

01:49:17.800 --> 01:49:21.760
[Guest]: be able to translate all of those languages to any other language.

01:49:21.760 --> 01:49:25.320
[Guest]: Give it, let it learn, let the machine learn on its own.

01:49:25.320 --> 01:49:28.480
[Guest]: So apparently one such test, and I don't know how to, this is a friend who told me this

01:49:28.480 --> 01:49:33.560
[Guest]: and he's pretty knowledgeable in this subject, but he says, Deepak, they went in and then

01:49:33.560 --> 01:49:39.040
[Guest]: they built this thing, they trained it, they put so much machinery behind it that it was

01:49:39.040 --> 01:49:44.000
[Guest]: a multi-machine system, so you could have a hundred machines doing the same kind of

01:49:44.000 --> 01:49:45.000
[Guest]: processing.

01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:50.680
[Guest]: Eventually, this machine figured out that they could take any language and break it

01:49:50.680 --> 01:49:55.300
[Guest]: into this intermediate language that it had, then if you use that intermediate language

01:49:55.300 --> 01:49:57.540
[Guest]: to translate into any other language.

01:49:57.540 --> 01:50:01.320
[Guest]: So the machine figured this out, right?

01:50:01.320 --> 01:50:08.280
[Guest]: And then there were multiple machines, and when they start transmitting this intermediate

01:50:08.280 --> 01:50:14.600
[Guest]: language bytes to each other, these guys realized that, holy shit, they're talking to each other,

01:50:14.600 --> 01:50:18.360
[Guest]: they're computers, they're talking to each other in a language we don't understand.

01:50:18.360 --> 01:50:21.200
[Amit Varma]: We have no idea what they're saying to each other.

01:50:21.200 --> 01:50:22.680
[Guest]: They shut it down.

01:50:22.680 --> 01:50:33.880
[Guest]: And this is like the Silicon Valley theme thing and all that, but it's true that eventually

01:50:33.880 --> 01:50:39.120
[Guest]: stuff will happen that is downright scary, and it's already scary for many of us.

01:50:39.120 --> 01:50:45.000
[Guest]: I mean, I could say, sometimes I just say, okay, and my phone says, hi, what did you

01:50:45.000 --> 01:50:46.000
[Guest]: just say?

01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:49.760
[Guest]: Because it's looking for, okay, Google or something like that.

01:50:49.760 --> 01:50:57.560
[Guest]: So the problem really is that you don't know right now how much things are happening without

01:50:57.560 --> 01:51:02.280
[Guest]: even the heuristics of a human are leading it.

01:51:02.280 --> 01:51:07.760
[Guest]: It could be the machines that, and I'm not afraid of it, and I know that it's eventually

01:51:07.760 --> 01:51:13.680
[Guest]: going to happen, but it's amazing how far this can get, and this can get there in computers

01:51:13.680 --> 01:51:15.400
[Guest]: as well, where they've kind of figured it out.

01:51:15.400 --> 01:51:19.880
[Guest]: In the end, dude, whatever you do, all you'll do is either make me money or lose money,

01:51:19.880 --> 01:51:20.880
[Guest]: and I can control that.

01:51:20.880 --> 01:51:23.200
[Guest]: I can shut you down when you're losing me too much money.

01:51:23.200 --> 01:51:27.240
[Guest]: So in the algorithmic world, they said, go ahead, go do whatever the hell you want.

01:51:27.240 --> 01:51:31.240
[Guest]: You want to build an intermediate language, you want to analyze Twitter feeds and figure

01:51:31.240 --> 01:51:34.680
[Guest]: out which stock is going to move tomorrow, go ahead and do it.

01:51:34.680 --> 01:51:39.520
[Guest]: So ML over there is basically saying our older ways of judgment.

01:51:39.520 --> 01:51:45.160
[Guest]: Now, what's interesting is that George Soros thing of reflexivity.

01:51:45.160 --> 01:51:52.280
[Guest]: The more people that use algorithms to determine a certain pattern, the more likely it is that

01:51:52.280 --> 01:51:57.000
[Guest]: if I know that this is the pattern you're going to recognize, that I can write a program

01:51:57.000 --> 01:51:59.400
[Guest]: to beat that.

01:51:59.400 --> 01:52:04.360
[Guest]: It effectively means that I could build my machine, which is entirely built to beat your

01:52:04.360 --> 01:52:05.360
[Guest]: machine.

01:52:05.360 --> 01:52:09.480
[Guest]: It's not meant to beat you, but all I have to know that there's an, I'll give you an

01:52:09.480 --> 01:52:10.480
[Guest]: example of this.

01:52:10.480 --> 01:52:15.680
[Guest]: There's an algorithm written in the U.S. for people who want to sell a large number of

01:52:15.680 --> 01:52:16.680
[Guest]: stocks.

01:52:16.680 --> 01:52:20.280
[Guest]: Because if I have like 10 million shares of some company to sell, I am not going to be

01:52:20.280 --> 01:52:24.000
[Guest]: able to sell them because the minute I start telling my broker, I need to sell these shares,

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:28.440
[Guest]: the broker's going to tell all his clients, dump this because this Deepak Chennai is selling

01:52:28.440 --> 01:52:32.520
[Guest]: 10 million shares of it, and before I sell all of his, I want you to get out because

01:52:32.520 --> 01:52:34.760
[Guest]: he's going to destroy the price.

01:52:34.760 --> 01:52:36.080
[Guest]: So I don't want him to front run it.

01:52:36.080 --> 01:52:39.080
[Guest]: So I get a terminal of my own and start putting orders.

01:52:39.080 --> 01:52:42.760
[Guest]: And if I start, I suddenly realized that I can't do this because it's too much time.

01:52:42.760 --> 01:52:48.920
[Guest]: I buy a computer algorithm and one of the algorithms that did this was to sell shares

01:52:48.920 --> 01:52:55.080
[Guest]: at odd intervals, it would send 100 shares at a time, at even intervals it would send

01:52:55.080 --> 01:52:56.080
[Guest]: 500.

01:52:56.080 --> 01:53:00.000
[Guest]: So it would rotate between 100, 500, 100, 500.

01:53:00.000 --> 01:53:05.840
[Guest]: There was a computer program written to just detect this pattern of 100 and 500 so that

01:53:05.840 --> 01:53:08.400
[Guest]: they could game it.

01:53:08.400 --> 01:53:13.960
[Guest]: So finance is evil, okay, and we have no idea how evil because I can tell you that there

01:53:13.960 --> 01:53:16.400
[Guest]: are no morals and no scruples in this industry.

01:53:16.400 --> 01:53:21.920
[Guest]: So people will do this if they were widows and orphans involved because they don't care.

01:53:21.920 --> 01:53:28.560
[Guest]: And we've seen this in Enron, a bunch of these things, but these are legit programs.

01:53:28.560 --> 01:53:32.880
[Guest]: And they were written with that particular philosophy of saying, my only job is to zip

01:53:32.880 --> 01:53:34.280
[Guest]: the other guy.

01:53:34.280 --> 01:53:41.040
[Guest]: And so you get the machine learning on the machine learning kind of algorithms as well.

01:53:41.040 --> 01:53:43.760
[Guest]: So it can get quite deep in that.

01:53:43.760 --> 01:53:46.440
[Guest]: What we figured out is, listen, we don't want to do all of that stuff.

01:53:46.440 --> 01:53:55.040
[Guest]: Not because it's a very complex argument of why, but I think what makes sense and a lot

01:53:55.040 --> 01:54:01.440
[Guest]: of sense to people is because when you do something that is algorithmic, very high frequency

01:54:01.440 --> 01:54:08.920
[Guest]: and all of that stuff, you introduce layers of taxation, layers of, you know, economic

01:54:08.920 --> 01:54:18.600
[Guest]: value, transaction costs, and all of that stuff that kind of hurt a person's return.

01:54:18.600 --> 01:54:23.680
[Guest]: Managing money for somebody else, you want a strategy that doesn't trade too much, but

01:54:23.680 --> 01:54:29.560
[Guest]: also at the same time has some kind of system behind it.

01:54:29.560 --> 01:54:34.680
[Guest]: If I follow the system consistently over time, I will make enough money.

01:54:34.680 --> 01:54:38.960
[Guest]: Sometimes it's the algorithm, the way the algorithm is accepted, the momentum is one

01:54:38.960 --> 01:54:45.160
[Guest]: of these things which have this weird problem that people don't seem to understand it.

01:54:45.160 --> 01:54:46.160
[Guest]: It's very counterintuitive.

01:54:46.160 --> 01:54:51.400
[Guest]: Like I said, a stock making a new high is in momentum and you should buy it.

01:54:51.400 --> 01:54:52.560
[Guest]: Why should you buy it?

01:54:52.560 --> 01:54:58.000
[Guest]: Because if you look at the system and test it backwards, the odds of winning or how much

01:54:58.000 --> 01:55:03.000
[Guest]: you make when you win is higher if you have the right strategy than how much you lose

01:55:03.000 --> 01:55:04.000
[Guest]: when you lose.

01:55:04.000 --> 01:55:05.480
[Guest]: And the strategy is simple.

01:55:05.480 --> 01:55:07.040
[Guest]: Just keep buying the highest momentum stocks.

01:55:07.040 --> 01:55:11.400
[Guest]: When the stock loses momentum, replace it with one that has a higher momentum.

01:55:11.400 --> 01:55:20.760
[Guest]: So over time, if your edge here is that, if there's no edge, it's 50-50, let's say.

01:55:20.760 --> 01:55:24.640
[Guest]: But you still make more when you win than you lose when you lose.

01:55:24.640 --> 01:55:31.080
[Guest]: At the extreme, you can only lose 100% of what you put in a stock, but you can make

01:55:31.080 --> 01:55:33.040
[Guest]: 300%.

01:55:33.040 --> 01:55:39.360
[Guest]: So if you only had binary win or lose, all you needed is a few winners and you would

01:55:39.360 --> 01:55:45.080
[Guest]: still make more money than you lose because you can win more than 2x or more than 1x when

01:55:45.080 --> 01:55:46.080
[Guest]: you win.

01:55:46.080 --> 01:55:53.000
[Guest]: So momentum is simply that embodied into a strategy where it says, I will discover which

01:55:53.000 --> 01:55:57.800
[Guest]: stocks are moving and they are more likely to give me outsized returns.

01:55:57.800 --> 01:56:02.120
[Guest]: Not more likely to win, but to give me outsized returns and the losses are controlled because

01:56:02.120 --> 01:56:04.320
[Guest]: I get out when they lose momentum.

01:56:04.320 --> 01:56:07.800
[Guest]: So when they lose momentum, they would have lost only 10% or 15%, but when they win, they

01:56:07.800 --> 01:56:09.920
[Guest]: give me 40-50%.

01:56:09.920 --> 01:56:14.440
[Guest]: On average, over a long period of time, I will make money.

01:56:14.440 --> 01:56:22.480
[Guest]: This is a very simple philosophy and we know what we call indexes are embodiments of momentum

01:56:22.480 --> 01:56:23.480
[Guest]: in a different way.

01:56:23.480 --> 01:56:25.360
[Guest]: What are our biggest stocks?

01:56:25.360 --> 01:56:30.600
[Guest]: In India today, the biggest stocks are Reliance, TCS, HDFC, HDFC Bank.

01:56:30.600 --> 01:56:34.000
[Guest]: 20 years ago, there was still Reliance, but there was no TCS.

01:56:34.000 --> 01:56:38.200
[Guest]: There was probably Hindustan Unilever, which was one of the top most stocks.

01:56:38.200 --> 01:56:40.920
[Guest]: So why did they change over time?

01:56:40.920 --> 01:56:45.600
[Guest]: The answer is that the market capitalization of these stocks changed.

01:56:45.600 --> 01:56:51.320
[Guest]: Now an inferior TCS weren't the top market cap stocks at about 20 years ago.

01:56:51.320 --> 01:56:53.240
[Guest]: They may be so today.

01:56:53.240 --> 01:57:00.000
[Guest]: So over time, the momentum in market cap made them as part of this index.

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:07.040
[Guest]: Reliance is the highest market cap stock today, but five or six years ago, it was TCS.

01:57:07.040 --> 01:57:12.960
[Guest]: If you look at the US, Amazon or Apple have shared the mantle of the highest market cap

01:57:12.960 --> 01:57:13.960
[Guest]: stock.

01:57:13.960 --> 01:57:18.280
[Guest]: 20 years ago, it was Exxon, and 20 years before that, it was something else.

01:57:18.280 --> 01:57:23.320
[Guest]: So the leaders have changed, but what has happened really is that each of them has had

01:57:23.320 --> 01:57:26.280
[Guest]: momentum in market cap.

01:57:26.280 --> 01:57:30.920
[Guest]: The total number of shares they own multiplied by their stock price is the market cap.

01:57:30.920 --> 01:57:34.640
[Guest]: The company, the most valuable companies have floated to the top.

01:57:34.640 --> 01:57:38.320
[Guest]: So you've taken a moment, and this is there everywhere.

01:57:38.320 --> 01:57:42.480
[Guest]: If Virat Kohli is in form, it's a form of momentum.

01:57:42.480 --> 01:57:52.640
[Guest]: It means that it makes sense to bet on him on every subsequent match simply because he's

01:57:52.640 --> 01:57:53.760
[Guest]: in form.

01:57:53.760 --> 01:57:56.880
[Guest]: And sometimes being in form itself is a factor.

01:57:56.880 --> 01:57:58.540
[Guest]: It's a reflexive factor.

01:57:58.540 --> 01:58:01.600
[Guest]: If you are in form, you have confidence.

01:58:01.600 --> 01:58:06.920
[Guest]: If you have confidence, the chances that you will get unnerved when something bad happens

01:58:06.920 --> 01:58:08.840
[Guest]: to you is slightly lesser.

01:58:08.840 --> 01:58:14.320
[Guest]: One good ball, and that confidence starts to show in your batting, in subsequent things.

01:58:14.320 --> 01:58:18.000
[Guest]: Your shoulders droop a little bit lesser, you stand up a little bit straighter, you

01:58:18.000 --> 01:58:22.000
[Guest]: get your stance a little bit better, you're less nervous.

01:58:22.000 --> 01:58:25.120
[Guest]: That contributes to your playing better, and that increases your form again.

01:58:25.120 --> 01:58:29.360
[Guest]: So the form kind of positive feedbacks itself and leads you on.

01:58:29.360 --> 01:58:31.280
[Guest]: The same thing happens to a company.

01:58:31.280 --> 01:58:32.280
[Guest]: Company does well.

01:58:32.280 --> 01:58:35.320
[Guest]: Its customers look and say, your stock is doing really well.

01:58:35.320 --> 01:58:39.400
[Guest]: And you're looking at them and saying, our stock is doing really well, we'll give you

01:58:39.400 --> 01:58:40.520
[Guest]: more money.

01:58:40.520 --> 01:58:41.520
[Guest]: So he gets more money.

01:58:41.520 --> 01:58:46.240
[Guest]: Obviously, people say, dude, the stock is good because the stock price is going up because

01:58:46.240 --> 01:58:48.120
[Guest]: the company is making more money.

01:58:48.120 --> 01:58:51.800
[Guest]: But nobody says the company's making more money because the stock price is going up.

01:58:51.800 --> 01:58:55.120
[Guest]: And that factor, it's not sexy.

01:58:55.120 --> 01:58:59.360
[Guest]: So people don't like to say it, but sometimes that adds to it.

01:58:59.360 --> 01:59:01.000
[Guest]: It's the form that adds to form.

01:59:01.000 --> 01:59:07.320
[Guest]: It's the momentum that adds to business sometimes, which is also another layer why businesses

01:59:07.320 --> 01:59:14.240
[Guest]: that are in great momentum in the stock market sometimes have an irrationally good effect

01:59:14.240 --> 01:59:17.860
[Guest]: on their underlying business potential as well.

01:59:17.860 --> 01:59:23.800
[Guest]: So this strategy, of course, I justify it in hindsight, perhaps.

01:59:23.800 --> 01:59:28.240
[Guest]: And though I'm not the first person there, the momentum has been a thing that's happening

01:59:28.240 --> 01:59:29.240
[Guest]: forever.

01:59:29.240 --> 01:59:31.800
[Guest]: I say it like my kids love Formula One.

01:59:31.800 --> 01:59:33.600
[Guest]: I used to love Formula One.

01:59:33.600 --> 01:59:37.600
[Guest]: I still like Formula One a lot, but I don't have the patience to sit through three hours

01:59:37.600 --> 01:59:41.240
[Guest]: of car race as much as I did when I was younger.

01:59:41.240 --> 01:59:44.520
[Guest]: But when I was younger, it was Michael Schumacher and Ferrari.

01:59:44.520 --> 01:59:46.760
[Guest]: So I have this fond love for Ferrari.

01:59:46.760 --> 01:59:50.400
[Guest]: And I keep saying this to other people, saying, I love Ferrari.

01:59:50.400 --> 01:59:52.280
[Guest]: So I ask my kids, why don't you like Ferrari?

01:59:52.280 --> 01:59:55.680
[Guest]: Why do you like this Lewis Hamilton of Mercedes?

01:59:55.680 --> 01:59:57.600
[Guest]: They say, because he wins.

01:59:57.600 --> 01:59:58.600
[Guest]: And that's the answer.

01:59:58.600 --> 01:59:59.600
[Guest]: The momentum.

01:59:59.600 --> 02:00:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Actually, everything you said is very fascinating, and I'll unpack different parts of it.

02:00:04.000 --> 02:00:07.360
[Amit Varma]: But I'll throw in a couple of minor disagreements with the things that you said right at the

02:00:07.360 --> 02:00:08.360
[Amit Varma]: end.

02:00:08.360 --> 02:00:12.240
[Amit Varma]: For example, with sports, I think, you know, I've seen studies that people form sporting

02:00:12.240 --> 02:00:17.480
[Amit Varma]: loyalties towards those teams or individuals who are doing well when they are at a certain

02:00:17.480 --> 02:00:22.000
[Amit Varma]: age when they are beginning to follow a sport, maybe 13, 14, or maybe later when they begin

02:00:22.000 --> 02:00:23.260
[Amit Varma]: to follow something.

02:00:23.260 --> 02:00:28.640
[Amit Varma]: So it's natural that, you know, you would remember Schumacher and Ferrari fondly and, you know,

02:00:28.640 --> 02:00:32.840
[Amit Varma]: and just from seeing who's an Arsenal fan, I can make out how old they are.

02:00:32.840 --> 02:00:36.360
[Amit Varma]: Because it means that, you know, those were Arsenal's peak years under Arsene Wenger.

02:00:36.360 --> 02:00:41.800
[Amit Varma]: And that is why, you know, today, you know, you might have people liking different teams.

02:00:41.800 --> 02:00:46.920
[Amit Varma]: So why Indians would, you know, have such a hardcore loyalty for these British football

02:00:46.920 --> 02:00:48.760
[Amit Varma]: teams completely baffles me.

02:00:48.760 --> 02:00:52.720
[Amit Varma]: As far as momentum is concerned, I'd actually say cricket and sports is the wrong example

02:00:52.720 --> 02:00:53.720
[Amit Varma]: to use.

02:00:53.720 --> 02:00:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Because I think when we talk of form, and when we talk of momentum in sport, you are

02:00:58.480 --> 02:01:00.000
[Amit Varma]: absolutely right about your domain.

02:01:00.000 --> 02:01:05.240
[Amit Varma]: But in sport, when we talk about it, I think we are often imposing narratives in hindsight,

02:01:05.240 --> 02:01:08.880
[Amit Varma]: that in hindsight, we can look back and say, ki haan yaar yeh form mein tha.

02:01:08.880 --> 02:01:11.480
[Amit Varma]: And we define that period by when it ended.

02:01:11.480 --> 02:01:13.440
[Amit Varma]: But that is a narrative in hindsight.

02:01:13.440 --> 02:01:17.120
[Amit Varma]: In the moment, there's really no such thing, which is why, you know, the sports illustrated

02:01:17.120 --> 02:01:18.120
[Amit Varma]: jinx comes up.

02:01:18.120 --> 02:01:21.720
[Amit Varma]: The sports illustrated jinx, of course, is that, you know, the moment you put someone

02:01:21.720 --> 02:01:24.920
[Amit Varma]: on the cover of sports illustrated, their career goes downwards.

02:01:24.920 --> 02:01:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And the reason it happens is that, you know, they were on a lucky streak at that time,

02:01:29.120 --> 02:01:31.560
[Amit Varma]: which you could ascribe to form or whatever.

02:01:31.560 --> 02:01:34.720
[Amit Varma]: And you basically put them on the cover when they were at their peak, and then there was

02:01:34.720 --> 02:01:36.540
[Amit Varma]: a regression to the mean.

02:01:36.540 --> 02:01:39.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it appeared that that is a curse, and it isn't.

02:01:39.480 --> 02:01:44.240
[Guest]: Yeah, in fact, I've limited let me tell you that, in fact, that is exactly what it isn't.

02:01:44.240 --> 02:01:48.640
[Guest]: The reason why I'm saying it's not different is because we call we have something called

02:01:48.640 --> 02:01:55.160
[Guest]: loyalties, which is stupid, in a momentum theory, you have no loyalties, you have only

02:01:55.160 --> 02:02:00.840
[Guest]: loyalties to momentum, which means I will go so I will go with the Roger Federer as

02:02:00.840 --> 02:02:02.620
[Guest]: long as he's winning.

02:02:02.620 --> 02:02:04.640
[Guest]: And sometimes he's winning because he's winning.

02:02:04.640 --> 02:02:05.640
[Guest]: I don't care.

02:02:05.640 --> 02:02:10.720
[Guest]: I form no loyalties to tomorrow, he gets beaten by Nadal, I will go to Nadal, if he gets beaten

02:02:10.720 --> 02:02:11.720
[Guest]: by the next guy.

02:02:11.720 --> 02:02:14.800
[Guest]: Sometimes I don't know who the new latest players are in the first place.

02:02:14.800 --> 02:02:19.360
[Guest]: But let's say somebody else comes in and there was a time I was a big Boris Becker fan.

02:02:19.360 --> 02:02:20.880
[Guest]: I was an Ivan Lendl fan.

02:02:20.880 --> 02:02:24.280
[Guest]: And to be fair, I was more an Ivan Lendl fan than a Boris Becker fan.

02:02:24.280 --> 02:02:27.080
[Guest]: But that didn't work out quite as well.

02:02:27.080 --> 02:02:30.920
[Guest]: And I was a big Steffi Graf fan and big Serena Williams fan.

02:02:30.920 --> 02:02:35.960
[Guest]: But in tennis, I found it easy to kind of not have loyalties.

02:02:35.960 --> 02:02:40.720
[Amit Varma]: In fact, since you bring up tennis players of that era, I remember, I once saw this interview

02:02:40.720 --> 02:02:44.480
[Amit Varma]: when Jim Courier was doing really well, he won a couple of Grand Slam tournaments.

02:02:44.480 --> 02:02:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And at that time, Pete Sampras had just become number one in the world, but hadn't yet won

02:02:48.240 --> 02:02:53.040
[Amit Varma]: his first Grand Slam tournament, which I think was a US Open, which he went on to win.

02:02:53.040 --> 02:02:57.000
[Amit Varma]: So Courier was asked that you are winning all these Grand Slams, but you know, Sampras

02:02:57.000 --> 02:02:58.000
[Amit Varma]: is world number one.

02:02:58.000 --> 02:03:01.480
[Amit Varma]: He said world number one doesn't matter, tell him to win some Grand Slams first.

02:03:01.480 --> 02:03:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And then I think Sampras won the very next one.

02:03:04.680 --> 02:03:08.240
[Amit Varma]: And then history just unfolded.

02:03:08.240 --> 02:03:14.400
[Amit Varma]: My sort of clarification to the whole momentum thing is, is it the case that humans are basically

02:03:14.400 --> 02:03:18.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, the anchoring effect takes place, that you see a stock at a particular point,

02:03:18.400 --> 02:03:21.920
[Amit Varma]: say it's 100 rupees, it goes to 110, you are anchored to the 100.

02:03:21.920 --> 02:03:27.160
[Amit Varma]: So in relative to that 110 seems high, and you're like, might as well sell now, while

02:03:27.160 --> 02:03:31.120
[Amit Varma]: actually it doesn't matter that every single time you look at a stock, you should do a

02:03:31.120 --> 02:03:33.140
[Amit Varma]: clean reset in your head.

02:03:33.140 --> 02:03:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, not refer to previous prices, but in fact, refer to previous trends like

02:03:39.240 --> 02:03:40.240
[Amit Varma]: the momentum.

02:03:40.240 --> 02:03:43.760
[Amit Varma]: And what you're saying is that that is more indicative of what is going to happen to the

02:03:43.760 --> 02:03:45.200
[Amit Varma]: stock tomorrow.

02:03:45.200 --> 02:03:49.640
[Amit Varma]: And if that momentum is an upward momentum, then just speaking of probabilities, it is

02:03:49.640 --> 02:03:53.080
[Amit Varma]: likelier to go up than to go down and vice versa.

02:03:53.080 --> 02:03:54.080
[Guest]: Is that?

02:03:54.080 --> 02:03:55.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:03:55.080 --> 02:03:57.960
[Guest]: So interesting, you know, you bring that up, because this is actually one of the biggest

02:03:57.960 --> 02:04:03.440
[Guest]: problems that you have, as a trader yourself, you will buy a stock at 100, and you sell

02:04:03.440 --> 02:04:04.960
[Guest]: it at 120.

02:04:04.960 --> 02:04:06.480
[Guest]: This is a curse.

02:04:06.480 --> 02:04:10.000
[Guest]: Because you've made this 20 rupees and you're damn good with yourself, but I'll tell you

02:04:10.000 --> 02:04:11.000
[Guest]: why it's a curse.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:15.760
[Guest]: Because let's say the stock falls back to 90, you are thinking of yourself as this hero.

02:04:15.760 --> 02:04:20.560
[Guest]: Boss, I bought it at 100, I sold it at 120, I am the boss and all that.

02:04:20.560 --> 02:04:23.560
[Guest]: And then it goes back to 130.

02:04:23.560 --> 02:04:29.600
[Guest]: You are going to literally kill yourself before you buy that stock again.

02:04:29.600 --> 02:04:33.200
[Guest]: Because you're thinking, I sold it at 130, I sold it at 120.

02:04:33.200 --> 02:04:37.400
[Guest]: Mentally, your mind is telling you, were you wrong to sell at 120?

02:04:37.400 --> 02:04:40.240
[Guest]: But your mind is also telling you, but you were right, it went to 90, you know, it'll

02:04:40.240 --> 02:04:41.240
[Guest]: go back to 90.

02:04:41.240 --> 02:04:43.560
[Guest]: That time you buy it again.

02:04:43.560 --> 02:04:47.800
[Guest]: This is your mind playing tricks on you, and your mind thinking that it's a reversal to

02:04:47.800 --> 02:04:50.280
[Guest]: mean kind of happening, but it's not.

02:04:50.280 --> 02:04:57.520
[Guest]: And what happens here is that 130 stock goes to 200 rupees, and you kill yourself.

02:04:57.520 --> 02:05:01.400
[Guest]: Not because you didn't buy it at 130, because you didn't buy it at 140, you didn't buy it

02:05:01.400 --> 02:05:03.520
[Guest]: at 150, you didn't buy it at 160.

02:05:03.520 --> 02:05:07.360
[Guest]: And any of those times, if you had bought it, you would have still made enough returns

02:05:07.360 --> 02:05:08.720
[Guest]: to be proud of.

02:05:08.720 --> 02:05:12.440
[Guest]: But you didn't, because you were fascinated, like you said, the anchoring effect of that

02:05:12.440 --> 02:05:13.440
[Guest]: 120.

02:05:13.440 --> 02:05:20.480
[Guest]: It's not the 120 price that was existing, it was the point that you had sold at 120

02:05:20.480 --> 02:05:21.480
[Guest]: after buying at 100.

02:05:21.480 --> 02:05:27.920
[Guest]: So you were the hero, how can you not be the hero to give up and say, buy it back at 130?

02:05:27.920 --> 02:05:33.440
[Guest]: This is usually where it kills a lot of people, especially value investors, where you're looking

02:05:33.440 --> 02:05:37.400
[Guest]: at this Benjamin Graham kind of value thing, and you can't be wrong, I mean, you find it

02:05:37.400 --> 02:05:38.760
[Guest]: difficult to be wrong.

02:05:38.760 --> 02:05:46.320
[Guest]: So this is where momentum comes in and says to just discipline, it doesn't matter what,

02:05:46.320 --> 02:05:51.080
[Guest]: and that it doesn't matter what the underlying, I'll give you an example of the last, maybe

02:05:51.080 --> 02:05:53.360
[Guest]: eight months, and maybe people are right.

02:05:53.360 --> 02:05:56.920
[Guest]: So in the stock markets, it's not a zero sum game.

02:05:56.920 --> 02:06:02.360
[Guest]: To give you an example, I create a company, and I sell you shares at 100 rupees.

02:06:02.360 --> 02:06:07.440
[Guest]: And I have probably invested 50 rupees in the business, but I sell it to you at 100,

02:06:07.440 --> 02:06:11.520
[Guest]: I'm happy you've got 100 rupees, I've got 50 rupees of profit.

02:06:11.520 --> 02:06:16.120
[Guest]: You take that business, that share, and whoever's running that business earns a little more

02:06:16.120 --> 02:06:17.520
[Guest]: profit.

02:06:17.520 --> 02:06:21.080
[Guest]: Somebody else says I have value, I see value in it at 200 rupees.

02:06:21.080 --> 02:06:25.760
[Guest]: You sell it to that person at 200, you've made a 100 rupee profit.

02:06:25.760 --> 02:06:27.960
[Guest]: That person looks at it, the stock price goes to 300.

02:06:27.960 --> 02:06:28.960
[Guest]: Who has lost?

02:06:28.960 --> 02:06:32.800
[Guest]: It's a zero sum game, means somebody should have lost and somebody should have won.

02:06:32.800 --> 02:06:33.880
[Guest]: Nobody lost.

02:06:33.880 --> 02:06:37.080
[Guest]: It's the underlying value of the company that became bigger and bigger.

02:06:37.080 --> 02:06:39.280
[Guest]: But nobody actually lost the money on this front.

02:06:39.280 --> 02:06:43.800
[Guest]: It would have lost money if you had sold at 200, and then the price came back to 100,

02:06:43.800 --> 02:06:47.040
[Guest]: and you bought it back at 100, and that person lost the money and so on.

02:06:47.040 --> 02:06:52.600
[Guest]: So that's usually not, the stock market as a whole is not a zero sum game.

02:06:52.600 --> 02:07:00.720
[Guest]: So your ability to pick up momentum is not at the cost of someone else, or pick up stocks

02:07:00.720 --> 02:07:01.720
[Guest]: that are doing well.

02:07:01.720 --> 02:07:02.720
[Guest]: It's not at the cost of somebody else.

02:07:02.720 --> 02:07:06.280
[Guest]: It's that somebody else does not need to lose in order for you to win.

02:07:06.280 --> 02:07:11.680
[Guest]: This is something that I, and I also feel that this philosophy has to, it doesn't come

02:07:11.680 --> 02:07:12.680
[Guest]: naturally to us.

02:07:12.680 --> 02:07:15.560
[Guest]: We always think of life as a battle.

02:07:15.560 --> 02:07:17.140
[Guest]: If you've won, then who's lost?

02:07:17.140 --> 02:07:20.040
[Guest]: If India has won, then Australia should have lost the test match.

02:07:20.040 --> 02:07:25.320
[Guest]: So how can you have India and Australia both win, and yet have a match?

02:07:25.320 --> 02:07:30.080
[Guest]: So the answer to this is not, it's not intuitive to us.

02:07:30.080 --> 02:07:35.880
[Guest]: You learn it over time that one person's win could be in one time frame.

02:07:35.880 --> 02:07:37.680
[Guest]: Another person's win could be in a different time frame.

02:07:37.680 --> 02:07:40.560
[Guest]: They could be overlapping or not even related.

02:07:40.560 --> 02:07:46.240
[Guest]: And this is where momentum scores, because you don't have to always win.

02:07:46.240 --> 02:07:52.840
[Guest]: You just have, so if a stock goes from 10 to 100, if you make between 25 and 50, that's

02:07:52.840 --> 02:07:54.200
[Guest]: enough.

02:07:54.200 --> 02:07:58.160
[Guest]: You don't have had to make, made entirely from 10 to 100.

02:07:58.160 --> 02:08:03.520
[Guest]: You shouldn't have picked the bottoms or picked the, sold at the tops.

02:08:03.520 --> 02:08:07.520
[Guest]: If you made anything in the middle, you made the meat of the whole thing.

02:08:07.520 --> 02:08:11.880
[Guest]: This is the tough thing in momentum, because you're fighting your own gut.

02:08:11.880 --> 02:08:13.920
[Guest]: And I do this, for me, it's there all the time.

02:08:13.920 --> 02:08:17.480
[Guest]: I have the same emotional challenges as anybody else.

02:08:17.480 --> 02:08:21.640
[Guest]: It's just that, you know, sometimes, because I've seen it before, I still make those mistakes.

02:08:21.640 --> 02:08:29.160
[Guest]: I sometimes sell because the stock is run up too much, it goes to 10,000 rupees.

02:08:29.160 --> 02:08:32.720
[Guest]: And then you're like, oh my God, I sold at seven, I had no idea.

02:08:32.720 --> 02:08:36.640
[Guest]: And then now I realize that, you know, I will not have an idea.

02:08:36.640 --> 02:08:44.680
[Guest]: But I should sell according to a system rather than according to a lopsided view of, oh,

02:08:44.680 --> 02:08:47.440
[Guest]: this company has run up too much.

02:08:47.440 --> 02:08:50.040
[Guest]: That's the only thing that protects me sometimes.

02:08:50.040 --> 02:08:52.960
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of quick asides before I go on to my next question.

02:08:52.960 --> 02:08:57.600
[Amit Varma]: And one is about the whole zero something, it's practically, you know, it's a common

02:08:57.600 --> 02:09:01.400
[Amit Varma]: trope, if not a cliche on the show for me to whine about how we are wired to think of

02:09:01.400 --> 02:09:04.640
[Amit Varma]: the world in zero some ways, and it doesn't really work in those ways.

02:09:04.640 --> 02:09:07.760
[Amit Varma]: So it's refreshing to see you sort of talk about that.

02:09:07.760 --> 02:09:11.360
[Amit Varma]: The other thing which I'll take some time to process is the difference between poker

02:09:11.360 --> 02:09:14.320
[Amit Varma]: and investing in this case, and poker, of course, is a zero sum game.

02:09:14.320 --> 02:09:15.960
[Amit Varma]: And that may be part of the difference.

02:09:15.960 --> 02:09:19.560
[Amit Varma]: But what you were earlier saying about how a machine learning figures out a strategy,

02:09:19.560 --> 02:09:23.880
[Amit Varma]: but if another machine can know that strategy, it can figure out a better strategy.

02:09:23.880 --> 02:09:28.760
[Amit Varma]: Now in poker, typically, there are two ways to play poker, one is exploitative, which

02:09:28.760 --> 02:09:32.800
[Amit Varma]: is if I know your strategy, I can exploit your strategy, because you could be bluffing

02:09:32.800 --> 02:09:38.040
[Amit Varma]: too much, in which case I will call you more, or you could not be bluffing enough, in which

02:09:38.040 --> 02:09:42.720
[Amit Varma]: case I'll know that you have more value bets, and I'll fold to you more, and so on and so

02:09:42.720 --> 02:09:43.720
[Amit Varma]: forth.

02:09:43.720 --> 02:09:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Whatever you do, I can exploit you.

02:09:45.000 --> 02:09:49.560
[Amit Varma]: However, the other way of playing poker is what is called game theory optimal, where

02:09:49.560 --> 02:09:55.080
[Amit Varma]: if your sort of ranges are perfect, it doesn't matter what the other person has or what the

02:09:55.080 --> 02:09:57.840
[Amit Varma]: other person does, you're guaranteed not to lose.

02:09:57.840 --> 02:10:02.300
[Amit Varma]: So for example, let's say there's 200 bucks in a pot, and I bet 100 rupees.

02:10:02.300 --> 02:10:05.640
[Amit Varma]: So you have to call 100 to win 300, right?

02:10:05.640 --> 02:10:09.600
[Amit Varma]: You're getting three to one odds, you have to be right 20 to 25% of the time.

02:10:09.600 --> 02:10:15.520
[Amit Varma]: Now, therefore, if I build my range, so that exactly 25% of the time I have a bluff and

02:10:15.520 --> 02:10:19.120
[Amit Varma]: the other 75%, I have a value hand, I cannot lose to you.

02:10:19.120 --> 02:10:24.400
[Amit Varma]: You can lose if your frequencies are not correct, and they go on either side, but I cannot lose.

02:10:24.400 --> 02:10:28.720
[Amit Varma]: And what would then happen is if you and I are both playing GTO, or game theory optimal,

02:10:28.720 --> 02:10:31.580
[Amit Varma]: which is only possible only in theory, because after all, we are all human.

02:10:31.580 --> 02:10:37.440
[Amit Varma]: If you're both playing GTO, and if the casino isn't taking a cut, it's basically bang zero

02:10:37.440 --> 02:10:38.920
[Amit Varma]: sum, nobody can win or lose.

02:10:38.920 --> 02:10:42.840
[Amit Varma]: But because others can't play GTO, the closer you get to it, you can win.

02:10:42.840 --> 02:10:48.280
[Amit Varma]: But your description of what, you know, different machine learning algos fighting each other

02:10:48.280 --> 02:10:53.680
[Amit Varma]: indicates that in stock markets, there's no GTO, it's all sort of exploitative, or perhaps,

02:10:53.680 --> 02:10:59.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, GTO would be too complex to kind of even understand what that could be like.

02:10:59.360 --> 02:11:02.800
[Amit Varma]: But my question before I go on to, you know, I said there were three questions arising

02:11:02.800 --> 02:11:05.080
[Amit Varma]: out of complexity and humility.

02:11:05.080 --> 02:11:09.640
[Amit Varma]: Before we end this, this particular first question about AI, would you agree that at

02:11:09.640 --> 02:11:14.200
[Amit Varma]: some point, like it seems inevitable to me, that all trading at some point must be done

02:11:14.200 --> 02:11:19.520
[Amit Varma]: by machines, must, because one, they can process information much better and process complexity

02:11:19.520 --> 02:11:20.600
[Amit Varma]: much better.

02:11:20.600 --> 02:11:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And two, humans are hardwired with so many biases that get in the way, some of which

02:11:25.120 --> 02:11:26.160
[Amit Varma]: you described.

02:11:26.160 --> 02:11:31.680
[Amit Varma]: So is it then only a question of time that, you know, that that eventually happens?

02:11:31.680 --> 02:11:38.260
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, you know, there is actually this theory that eventually, see, the forex

02:11:38.260 --> 02:11:45.720
[Guest]: markets are 99% trading by machines, most of it, eventually, a lot of the stock markets

02:11:45.720 --> 02:11:50.540
[Guest]: will also be mostly traded by machines, it's just the way that they can trade a lot more.

02:11:50.540 --> 02:11:51.540
[Guest]: And they're probably more efficient.

02:11:51.540 --> 02:11:55.120
[Guest]: So instead of me saying, I want to sell so many shares, and I believe this is, I have

02:11:55.120 --> 02:11:59.960
[Guest]: proposed this as a solution, even in India, to the government selling stakes in their

02:11:59.960 --> 02:12:00.960
[Guest]: disinvestment program.

02:12:00.960 --> 02:12:01.960
[Guest]: So I'm like, yeah, why disinvest?

02:12:01.960 --> 02:12:07.600
[Guest]: Ek kaam karo na, ek program rakho, roj jata hai, 2-3 share, 3-4 share, and whenever it

02:12:07.600 --> 02:12:12.200
[Guest]: finds some volume, it sells some more shares, you will eventually get some 10-15,000 crores

02:12:12.200 --> 02:12:16.040
[Guest]: or 20, whatever you want to make, you make 100,000 crores, you can get it out of that

02:12:16.040 --> 02:12:20.640
[Guest]: system like that, they just hunt for volume, and they will, it will figure out when it's

02:12:20.640 --> 02:12:23.040
[Guest]: trying to get game, when somebody's trying to game it.

02:12:23.040 --> 02:12:27.480
[Guest]: So it might actually not sell at those times, and then it can figure out when people actually

02:12:27.480 --> 02:12:31.160
[Guest]: want to buy those shares, so it can sell a little more at those times.

02:12:31.160 --> 02:12:34.400
[Guest]: It is completely better that that is true.

02:12:34.400 --> 02:12:39.000
[Guest]: And there's a political reason for this, because if a politician decides to sell a business,

02:12:39.000 --> 02:12:42.680
[Guest]: he's going to demand bids, and then he's going to disqualify some people and that will be

02:12:42.680 --> 02:12:43.680
[Guest]: politically challenged.

02:12:43.680 --> 02:12:46.180
[Guest]: Machine chal raha hai, how can you question?

02:12:46.180 --> 02:12:50.080
[Guest]: So you can't, it's a very interesting way to solve a problem that might be both economic

02:12:50.080 --> 02:12:51.320
[Guest]: and political.

02:12:51.320 --> 02:12:54.600
[Guest]: But that kind of trading will be done by machines forever.

02:12:54.600 --> 02:12:59.560
[Guest]: Now eventually, some part of decision making or whether to sell or to buy will also be

02:12:59.560 --> 02:13:03.680
[Guest]: done by machines, by saying, listen, there seems to be too much demand, let me put supply

02:13:03.680 --> 02:13:08.120
[Guest]: in the place and too much demand, I put too much supply, I put demand, so I sell.

02:13:08.120 --> 02:13:11.520
[Guest]: So this part of this equation is definitely going there.

02:13:11.520 --> 02:13:16.320
[Guest]: But if you see the last few years, and how things have changed for us, people in the

02:13:16.320 --> 02:13:19.240
[Guest]: stock markets, where's the money being made?

02:13:19.240 --> 02:13:24.920
[Guest]: It's the guys that invested in these new startups, where there is no price on a daily basis.

02:13:24.920 --> 02:13:31.360
[Guest]: So there is a startup that's interesting, it comes up, and it becomes so big, and it

02:13:31.360 --> 02:13:34.600
[Guest]: raises money from a bunch of investors, then a bunch of other investors, then a bunch of

02:13:34.600 --> 02:13:37.560
[Guest]: third, and then goes to the stock market and sells its shares.

02:13:37.560 --> 02:13:40.040
[Guest]: And then it becomes publicly traded, blah, blah, blah.

02:13:40.040 --> 02:13:46.200
[Guest]: But it's possible that, you know, I'm sitting on this side of this business, which says,

02:13:46.200 --> 02:13:49.540
[Guest]: when it comes to the stock market, then I'll buy it, then it'll become big.

02:13:49.540 --> 02:13:51.720
[Guest]: What if it's already become big?

02:13:51.720 --> 02:13:56.900
[Guest]: Which is what has happened in the last 20 years, is that all the human intelligence

02:13:56.900 --> 02:14:02.280
[Guest]: has gone into places where there's no data, or the data is hidden to you, or the data

02:14:02.280 --> 02:14:03.680
[Guest]: is not available to you.

02:14:03.680 --> 02:14:09.960
[Guest]: They're creating new businesses by changing the rules of the game, whereas the stock market

02:14:09.960 --> 02:14:15.620
[Guest]: guys are working with places where the rules to the game are more well-defined.

02:14:15.620 --> 02:14:19.860
[Guest]: So you don't get a paytm in the stock markets.

02:14:19.860 --> 02:14:24.200
[Guest]: And in other times, a paytm would have been listed in the stock markets, you would have

02:14:24.200 --> 02:14:25.200
[Guest]: been able to buy it.

02:14:25.200 --> 02:14:30.240
[Guest]: But because of our listing rules and people doing lots of frauds with listing shady companies

02:14:30.240 --> 02:14:34.280
[Guest]: in the past, we've set rules that said, oh, no, you know what, only profitable, more than

02:14:34.280 --> 02:14:37.080
[Guest]: three years of profitability, yay, whoa, whoa, yay.

02:14:37.080 --> 02:14:39.720
[Guest]: Those guys are like, dude, I don't care, we'll grow big.

02:14:39.720 --> 02:14:43.440
[Guest]: And now it's gone to a point where if paytm in India perhaps was listed, it would be probably

02:14:43.440 --> 02:14:47.080
[Guest]: part of the nifty-flifty, it's valued at that much.

02:14:47.080 --> 02:14:50.640
[Guest]: Even Zomato is probably valued at a time point where it would be called a large cap company,

02:14:50.640 --> 02:14:52.560
[Guest]: the top 100 companies in India.

02:14:52.560 --> 02:14:59.440
[Guest]: This is a factor, I think, more of, if you think about machines trading, where there's

02:14:59.440 --> 02:15:03.880
[Guest]: a lot of data, there's enough data to analyze it, and they make those trades.

02:15:03.880 --> 02:15:11.440
[Guest]: The human trading has shifted into the non-exchange traded investment business.

02:15:11.440 --> 02:15:13.600
[Guest]: If you automate that, they'll find another way.

02:15:13.600 --> 02:15:22.000
[Guest]: So humans, like with the famous Jurassic Park dialogue, which is finally a non-cartoon movie,

02:15:22.000 --> 02:15:23.680
[Guest]: life finds a way.

02:15:23.680 --> 02:15:30.080
[Guest]: So if you take all the jobs away from the trading humans, they will find something else

02:15:30.080 --> 02:15:31.080
[Guest]: to trade.

02:15:31.080 --> 02:15:34.400
[Guest]: Today, Bitcoin trading is done by machines.

02:15:34.400 --> 02:15:35.400
[Guest]: It wasn't that way.

02:15:35.400 --> 02:15:40.440
[Guest]: Earlier machines, humans entered the trade, and now the Bitcoin machines trade against

02:15:40.440 --> 02:15:41.600
[Guest]: each other, perhaps.

02:15:41.600 --> 02:15:45.720
[Guest]: Tomorrow, there will be another system that will allow humans to trade off of different

02:15:45.720 --> 02:15:46.900
[Guest]: levels.

02:15:46.900 --> 02:15:48.960
[Guest]: People make money off of different things.

02:15:48.960 --> 02:15:51.000
[Guest]: So scarcity is one.

02:15:51.000 --> 02:15:56.040
[Guest]: Scarcity is basically, it's one of the ways Indian stock markets work, is that if most

02:15:56.040 --> 02:16:00.840
[Guest]: of the shares are held by a very concentrated set of people, then the remaining shares are

02:16:00.840 --> 02:16:01.840
[Guest]: too few.

02:16:01.840 --> 02:16:05.200
[Guest]: So even a small amount of demand can rocket the price up.

02:16:05.200 --> 02:16:08.400
[Guest]: The U.S. operates on a slightly different phenomenon, but Bitcoin is the same.

02:16:08.400 --> 02:16:12.440
[Guest]: So Bitcoin is very low float, everybody else wants to hold.

02:16:12.440 --> 02:16:17.920
[Guest]: So the prices are basically, if there's enough volume or liquidity at any point, there are

02:16:17.920 --> 02:16:20.960
[Guest]: chances the price could drop quite as much, which has also happened.

02:16:20.960 --> 02:16:22.760
[Guest]: So that's why it's very volatile.

02:16:22.760 --> 02:16:28.440
[Guest]: This phenomenon, I think, has contours that cause...

02:16:28.440 --> 02:16:33.040
[Guest]: So machines will trade, and I think humans will also always trade.

02:16:33.040 --> 02:16:38.600
[Guest]: They'll find something new, from tulips in the past to private companies today.

02:16:38.600 --> 02:16:42.080
[Guest]: There is always something, because humans are geared towards trading.

02:16:42.080 --> 02:16:43.080
[Guest]: We love to make deals.

02:16:43.080 --> 02:16:47.520
[Guest]: We are like, by nature, deal-making individuals.

02:16:47.520 --> 02:16:51.200
[Guest]: So if you tell that the machines are making all the deals, that's just not going to fly.

02:16:51.200 --> 02:16:52.600
[Guest]: We'll find something else to deal with.

02:16:52.600 --> 02:16:57.000
[Amit Varma]: So you talk about humans being deal-making creatures, and we're always craving action.

02:16:57.000 --> 02:16:59.880
[Amit Varma]: We want to push the chips forward, so to say.

02:16:59.880 --> 02:17:01.440
[Amit Varma]: Is that a bug rather than a feature?

02:17:01.440 --> 02:17:05.280
[Amit Varma]: For example, in poker, it's really just a small 2-3% of the people who really make money

02:17:05.280 --> 02:17:07.960
[Amit Varma]: everybody else loses, but that's a zero-sum game.

02:17:07.960 --> 02:17:11.360
[Amit Varma]: The point that you were making is that stock markets are a positive-sum game, though when

02:17:11.360 --> 02:17:14.000
[Amit Varma]: they're going down, they might seem like a negative-sum game as well.

02:17:14.000 --> 02:17:18.360
[Amit Varma]: My second question that arises from complexity and the humility which it should bring us

02:17:18.360 --> 02:17:22.120
[Amit Varma]: to is, should the common person invest?

02:17:22.120 --> 02:17:26.040
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier, at the start of the show, you gave the advice that everyone should invest,

02:17:26.040 --> 02:17:27.560
[Amit Varma]: because that is how you make money.

02:17:27.560 --> 02:17:31.920
[Amit Varma]: But that is under the assumption that they are investing in a sensible way and that they

02:17:31.920 --> 02:17:32.920
[Amit Varma]: have an edge.

02:17:32.920 --> 02:17:37.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, an argument could be made that most people don't have enough knowledge to invest, like

02:17:37.240 --> 02:17:42.020
[Amit Varma]: I certainly I don't because of exactly that reason, that most people don't have the knowledge

02:17:42.020 --> 02:17:43.120
[Amit Varma]: to invest.

02:17:43.120 --> 02:17:44.680
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, they are the suckers at the table.

02:17:44.680 --> 02:17:48.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's an old saying, if you don't know who is a sucker at the table, it's you.

02:17:48.520 --> 02:17:52.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, they are the suckers at the table, they might feel good about themselves

02:17:52.080 --> 02:17:56.640
[Amit Varma]: as they ride a bull market, but then it crashes and they realize they know nothing at all.

02:17:56.640 --> 02:18:01.400
[Amit Varma]: And that, you know, and that sort of epistemic humility is something that people like you

02:18:01.400 --> 02:18:05.920
[Amit Varma]: and I in the different domains, which we actually do know a few things about, the more we learn

02:18:05.920 --> 02:18:09.640
[Amit Varma]: about it, the more we realize that there is so much yet to learn, right?

02:18:09.640 --> 02:18:11.760
[Amit Varma]: And that constant humility is what makes us better.

02:18:11.760 --> 02:18:14.440
[Amit Varma]: The common investor doesn't really have that humility.

02:18:14.440 --> 02:18:19.080
[Amit Varma]: And like you also pointed out that the time to exit a share is possibly when the panwala

02:18:19.080 --> 02:18:22.000
[Amit Varma]: tells you it's a good time to buy the share.

02:18:22.000 --> 02:18:27.880
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that, you know, there is a case to be made that maybe common people

02:18:27.880 --> 02:18:32.520
[Amit Varma]: should not get excited and go in for some of the action because they could just be in

02:18:32.520 --> 02:18:33.520
[Amit Varma]: above their heads.

02:18:33.520 --> 02:18:37.680
[Amit Varma]: A lot of the trading is being done by machines, people like you are using incredibly complicated

02:18:37.680 --> 02:18:38.680
[Amit Varma]: software.

02:18:38.680 --> 02:18:41.960
[Amit Varma]: Of course, one way of investing is you go to a capital mind and, you know, trust Deepak

02:18:41.960 --> 02:18:43.480
[Amit Varma]: Shenoy with your money, which is great.

02:18:43.480 --> 02:18:48.480
[Amit Varma]: So then you have an expert and he'll do what he has to for you, which is possibly a sensible

02:18:48.480 --> 02:18:49.640
[Amit Varma]: way to start.

02:18:49.640 --> 02:18:54.960
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise be kind of wary because and always, you know, the Dunning-Kruger effect,

02:18:54.960 --> 02:18:57.480
[Amit Varma]: the less you know, the more you think, you know.

02:18:57.480 --> 02:19:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's a great danger with markets where inevitably somebody who is just out there

02:19:02.000 --> 02:19:05.360
[Amit Varma]: to exploit the whole greater fool theory is the greater fool.

02:19:05.360 --> 02:19:07.800
[Amit Varma]: So what's your kind of take on this?

02:19:07.800 --> 02:19:11.640
[Amit Varma]: Because I know that, you know, you care about investing, you would evangelize it.

02:19:11.640 --> 02:19:15.920
[Amit Varma]: But there is also this downside that, you know, people can just lose a lot because they

02:19:15.920 --> 02:19:16.920
[Guest]: don't know what they're doing.

02:19:16.920 --> 02:19:19.440
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, let me take this into three parts.

02:19:19.440 --> 02:19:23.400
[Guest]: So firstly, the why investment.

02:19:23.400 --> 02:19:28.000
[Guest]: So it comes close to a point about why save at all.

02:19:28.000 --> 02:19:29.000
[Guest]: And why should you save?

02:19:29.000 --> 02:19:30.000
[Guest]: You could keep working.

02:19:30.000 --> 02:19:32.200
[Guest]: I mean, our politicians are 80 years old, they're still working.

02:19:32.200 --> 02:19:33.200
[Guest]: And why can't we?

02:19:33.200 --> 02:19:39.080
[Guest]: We could continuously work to build your capital and whatever comes, spend it and you don't

02:19:39.080 --> 02:19:40.080
[Guest]: have to do anything.

02:19:40.080 --> 02:19:44.800
[Guest]: The minute you will counter this will probably with, Deepak, what happens if I get an injury?

02:19:44.800 --> 02:19:45.960
[Guest]: I don't want to work anymore.

02:19:45.960 --> 02:19:46.960
[Guest]: I have to take a holiday.

02:19:46.960 --> 02:19:48.680
[Guest]: Where will I get the money for that?

02:19:48.680 --> 02:19:49.680
[Guest]: I have to save.

02:19:49.680 --> 02:19:50.680
[Guest]: Well, yes, you do.

02:19:50.680 --> 02:19:51.680
[Guest]: Then where are you going to save?

02:19:51.680 --> 02:19:57.360
[Guest]: So the answer to that is, well, you know what, I'll put it in the bank, and the bank's not

02:19:57.360 --> 02:20:01.720
[Guest]: going to cover inflation, your costs are going up, you got to have the money grow to a point

02:20:01.720 --> 02:20:07.240
[Guest]: where it's at least the saving is enough to say meet that emergency that you really needed

02:20:07.240 --> 02:20:08.240
[Guest]: to meet and so on.

02:20:08.240 --> 02:20:11.400
[Guest]: So you're going to have to, you know, kind of beat inflation.

02:20:11.400 --> 02:20:16.600
[Guest]: For the longest time, India had these 10%, 11%, 12% rates where I could say, forget it,

02:20:16.600 --> 02:20:20.960
[Guest]: put your money in a bank, even if it's a fixed deposit, it's fine, you're getting 12%.

02:20:20.960 --> 02:20:25.160
[Guest]: And you'll pay some tax on it and you'll get 8%.

02:20:25.160 --> 02:20:28.960
[Guest]: This era has unfortunately gone.

02:20:28.960 --> 02:20:38.120
[Guest]: So we're facing a point where a lot of countries have 0% deposit rates, interest rates, a lot

02:20:38.120 --> 02:20:39.840
[Guest]: of countries have negative interest rates.

02:20:39.840 --> 02:20:43.080
[Guest]: So when you put 100 into a bank, they give you back 99.

02:20:43.080 --> 02:20:46.960
[Guest]: The answer to why is very complicated, but it's there, that's the situation, it's happening

02:20:46.960 --> 02:20:48.160
[Guest]: in India as well.

02:20:48.160 --> 02:20:53.200
[Guest]: As recently as yesterday, I was looking at fixed deposit rates and they've reached 4.5%.

02:20:53.200 --> 02:20:59.200
[Guest]: 4.5% may still be okay, compared to the US, but for India, it sounds like a horrible,

02:20:59.200 --> 02:21:00.480
[Guest]: horrible number.

02:21:00.480 --> 02:21:06.720
[Guest]: But given this, if you want your investments to beat that 4.5%, or you need your money

02:21:06.720 --> 02:21:09.940
[Guest]: to grow a little bit more than that, you're going to have to invest.

02:21:09.940 --> 02:21:15.640
[Guest]: So sometimes when I say invest, it's only because there is almost no alternative doing

02:21:15.640 --> 02:21:16.640
[Guest]: so.

02:21:16.640 --> 02:21:18.480
[Guest]: And I don't say invest only in stocks.

02:21:18.480 --> 02:21:25.280
[Guest]: Investment is a way to deploy your money so that it becomes more than what it was.

02:21:25.280 --> 02:21:29.400
[Guest]: Not necessarily that it should be only in equities and stock markets and some stuff

02:21:29.400 --> 02:21:30.400
[Guest]: like that.

02:21:30.400 --> 02:21:32.840
[Guest]: Today, I would say there's a bunch of more things that you can invest in.

02:21:32.840 --> 02:21:33.840
[Guest]: You can buy real estate.

02:21:33.840 --> 02:21:38.680
[Guest]: Real estate values are believed to go up over time, though in the last 10 years, they have

02:21:38.680 --> 02:21:40.560
[Guest]: not perhaps gone anywhere.

02:21:40.560 --> 02:21:45.360
[Guest]: There is investment in gold, which is one of those old assets where you almost never

02:21:45.360 --> 02:21:51.280
[Guest]: over a 10-year period see a loss, so it tends to grow at the rate that inflation goes up.

02:21:51.280 --> 02:21:55.520
[Guest]: Again, something that may not necessarily have occurred in the last 10 years.

02:21:55.520 --> 02:22:00.600
[Guest]: The last two years perhaps are an anomaly more than anything else.

02:22:00.600 --> 02:22:02.960
[Guest]: But before that, the gold price was more or less stable.

02:22:02.960 --> 02:22:08.240
[Guest]: So there are different things you can invest in, and you need to be able to invest primarily

02:22:08.240 --> 02:22:12.660
[Guest]: just to make those extra returns that will beat inflation.

02:22:12.660 --> 02:22:16.080
[Guest]: If you don't invest, then you've got to work for the rest of your life and assume that

02:22:16.080 --> 02:22:17.720
[Guest]: you have a stable income.

02:22:17.720 --> 02:22:21.440
[Guest]: The best thing that you could do is build yourself an income that is passive.

02:22:21.440 --> 02:22:27.880
[Guest]: When I say that, I mean it could mean writing a book that gets you royalties forever.

02:22:27.880 --> 02:22:32.640
[Guest]: But we all know that not all books give you royalties forever, and it's very difficult

02:22:32.640 --> 02:22:33.720
[Guest]: to write a book.

02:22:33.720 --> 02:22:36.640
[Guest]: Sometimes people just don't know how to write, and sometimes people, I know you're trying

02:22:36.640 --> 02:22:38.680
[Guest]: to change that, but I hope you do.

02:22:38.680 --> 02:22:42.600
[Guest]: There's a lot more people that come out with great books, but the way people consume content

02:22:42.600 --> 02:22:46.680
[Guest]: today is no longer in the format of books alone.

02:22:46.680 --> 02:22:49.400
[Guest]: It could be, and today has opened up new avenues.

02:22:49.400 --> 02:22:55.560
[Guest]: You could build YouTube videos that eventually get you advertising revenue without even you

02:22:55.560 --> 02:22:57.500
[Guest]: having to work for it.

02:22:57.500 --> 02:23:01.360
[Guest]: So this passive income thing is a great thing to do around investing.

02:23:01.360 --> 02:23:05.340
[Guest]: So it's like saying, listen, I'm getting something else that gives me continuous income, but not

02:23:05.340 --> 02:23:06.360
[Guest]: the same thing.

02:23:06.360 --> 02:23:13.960
[Guest]: So stocks, or bonds, or fixed deposits, or whatever it is that you invest in, that is

02:23:13.960 --> 02:23:20.040
[Guest]: also another way for you to have an income that is beyond the primary job that you're

02:23:20.040 --> 02:23:21.040
[Guest]: doing.

02:23:21.040 --> 02:23:25.080
[Guest]: That income could be by eating off of the corpus, or by those stocks paying you dividends.

02:23:25.080 --> 02:23:27.360
[Guest]: However it is, it doesn't matter.

02:23:27.360 --> 02:23:31.800
[Guest]: Because let's say you had five crores today, and that five crores was giving you half a

02:23:31.800 --> 02:23:32.800
[Guest]: percent a month.

02:23:32.800 --> 02:23:36.440
[Guest]: That's two and a half lakh rupees a month that you could take out of that five crores

02:23:36.440 --> 02:23:37.440
[Guest]: every month and spend.

02:23:37.440 --> 02:23:42.120
[Guest]: And if you're spending less, maybe only a lakh a month, then one and a half lakhs keeps

02:23:42.120 --> 02:23:48.580
[Guest]: getting added to that five crore corpus, and which keeps growing until you draw out enough.

02:23:48.580 --> 02:23:56.280
[Guest]: So your ability to now quit whatever you're doing and do something else has no impact

02:23:56.280 --> 02:23:59.800
[Guest]: to your life, because you could say, listen, even if I don't get a salary, I could take

02:23:59.800 --> 02:24:04.360
[Guest]: out the one lakh a month from this money I'm making from the investments that I have.

02:24:04.360 --> 02:24:08.240
[Guest]: And so it gives you that one additional degree of freedom.

02:24:08.240 --> 02:24:13.360
[Guest]: And we don't appreciate this enough, but having as many degrees of freedom as you can in your

02:24:13.360 --> 02:24:16.620
[Guest]: life is what eventually drives happiness.

02:24:16.620 --> 02:24:17.620
[Guest]: Not joys.

02:24:17.620 --> 02:24:18.980
[Guest]: Joys you can buy.

02:24:18.980 --> 02:24:23.680
[Guest]: You can go to Bali, do snorkeling, you'll get joy.

02:24:23.680 --> 02:24:25.680
[Guest]: But happiness is a state of mind.

02:24:25.680 --> 02:24:32.440
[Guest]: So it requires you to remove those little latent fears in the back of your head.

02:24:32.440 --> 02:24:34.920
[Guest]: And that's one of the reasons why you invest.

02:24:34.920 --> 02:24:37.720
[Guest]: Not because you should or you have to.

02:24:37.720 --> 02:24:41.740
[Guest]: Because inherent uncertainty, the squirrel that stores nuts.

02:24:41.740 --> 02:24:46.440
[Guest]: This is why taxes are bad, because they end up taking away from the guys who save the

02:24:46.440 --> 02:24:49.760
[Guest]: nuts for the winter.

02:24:49.760 --> 02:24:55.400
[Guest]: But the squirrels saving their winter food is what I call akin to investing.

02:24:55.400 --> 02:24:56.480
[Guest]: You don't have to do it.

02:24:56.480 --> 02:25:02.080
[Guest]: You could hope to find enough nuts at any point in time to be able to survive.

02:25:02.080 --> 02:25:05.840
[Guest]: But it's the recognition of the fact that the nuts may not be there, they may be a winter

02:25:05.840 --> 02:25:09.240
[Guest]: and the winter is coming is the reason why.

02:25:09.240 --> 02:25:12.880
[Guest]: But I also think that the complexity of investing is too much.

02:25:12.880 --> 02:25:14.120
[Guest]: There is way too...

02:25:14.120 --> 02:25:16.840
[Guest]: And that's because people in this industry are evil.

02:25:16.840 --> 02:25:21.840
[Guest]: That is why they will tell you stupid things like, give me money for six years, then I'll

02:25:21.840 --> 02:25:26.400
[Guest]: give you back so much money for five years and oh my God, this is a fantastic return.

02:25:26.400 --> 02:25:30.240
[Guest]: And they call it a unit linked insurance package and you're like, oh my God, a ULIP, everybody's

02:25:30.240 --> 02:25:31.480
[Guest]: talking about ULIPs now.

02:25:31.480 --> 02:25:33.600
[Guest]: But this is just like putting lipstick on a pig.

02:25:33.600 --> 02:25:34.600
[Guest]: It's a pig.

02:25:34.600 --> 02:25:38.320
[Guest]: It's actually better to have put your money in a fixed deposit in your bank, you would

02:25:38.320 --> 02:25:39.640
[Guest]: have got higher returns.

02:25:39.640 --> 02:25:41.000
[Guest]: But nobody's telling you that.

02:25:41.000 --> 02:25:47.880
[Guest]: They've invented this because A, too much education and B, too little use of education

02:25:47.880 --> 02:25:48.880
[Guest]: elsewhere.

02:25:48.880 --> 02:25:52.920
[Guest]: So basically, I mean, I say this is a very like uncle kind of dialogue, but the idea

02:25:52.920 --> 02:26:00.320
[Guest]: is that if you make things complex, they sound attractive to people who are smart.

02:26:00.320 --> 02:26:03.640
[Guest]: And they sound attractive to people who are not smart, also thinking that this person

02:26:03.640 --> 02:26:08.440
[Guest]: is smart, he's using words like ULIP in a sentence, which is possibly means that he

02:26:08.440 --> 02:26:09.440
[Guest]: knows what he's talking about.

02:26:09.440 --> 02:26:13.680
[Guest]: So you automatically get money coming to you, fame, recognition, power, eventually you have

02:26:13.680 --> 02:26:17.800
[Guest]: enough money to tell other people that you shouldn't chase after money in your life.

02:26:17.800 --> 02:26:22.280
[Guest]: It's a very famous shitty dialogue that people say, you shouldn't look where you go after

02:26:22.280 --> 02:26:23.280
[Guest]: passion.

02:26:23.280 --> 02:26:27.440
[Guest]: I mean, dude, come on, make your money and then you do whatever passion stuff you want.

02:26:27.440 --> 02:26:36.800
[Guest]: But the point about my saying that investing is important and is that you should know that

02:26:36.800 --> 02:26:43.040
[Guest]: the need to invest is driven by those saving nuts for winter.

02:26:43.040 --> 02:26:45.280
[Guest]: I don't mean nuts in any other way.

02:26:45.280 --> 02:26:52.040
[Guest]: And I literally say that that is what will save you from a winter.

02:26:52.040 --> 02:26:56.040
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean that you have to go and overcomplicate your life by going and

02:26:56.040 --> 02:27:00.400
[Guest]: buying a stock that somebody sent you on WhatsApp today, just because that guy sent you five

02:27:00.400 --> 02:27:05.000
[Guest]: picks in stock WhatsApp yesterday, because you don't understand this stuff.

02:27:05.000 --> 02:27:09.160
[Guest]: Once you do, you might appreciate that that guy's bullshitting himself.

02:27:09.160 --> 02:27:12.480
[Guest]: And then you have to have a strategy and a discipline to do things.

02:27:12.480 --> 02:27:17.920
[Guest]: And all these complexities of how so discovering, I talked about value investing at one stage,

02:27:17.920 --> 02:27:23.160
[Guest]: momentum investing, algorithmic investing, the three different styles.

02:27:23.160 --> 02:27:25.240
[Guest]: Not every style appeals to every person.

02:27:25.240 --> 02:27:29.680
[Guest]: It takes a four or five year discovery process in order to get enough of an education.

02:27:29.680 --> 02:27:33.400
[Guest]: And you're going to pay serious fees to the market for giving you that education before

02:27:33.400 --> 02:27:35.360
[Guest]: you figure out who you are.

02:27:35.360 --> 02:27:38.440
[Guest]: If you're not that kind of a person, you shouldn't get into complexity.

02:27:38.440 --> 02:27:42.680
[Guest]: So simplicity would be easier if they sold it better.

02:27:42.680 --> 02:27:43.680
[Guest]: But it is available.

02:27:43.680 --> 02:27:45.240
[Guest]: So fixed deposits are simple.

02:27:45.240 --> 02:27:47.880
[Guest]: You put so much money, you get so much money, or this is the simplest thing in the world.

02:27:47.880 --> 02:27:51.440
[Guest]: It's like, you know, there's no other thing.

02:27:51.440 --> 02:27:53.880
[Guest]: But there is complexity in stock markets.

02:27:53.880 --> 02:27:56.800
[Guest]: People say, buy this stock versus that complex.

02:27:56.800 --> 02:27:59.000
[Guest]: Buy an index makes sense.

02:27:59.000 --> 02:28:00.920
[Guest]: I don't care who the top stocks are.

02:28:00.920 --> 02:28:05.040
[Guest]: I just have to buy the index and or maybe I pay an index fund manager.

02:28:05.040 --> 02:28:09.200
[Guest]: He charges me very little fees, but he always buys the top stocks and I'm happy to go with

02:28:09.200 --> 02:28:10.200
[Guest]: that.

02:28:10.200 --> 02:28:11.200
[Guest]: I'm not going to put 100 rupees into equities.

02:28:11.200 --> 02:28:16.500
[Guest]: I'm going to put only 70, 30 rupees will be in fixed deposits or in bonds.

02:28:16.500 --> 02:28:17.640
[Guest]: And that's it.

02:28:17.640 --> 02:28:18.640
[Guest]: That's the end of my life.

02:28:18.640 --> 02:28:23.880
[Guest]: No, Harry Markowitz created this phenomenal, and this goes back to your other thing about

02:28:23.880 --> 02:28:33.080
[Guest]: how your childhood or your prime years shape your fears and your, you know, your loyalties.

02:28:33.080 --> 02:28:37.160
[Guest]: Harry Markowitz created this massive capital allocation pro thing.

02:28:37.160 --> 02:28:39.240
[Guest]: He won some Nobel type of prize.

02:28:39.240 --> 02:28:40.240
[Guest]: Maybe it's a Nobel itself.

02:28:40.240 --> 02:28:41.240
[Guest]: I'm sorry.

02:28:41.240 --> 02:28:44.860
[Guest]: I don't want to, I don't mean to insult him, but he's a very famous guy.

02:28:44.860 --> 02:28:48.160
[Guest]: So when he was asked, how do you invest your money?

02:28:48.160 --> 02:28:53.320
[Guest]: Now people are expecting an answer like, God, I do calculate risk free capital versus risk

02:28:53.320 --> 02:28:54.320
[Guest]: cost of capital.

02:28:54.320 --> 02:28:57.960
[Guest]: And I do an adjustment and do an inverse derivative of this.

02:28:57.960 --> 02:29:05.600
[Guest]: He said, I thought about all of the alternatives and I put 50% of my money in stocks and 50%

02:29:05.600 --> 02:29:07.680
[Guest]: of my money in bonds.

02:29:07.680 --> 02:29:11.320
[Guest]: Although he invented the way to figure out how to allocate more money to stocks at a

02:29:11.320 --> 02:29:12.320
[Guest]: certain time.

02:29:12.320 --> 02:29:13.320
[Guest]: He said, it's too complex.

02:29:13.320 --> 02:29:15.920
[Guest]: I just like 50-50 and I'm done.

02:29:15.920 --> 02:29:19.960
[Guest]: The guy who invented the algorithm that tells you how to differentiate between the two doesn't

02:29:19.960 --> 02:29:21.120
[Guest]: do it himself.

02:29:21.120 --> 02:29:26.840
[Guest]: And there's another example of somebody else who talked about, he said about how the past

02:29:26.840 --> 02:29:27.840
[Guest]: shaped his life.

02:29:27.840 --> 02:29:35.760
[Guest]: He said, I grew up in Nazi Germany and I saw the worst of all the excesses that people

02:29:35.760 --> 02:29:39.120
[Guest]: lent in the nastiest side of life.

02:29:39.120 --> 02:29:43.240
[Guest]: And what, you know, the stock market bust, which is what Nazi Germany actually came out

02:29:43.240 --> 02:29:48.900
[Guest]: of the 1929, 1932 depression was caused by a stock market crash.

02:29:48.900 --> 02:29:52.600
[Guest]: And he says, when I see that and I see the evil that, you know, things happen, I am too

02:29:52.600 --> 02:29:56.240
[Guest]: scared of the future to put my money into anything but bonds.

02:29:56.240 --> 02:30:02.680
[Guest]: So most people who were born in those times have different risk appetites than people

02:30:02.680 --> 02:30:06.960
[Guest]: who were born in the forties in the US, which was the baby boomer era.

02:30:06.960 --> 02:30:11.080
[Guest]: And therefore those people are much more likely to put money into stocks.

02:30:11.080 --> 02:30:15.520
[Guest]: People who were born in the sixties saw the 1970s oil shocks and depressions, again, they

02:30:15.520 --> 02:30:16.920
[Guest]: were likely to put more money.

02:30:16.920 --> 02:30:22.080
[Guest]: So that's about also discovering who you are and how your past shapes your life.

02:30:22.080 --> 02:30:26.440
[Guest]: It's important to do that because you don't want to be unhappy choosing a strategy that

02:30:26.440 --> 02:30:29.120
[Guest]: is lousy.

02:30:29.120 --> 02:30:34.240
[Guest]: So just find, according to me, invest according to the kind of risk you can, you're willing

02:30:34.240 --> 02:30:35.240
[Guest]: to take.

02:30:35.240 --> 02:30:39.040
[Guest]: If you're not willing to take risk, don't believe anyone who tells you that you should

02:30:39.040 --> 02:30:40.040
[Guest]: take risk.

02:30:40.040 --> 02:30:46.000
[Guest]: The only caveat to this is if you're completely screwed, and this is my sheer advice to everybody,

02:30:46.000 --> 02:30:50.200
[Guest]: I've written this in a thing, the biggest advice somebody can give to you is make more

02:30:50.200 --> 02:30:51.640
[Guest]: money.

02:30:51.640 --> 02:30:53.800
[Guest]: That's the end of that story.

02:30:53.800 --> 02:30:59.960
[Guest]: Because if the advice does not involve make more money, you're too rich to care.

02:30:59.960 --> 02:31:00.960
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating.

02:31:00.960 --> 02:31:03.200
[Amit Varma]: And so it sounds much like be happy.

02:31:03.200 --> 02:31:05.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, you can just generally kind of throw it out there.

02:31:05.840 --> 02:31:07.000
[Amit Varma]: A couple of quick asides.

02:31:07.000 --> 02:31:12.360
[Amit Varma]: One is I'm glad that you railed against taxes, or you brought up saving nuts for winter there.

02:31:12.360 --> 02:31:16.740
[Amit Varma]: And my point about taxes simply is that we should think of taxes as part time slavery.

02:31:16.740 --> 02:31:21.160
[Amit Varma]: If I am giving 25% of my income to the government, I am basically working for the government

02:31:21.160 --> 02:31:22.760
[Amit Varma]: between January and March.

02:31:22.760 --> 02:31:27.080
[Amit Varma]: I start only in April between January and March, I am a slave of the government.

02:31:27.080 --> 02:31:30.280
[Amit Varma]: And which is not to say that there should be no taxes, there should you know, we need

02:31:30.280 --> 02:31:32.160
[Amit Varma]: taxes, we need the state.

02:31:32.160 --> 02:31:37.080
[Amit Varma]: But we should question what is done with our taxes far more than we actually do, which

02:31:37.080 --> 02:31:40.580
[Amit Varma]: is the unfortunate thing we keep demanding government should spend on this government

02:31:40.580 --> 02:31:43.000
[Amit Varma]: should rescue where India government should do this.

02:31:43.000 --> 02:31:47.680
[Amit Varma]: But it's our slavery, which is the consequence of that.

02:31:47.680 --> 02:31:51.280
[Amit Varma]: The other thing is, you said, you know, you spoke about going to Bali and all of that,

02:31:51.280 --> 02:31:53.440
[Amit Varma]: listen, I've just come out of a year of lockdown.

02:31:53.440 --> 02:31:57.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, I went to frickin Santa Cruz from Andheri the other day, and I felt so happy.

02:31:57.640 --> 02:32:00.280
[Amit Varma]: So don't kind of get me started on that.

02:32:00.280 --> 02:32:05.080
[Amit Varma]: The third thing I would say is that, you know, to sort of paraphrase what you said about

02:32:05.080 --> 02:32:09.560
[Amit Varma]: why invest, the point is that listen, you, even if you don't want to invest in the stock

02:32:09.560 --> 02:32:14.480
[Amit Varma]: market, you are making a decision of what to do with the money that you're saving, you

02:32:14.480 --> 02:32:18.640
[Amit Varma]: know, either it is in a savings account or a fixed deposit or a stock market or whatever.

02:32:18.640 --> 02:32:23.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, all of these carry different kinds of risk reward ratios, and so on and so forth.

02:32:23.640 --> 02:32:28.320
[Amit Varma]: And because it is your hard earned money, it is at least your responsibility to figure

02:32:28.320 --> 02:32:33.220
[Amit Varma]: out how much risk you're willing to take and get the information about which of these is

02:32:33.220 --> 02:32:34.680
[Amit Varma]: therefore right for you.

02:32:34.680 --> 02:32:40.280
[Amit Varma]: As you so wisely said, you know, I just follow inertia, and I just keep it lying in my savings

02:32:40.280 --> 02:32:45.240
[Amit Varma]: account, because, you know, just don't have the bandwidth to figure out all of the other

02:32:45.240 --> 02:32:46.240
[Amit Varma]: stuff.

02:32:46.240 --> 02:32:50.120
[Amit Varma]: And that kind of brings me to the other like, I don't buy and you know, relationship managers

02:32:50.120 --> 02:32:54.160
[Amit Varma]: from the bank will call me and say, Hey, why don't you buy this instrument or that instrument?

02:32:54.160 --> 02:32:58.720
[Amit Varma]: And I simply don't because as you pointed out that so much of investment advice that

02:32:58.720 --> 02:33:04.760
[Amit Varma]: the common person gets is so incredibly scammy, like selling insurance to 65 year olds, and,

02:33:04.760 --> 02:33:10.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, a common example that you've given in the past, and so much of it is so scammy.

02:33:10.680 --> 02:33:15.520
[Amit Varma]: And it makes me wonder that, you know, when I can sit at home and start a YouTube channel

02:33:15.520 --> 02:33:21.520
[Amit Varma]: or a podcast or whatever, with such simple tools at my disposal, you know, why don't

02:33:21.520 --> 02:33:25.800
[Amit Varma]: we have a stage where I could, you know, I could invest my money, you know, using such

02:33:25.800 --> 02:33:26.800
[Amit Varma]: simple tools.

02:33:26.800 --> 02:33:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And of course, one way of doing that is by going to Mr. Chinoy for advice or just finding

02:33:33.040 --> 02:33:37.160
[Amit Varma]: an intermediary who does that for you, but then which intermediary do you trust?

02:33:37.160 --> 02:33:38.600
[Amit Varma]: Why do you trust them?

02:33:38.600 --> 02:33:39.800
[Amit Varma]: And so on and so forth.

02:33:39.800 --> 02:33:44.060
[Amit Varma]: Like I remember my third question really coming out of complexity and that whole complexity

02:33:44.060 --> 02:33:49.280
[Amit Varma]: humility paradigm was really about how, if so much of stock prices are determined by

02:33:49.280 --> 02:33:53.900
[Amit Varma]: narratives, like one thing that you want about which is a sort of a red flag against the

02:33:53.900 --> 02:33:58.280
[Amit Varma]: companies when a company says we are going to do this, you know, we are going to raise

02:33:58.280 --> 02:34:03.520
[Amit Varma]: capital or we are going to sell this or sell that and whatever, and your point simply was

02:34:03.520 --> 02:34:05.640
[Amit Varma]: that why are you telling me you're going to do that?

02:34:05.640 --> 02:34:07.400
[Amit Varma]: Why don't you just freaking do it?

02:34:07.400 --> 02:34:11.420
[Amit Varma]: And the fact that it is telling you about what it is going to do instead of doing it

02:34:11.420 --> 02:34:15.960
[Amit Varma]: is a red flag, because it means it is trying to build that narrative and is focused on

02:34:15.960 --> 02:34:16.960
[Amit Varma]: the share price.

02:34:16.960 --> 02:34:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Now, our mutual friend, Nitin Pai, who is also your Bengaluru city mate, you know, once

02:34:22.960 --> 02:34:27.320
[Amit Varma]: remarked when those whole allegations came up against a particular party for hacking

02:34:27.320 --> 02:34:28.320
[Amit Varma]: EVMs.

02:34:28.320 --> 02:34:30.320
[Amit Varma]: And he said, why do they need to hack EVMs?

02:34:30.320 --> 02:34:32.680
[Amit Varma]: It is easier to hack the human mind.

02:34:32.680 --> 02:34:34.680
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that that is true.

02:34:34.680 --> 02:34:39.360
[Amit Varma]: And what you do have with all these peddlers of narratives is that you have incredibly

02:34:39.360 --> 02:34:46.240
[Amit Varma]: skilled marketers who know how to manipulate the human mind, perhaps using the kind of

02:34:46.240 --> 02:34:50.640
[Amit Varma]: jargon you mentioned, ki hum, you know, ULIP or debenture kar denge and whatever.

02:34:50.640 --> 02:34:53.120
[Amit Varma]: And you think, huh, this guy knows what he's talking about.

02:34:53.120 --> 02:34:58.600
[Amit Varma]: But techniques of hacking the human mind have become so complicated that as a common person

02:34:58.600 --> 02:35:05.220
[Amit Varma]: who doesn't know anything about this subject, my instinct is that just stay the hell away.

02:35:05.220 --> 02:35:07.040
[Amit Varma]: Because otherwise, I am going to get fooled.

02:35:07.040 --> 02:35:11.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, I know a lot about one or two subjects, but everything else, I am extremely wary of

02:35:11.800 --> 02:35:12.800
[Amit Varma]: being conned.

02:35:12.800 --> 02:35:15.880
[Amit Varma]: And here, of course, there is a lot at stake, so you can get conned.

02:35:15.880 --> 02:35:19.380
[Amit Varma]: So you know, is this something that you see changing the fact that the common man has

02:35:19.380 --> 02:35:20.880
[Amit Varma]: to be permanently bewildered?

02:35:20.880 --> 02:35:24.800
[Amit Varma]: Whereas with other things, like I no longer, you know, if I buy a printer, it's plug and

02:35:24.800 --> 02:35:25.800
[Amit Varma]: play.

02:35:25.800 --> 02:35:29.600
[Amit Varma]: I don't have to install 40 freaking drivers like we had to do 20 years ago.

02:35:29.600 --> 02:35:30.820
[Amit Varma]: That got simplified.

02:35:30.820 --> 02:35:35.340
[Amit Varma]: You were telling me before the session started about how you assembled a desktop computer

02:35:35.340 --> 02:35:36.340
[Amit Varma]: for your son.

02:35:36.340 --> 02:35:37.340
[Amit Varma]: And it was so easy.

02:35:37.340 --> 02:35:41.420
[Amit Varma]: Motherboard liya, chipset liya, hard drive liya, sab connect kiya and it's just working

02:35:41.420 --> 02:35:42.420
[Amit Varma]: out of the box.

02:35:42.420 --> 02:35:46.440
[Amit Varma]: To me, that's unimaginable because that's not how I know computers.

02:35:46.440 --> 02:35:50.740
[Amit Varma]: So can this kind of thing, what you do with your money and what happens to it, can this

02:35:50.740 --> 02:35:52.820
[Amit Varma]: ever get simplified?

02:35:52.820 --> 02:35:55.400
[Amit Varma]: Isn't that the next big problem waiting to be solved?

02:35:55.400 --> 02:35:56.400
[Guest]: This is very interesting.

02:35:56.400 --> 02:36:02.780
[Guest]: I think, I mean, okay, I'm betting my future on the fact that it is a problem worth solving.

02:36:02.780 --> 02:36:04.940
[Guest]: So I am very biased on that.

02:36:04.940 --> 02:36:13.300
[Guest]: So I believe it is my job to make my job obsolete, because I come from a background where automation

02:36:13.300 --> 02:36:19.220
[Guest]: is the only God you care about, which means you're from technology, you're going to automate

02:36:19.220 --> 02:36:21.020
[Guest]: things, you're going to remove the intermediaries.

02:36:21.020 --> 02:36:24.100
[Guest]: And yet here I am as an intermediary.

02:36:24.100 --> 02:36:29.780
[Guest]: Somebody I asked to trust me in order to figure out what's best for their money.

02:36:29.780 --> 02:36:34.580
[Guest]: Sometimes this philosophy can be, the more people have tried this in the past saying,

02:36:34.580 --> 02:36:39.340
[Guest]: listen, we'll give you an algorithm and you can invest according to that algorithm.

02:36:39.340 --> 02:36:44.300
[Guest]: You don't even need me, you just have to kind of, but every algorithm has its faults and

02:36:44.300 --> 02:36:50.780
[Guest]: every human therefore has a complication because they're now thinking not just because, is

02:36:50.780 --> 02:36:52.860
[Guest]: this a problem with the algorithm?

02:36:52.860 --> 02:36:58.700
[Guest]: Is this natural that once in a while I'll see a loss or do I have to change this algorithm?

02:36:58.700 --> 02:37:03.820
[Guest]: And now I need a human being to help me figure out whether this is the case or that is the

02:37:03.820 --> 02:37:04.820
[Guest]: case.

02:37:04.820 --> 02:37:08.420
[Guest]: And then if I need a human being anyway, and I'm going to go with his advice, then why

02:37:08.420 --> 02:37:09.420
[Guest]: do I need the algorithm?

02:37:09.420 --> 02:37:12.280
[Guest]: Let him go and select whatever it is that he wants.

02:37:12.280 --> 02:37:17.220
[Guest]: So we fall back on human trust today.

02:37:17.220 --> 02:37:22.740
[Guest]: I believe in the, like in the U.S. they have tried things like, oh, we do automatic accounts.

02:37:22.740 --> 02:37:25.820
[Guest]: So when you save your money into a bank account, it automatically gets swept into some kind

02:37:25.820 --> 02:37:27.380
[Guest]: of a money market account.

02:37:27.380 --> 02:37:32.180
[Guest]: And then from there it goes into some kind of stock market account and gets invested.

02:37:32.180 --> 02:37:37.460
[Guest]: Today, for instance, you and I don't have employee provident fund, but if we did, that

02:37:37.460 --> 02:37:42.140
[Guest]: money, 10% of it would be forcibly invested into the stock market.

02:37:42.140 --> 02:37:44.540
[Guest]: Even if we didn't like stocks, there's nothing we can do about it.

02:37:44.540 --> 02:37:46.900
[Guest]: Somebody is automatically doing that for us.

02:37:46.900 --> 02:37:54.900
[Guest]: India has come, interestingly, from a phase of forced investing by telling us that you

02:37:54.900 --> 02:38:00.180
[Guest]: don't know what is best for you and therefore a fixed deposit is that.

02:38:00.180 --> 02:38:05.940
[Guest]: You don't know what is best for you, so you give me money at 4.5%, 5%, 6% as a fixed deposit.

02:38:05.940 --> 02:38:09.820
[Guest]: I will go lend it to Reliance Industries at 9.5%.

02:38:09.820 --> 02:38:12.180
[Guest]: I will make the intermediate thing.

02:38:12.180 --> 02:38:16.380
[Guest]: And don't ask me why you can't lend to Reliance at 9.5% because you don't know what is good

02:38:16.380 --> 02:38:17.380
[Guest]: for you.

02:38:17.380 --> 02:38:22.700
[Guest]: When we evolved from there, we said, OK, maybe you know that giving money to Reliance is

02:38:22.700 --> 02:38:23.700
[Guest]: better for you.

02:38:23.700 --> 02:38:25.320
[Guest]: Go ahead and do it.

02:38:25.320 --> 02:38:29.780
[Guest]: So when we've evolved, we've just added one degree of freedom, removed the institution

02:38:29.780 --> 02:38:33.940
[Guest]: called the bank, which was the intermediary between us and Reliance, and allows us to

02:38:33.940 --> 02:38:34.940
[Guest]: directly talk to Reliance.

02:38:34.940 --> 02:38:39.900
[Guest]: Now, you might argue this is a good thing because it removes the power of the banker

02:38:39.900 --> 02:38:45.860
[Guest]: to manipulate our fortunes, because they have, and also allows us to get a slightly higher

02:38:45.860 --> 02:38:48.140
[Guest]: return by doing things ourselves.

02:38:48.140 --> 02:38:49.760
[Guest]: In this process now, there's complexity.

02:38:49.760 --> 02:38:52.700
[Guest]: The guy who doesn't know both the bank or Reliance doesn't know whether he should go

02:38:52.700 --> 02:38:54.380
[Guest]: to Reliance or he should go to bank.

02:38:54.380 --> 02:38:58.380
[Guest]: So now you have this dichotomy, which has been created by more information.

02:38:58.380 --> 02:39:04.940
[Guest]: It's like saying, why do we need 48 brands of soap?

02:39:04.940 --> 02:39:09.900
[Guest]: We know that all the soap does is clean you, and maybe you can put some scent in one and

02:39:09.900 --> 02:39:10.940
[Guest]: some scent in the other.

02:39:10.940 --> 02:39:14.220
[Guest]: But if you go to the market today, there are big, small, tiny.

02:39:14.220 --> 02:39:16.540
[Guest]: This melts fast, does not.

02:39:16.540 --> 02:39:19.780
[Guest]: So for women only, I'm like, hello, for women only?

02:39:19.780 --> 02:39:20.780
[Guest]: I mean, come on.

02:39:20.780 --> 02:39:23.260
[Guest]: But no, but that's the reality.

02:39:23.260 --> 02:39:27.580
[Guest]: And then you have shampoos for this kind of hair.

02:39:27.580 --> 02:39:32.900
[Guest]: So the more developed a country is, the more degrees of freedom a country has, the more

02:39:32.900 --> 02:39:35.980
[Guest]: choices of soap there are in its supermarkets.

02:39:35.980 --> 02:39:41.740
[Guest]: And therefore, the more choices of investments there will be for the citizens of that country.

02:39:41.740 --> 02:39:47.380
[Guest]: And therefore, at some level, that complexity is byproduct of our freedoms.

02:39:47.380 --> 02:39:53.340
[Guest]: So if we took it away in some way, and we continue to retain freedom as an important

02:39:53.340 --> 02:39:58.100
[Guest]: part of our society, then we would continue to have other investment products on top of

02:39:58.100 --> 02:39:59.540
[Guest]: whatever is simple.

02:39:59.540 --> 02:40:03.140
[Guest]: So what is simple is always not going to be easy to accept.

02:40:03.140 --> 02:40:12.020
[Guest]: But I do think that given the amount of misselling and the lack of retribution, because if somebody

02:40:12.020 --> 02:40:16.740
[Guest]: missold your policy, insurance policy, there is no retribution.

02:40:16.740 --> 02:40:20.160
[Guest]: The guy gets to continue to sleep at night while you don't.

02:40:20.160 --> 02:40:24.460
[Guest]: So this happens because people say that buyer has to beware.

02:40:24.460 --> 02:40:28.060
[Guest]: I don't think that's a correct philosophy, that we need laws.

02:40:28.060 --> 02:40:34.020
[Guest]: And here, I will be a little anti-libertarian in the sense I will say that you do need laws

02:40:34.020 --> 02:40:36.860
[Guest]: to protect against misselling of this kind.

02:40:36.860 --> 02:40:39.500
[Guest]: But at the same time, I don't want choice to be taken away.

02:40:39.500 --> 02:40:42.820
[Guest]: That means you're going to need that choice of saying, I go with the simple thing.

02:40:42.820 --> 02:40:46.300
[Guest]: That's just easy for everybody to see what I'm doing.

02:40:46.300 --> 02:40:52.140
[Guest]: And there's a low-risk thing and a high-risk thing, and it's very simple.

02:40:52.140 --> 02:40:54.740
[Guest]: Low-risk thing will be just bank deposit kind of thing.

02:40:54.740 --> 02:40:58.300
[Guest]: High-risk thing will be something more risky, like stocks or real estate or whatever it

02:40:58.300 --> 02:40:59.300
[Guest]: is.

02:40:59.300 --> 02:41:02.840
[Guest]: And you can choose some money here and some money there, and you're done.

02:41:02.840 --> 02:41:04.500
[Guest]: That would be a brilliant thing to have.

02:41:04.500 --> 02:41:10.820
[Guest]: I don't know whether, and I'm going to bet my future on the fact that people desire simplicity.

02:41:10.820 --> 02:41:14.920
[Guest]: Although everything in the past shows that they love complexity.

02:41:14.920 --> 02:41:19.740
[Guest]: But the example you said came to mind, which is, why do we just buy devices now and they

02:41:19.740 --> 02:41:21.480
[Guest]: just work?

02:41:21.480 --> 02:41:28.180
[Guest]: You don't hear people complaining a lot about, oh my God, I gave my cell phone to my service

02:41:28.180 --> 02:41:29.660
[Guest]: station for five days, it hasn't come back.

02:41:29.660 --> 02:41:32.260
[Guest]: Of course, you'll find once in a while those kind of complaints.

02:41:32.260 --> 02:41:36.060
[Guest]: But nobody gives their cell phones for service anymore.

02:41:36.060 --> 02:41:41.220
[Guest]: You either throw it away and buy a new one, or you know that once it goes wrong, it's

02:41:41.220 --> 02:41:42.220
[Guest]: gone.

02:41:42.220 --> 02:41:43.900
[Guest]: You just replace it.

02:41:43.900 --> 02:41:45.820
[Guest]: But you don't get your TV repaired.

02:41:45.820 --> 02:41:51.820
[Guest]: When I was a kid, my TV would always be going bad, and we'd call a repairer to come and

02:41:51.820 --> 02:41:54.660
[Guest]: he would do something complicated and repair it and go away.

02:41:54.660 --> 02:41:58.660
[Guest]: Now, these people are very smart, so they know exactly what is wrong with your cathode

02:41:58.660 --> 02:42:03.820
[Guest]: ray tube TV and whether something is bad or something like that.

02:42:03.820 --> 02:42:10.860
[Guest]: But their entire jobs have been taken away because you don't need to repair this thing

02:42:10.860 --> 02:42:11.860
[Guest]: anymore.

02:42:11.860 --> 02:42:17.100
[Guest]: When electric cars come, the nature of the system is that today a dealership exists a

02:42:17.100 --> 02:42:21.540
[Guest]: little bit because of sales, but this much because of service, much more.

02:42:21.540 --> 02:42:26.860
[Guest]: The service and spares give the dealership its much required revenue in order for it

02:42:26.860 --> 02:42:28.540
[Guest]: to continue to have a dealership.

02:42:28.540 --> 02:42:32.940
[Guest]: Tomorrow, if an electric car comes, they don't need any service.

02:42:32.940 --> 02:42:36.180
[Guest]: Tesla has a lifetime warranty.

02:42:36.180 --> 02:42:37.180
[Guest]: They can afford to do it.

02:42:37.180 --> 02:42:38.180
[Guest]: There are much lower parts.

02:42:38.180 --> 02:42:39.940
[Guest]: You don't have to do anything.

02:42:39.940 --> 02:42:42.940
[Guest]: There's no concept called an oil change of any sort.

02:42:42.940 --> 02:42:45.940
[Guest]: I mean, maybe there's some inside the motors, but I don't know.

02:42:45.940 --> 02:42:52.220
[Guest]: But however, what I'm trying to get at is that when you've simplified something through

02:42:52.220 --> 02:42:57.860
[Guest]: technology or through some kind of new this thing, it changes that industry forever.

02:42:57.860 --> 02:43:02.260
[Guest]: Tomorrow's dealers, they may not be no dealers, you may be directly buying from Tesla, which

02:43:02.260 --> 02:43:04.580
[Guest]: you currently have to because Tesla has no dealers.

02:43:04.580 --> 02:43:09.060
[Guest]: But every other manufacturer, Maruti, you don't buy from Maruti, you go to a dealer.

02:43:09.060 --> 02:43:15.340
[Guest]: You can't go to Hindustan Unilever's website and buy even one soap, although they sell

02:43:15.340 --> 02:43:16.340
[Guest]: soap.

02:43:16.340 --> 02:43:18.980
[Guest]: You can't go to P&G and buy diapers.

02:43:18.980 --> 02:43:22.380
[Guest]: They sell diapers, but the reason is because they've built a supply chain.

02:43:22.380 --> 02:43:26.220
[Guest]: You go to the distributors in the middle and those distributors earn a little bit of margin

02:43:26.220 --> 02:43:31.460
[Guest]: so that so and if P&G starts selling diapers directly and everybody were buying from them,

02:43:31.460 --> 02:43:34.820
[Guest]: all those people would go out of business and that would change the nature of life.

02:43:34.820 --> 02:43:41.500
[Guest]: So when you do that in finance, you also impact a very large number of people by removing

02:43:41.500 --> 02:43:43.180
[Guest]: the intermediaries in the place.

02:43:43.180 --> 02:43:45.220
[Guest]: But that's the only way to go.

02:43:45.220 --> 02:43:50.300
[Guest]: In the US, there's a company called Vanguard, which started in the 70s.

02:43:50.300 --> 02:43:53.660
[Guest]: It said, listen, don't invest with active fund managers.

02:43:53.660 --> 02:43:58.700
[Guest]: Active fund managers are perhaps maybe people like me who say, Deepak, I mean, so I'll tell

02:43:58.700 --> 02:44:00.980
[Guest]: you, listen, Amit, I know how to invest.

02:44:00.980 --> 02:44:01.980
[Guest]: I can find stocks.

02:44:01.980 --> 02:44:06.460
[Guest]: I have this fantastic strategy and I will find these stocks and I will make you lots

02:44:06.460 --> 02:44:07.460
[Guest]: of money.

02:44:07.460 --> 02:44:08.460
[Guest]: And you give me money.

02:44:08.460 --> 02:44:09.700
[Guest]: I'm actively managing your funds.

02:44:09.700 --> 02:44:15.260
[Guest]: For that, I charge you a 1%, 2% a year, or typically in India, it's like 2%.

02:44:15.260 --> 02:44:19.980
[Guest]: But they charge you 2% a year to manage your money.

02:44:19.980 --> 02:44:25.220
[Guest]: What Vanguard did was this guy called John Bogle, he said, listen, this is crazy because

02:44:25.220 --> 02:44:30.380
[Guest]: if I just bought the indexes, I would beat most of these active fund managers.

02:44:30.380 --> 02:44:34.700
[Guest]: Sure, one or two will beat me, but they're not going to be the same one or two for a

02:44:34.700 --> 02:44:35.700
[Guest]: long time.

02:44:35.700 --> 02:44:39.460
[Guest]: A few will beat me this year and tomorrow it'll be ICICI and day after tomorrow it'll

02:44:39.460 --> 02:44:41.900
[Guest]: be Axis and fourth year it'll be somebody else.

02:44:41.900 --> 02:44:45.940
[Guest]: So if you're stuck with one fund, chances are you'll be on top for one year, but then

02:44:45.940 --> 02:44:48.060
[Guest]: you'll be on the bottom for the rest of the years.

02:44:48.060 --> 02:44:53.620
[Guest]: So if you were to look at something simple enough and that beats just because of charging

02:44:53.620 --> 02:44:56.740
[Guest]: lower fees, Vanguard changed the ecosystem.

02:44:56.740 --> 02:45:00.980
[Guest]: It's the second largest fund manager in the world today.

02:45:00.980 --> 02:45:05.420
[Guest]: It manages, I don't know, some $7 trillion, $6 trillion worth of assets.

02:45:05.420 --> 02:45:10.380
[Guest]: The biggest one is a company called BlackRock, run by Larry Fink, which has both active and

02:45:10.380 --> 02:45:11.380
[Guest]: is passive.

02:45:11.380 --> 02:45:17.580
[Guest]: But the passive so much overshadows the active that you are running on a world that is almost

02:45:17.580 --> 02:45:19.580
[Guest]: entirely run on index funds.

02:45:19.580 --> 02:45:23.300
[Guest]: When I say index funds, it means people are not actively making decisions, they're just

02:45:23.300 --> 02:45:24.820
[Guest]: the largest market cap companies.

02:45:24.820 --> 02:45:29.140
[Guest]: And what happens when you have a system where the largest companies are the ones that everybody

02:45:29.140 --> 02:45:32.460
[Guest]: invests in, is that the largest companies get more money.

02:45:32.460 --> 02:45:37.420
[Guest]: So at some point, perhaps, it will not matter if these companies make profits or not.

02:45:37.420 --> 02:45:42.020
[Guest]: Because when you save money and it goes automatically into these passive funds, nobody's making

02:45:42.020 --> 02:45:43.020
[Guest]: any stock selections.

02:45:43.020 --> 02:45:45.340
[Guest]: People are just buying the highest-earned companies.

02:45:45.340 --> 02:45:49.460
[Guest]: So the money keeps going to the highest-quality companies.

02:45:49.460 --> 02:45:55.820
[Guest]: Eventually, there'll be a small set of people, perhaps influential, that will then say, listen,

02:45:55.820 --> 02:45:58.260
[Guest]: I know that this company is a fraud.

02:45:58.260 --> 02:46:02.100
[Guest]: You're giving it more money, but it's there in the top simply because you're giving it

02:46:02.100 --> 02:46:03.100
[Guest]: more money.

02:46:03.100 --> 02:46:04.100
[Guest]: But I think it'll go down.

02:46:04.100 --> 02:46:05.580
[Guest]: They go and short those stocks.

02:46:05.580 --> 02:46:07.260
[Guest]: Some of those stocks fall.

02:46:07.260 --> 02:46:11.100
[Guest]: Then you, because they fall, you stop giving them any more money.

02:46:11.100 --> 02:46:12.660
[Guest]: And then they fall all the way to zero.

02:46:12.660 --> 02:46:13.740
[Guest]: Something else comes up.

02:46:13.740 --> 02:46:16.920
[Guest]: This is the way the systems in the US and all work right now.

02:46:16.920 --> 02:46:22.260
[Guest]: And because they have simplified this process, it's very easy for you to make that investment.

02:46:22.260 --> 02:46:28.460
[Guest]: Hopefully in India, and I believe this will come because it's there, that you will be

02:46:28.460 --> 02:46:30.020
[Guest]: having one of those choices.

02:46:30.020 --> 02:46:34.300
[Guest]: And one of those choices will be, don't put too much of your mind to it.

02:46:34.300 --> 02:46:39.900
[Guest]: Go with a strategy, a passive concept that has worked in the past and that will continue

02:46:39.900 --> 02:46:40.900
[Guest]: to work.

02:46:40.900 --> 02:46:46.620
[Guest]: You may not be the best that's out there, but you will definitely not be the worst.

02:46:46.620 --> 02:46:48.780
[Guest]: Because you're not making these active calls.

02:46:48.780 --> 02:46:54.220
[Guest]: This philosophy, I think eventually it's probably less than 5% in India, but I think it will

02:46:54.220 --> 02:46:55.220
[Guest]: go up to 35-40% eventually.

02:46:55.220 --> 02:46:58.020
[Amit Varma]: Well, lots to unpack there again.

02:46:58.020 --> 02:47:02.020
[Amit Varma]: And I'd say that, you know, the sort of the car dealerships being driven out of car dealership

02:47:02.020 --> 02:47:05.420
[Amit Varma]: by electric cars, because, you know, they mostly do service and that won't be required.

02:47:05.420 --> 02:47:08.140
[Amit Varma]: Reminds me of the STD boots you spoke about earlier.

02:47:08.140 --> 02:47:11.340
[Amit Varma]: And I think we'd both agree that that kind of creative destruction is a damn good thing.

02:47:11.340 --> 02:47:13.300
[Amit Varma]: It brings value for people.

02:47:13.300 --> 02:47:16.940
[Amit Varma]: It goes back into the economy, creates new jobs and new sectors.

02:47:16.940 --> 02:47:21.460
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's not like all the people who were running STD boots could do nothing else

02:47:21.460 --> 02:47:22.460
[Amit Varma]: with their lives.

02:47:22.460 --> 02:47:24.820
[Amit Varma]: The economy boomed and they found other things to do.

02:47:24.820 --> 02:47:27.580
[Amit Varma]: And I would sort of contest a couple of things.

02:47:27.580 --> 02:47:31.900
[Amit Varma]: One is, I would say that, you know, having laws that protect pensioners from evil insurance

02:47:31.900 --> 02:47:34.340
[Amit Varma]: salesmen are not anti-libertarian.

02:47:34.340 --> 02:47:38.100
[Amit Varma]: Every libertarian would agree that you need that kind of protection, whether it's through

02:47:38.100 --> 02:47:42.300
[Amit Varma]: tort laws or someone, but if someone, you know, misrepresents a particular product or

02:47:42.300 --> 02:47:45.260
[Amit Varma]: service and they make money off you, that's basically cheating.

02:47:45.260 --> 02:47:48.180
[Amit Varma]: So of course, you want the rule of law to protect you from that.

02:47:48.180 --> 02:47:52.580
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing I'd say is that, you know, I used to bring about the supermarket analogy.

02:47:52.580 --> 02:47:56.100
[Amit Varma]: I used to talk about 80 kinds of shampoos at the supermarket and say how that's such

02:47:56.100 --> 02:47:57.180
[Amit Varma]: a great thing.

02:47:57.180 --> 02:48:01.460
[Amit Varma]: And I've written a column about this in the context of education, about how our students

02:48:01.460 --> 02:48:02.540
[Amit Varma]: today don't have choice.

02:48:02.540 --> 02:48:07.580
[Amit Varma]: They have one kind of system, one kind of school, but shampoo people have a lot of choice.

02:48:07.580 --> 02:48:11.340
[Amit Varma]: And I would say that, you know, what you said was that complexity is a byproduct of a free

02:48:11.340 --> 02:48:12.340
[Amit Varma]: society.

02:48:12.340 --> 02:48:17.300
[Amit Varma]: I'd say choice is a byproduct of a free society and not necessarily complexity.

02:48:17.300 --> 02:48:21.260
[Amit Varma]: Because when I go to buy a soap, I think I can be assured that every soap I pick up in

02:48:21.260 --> 02:48:24.140
[Amit Varma]: the supermarket will do the job of cleaning me.

02:48:24.140 --> 02:48:25.140
[Amit Varma]: Right?

02:48:25.140 --> 02:48:29.180
[Amit Varma]: Whereas I don't have the same assurance with any kind of financial product I see because

02:48:29.180 --> 02:48:33.780
[Amit Varma]: I just need too much know-how to even begin to understand how the hell they work.

02:48:33.780 --> 02:48:38.100
[Amit Varma]: But as you're pointing out, maybe, you know, we can, I think, simultaneously move towards

02:48:38.100 --> 02:48:41.380
[Amit Varma]: a greater choice and greater simplicity.

02:48:41.380 --> 02:48:46.900
[Amit Varma]: And all these frauds who fall by the wayside, as will inevitably happen, like the STD Boots

02:48:46.900 --> 02:48:47.900
[Amit Varma]: of yore.

02:48:47.900 --> 02:48:51.500
[Amit Varma]: Though the STD Boots guys weren't frauds, they were important businessmen providing

02:48:51.500 --> 02:48:54.460
[Amit Varma]: a useful service that is no longer required.

02:48:54.460 --> 02:48:57.780
[Amit Varma]: But you know that things will kind of change.

02:48:57.780 --> 02:49:02.420
[Guest]: Let me ask you point one thing over there, very interesting, because there's this interesting

02:49:02.420 --> 02:49:06.020
[Guest]: analogy of, I mean, the story that goes mixing the rounds.

02:49:06.020 --> 02:49:10.860
[Guest]: I rail about how an insurance policy that you could have taken would have made more

02:49:10.860 --> 02:49:12.860
[Guest]: money in a fixed deposit.

02:49:12.860 --> 02:49:13.860
[Guest]: Okay.

02:49:13.860 --> 02:49:18.900
[Guest]: And sometimes even I'm stupid, because the problem isn't that they're buying a substandard

02:49:18.900 --> 02:49:24.980
[Guest]: product that can help them make lesser money in the future.

02:49:24.980 --> 02:49:29.860
[Guest]: Sometimes all that is required that people need is to save money, regardless of whether

02:49:29.860 --> 02:49:34.380
[Guest]: it earns 5% or 3%, because there's a story that goes around doing the rounds saying this

02:49:34.380 --> 02:49:38.060
[Guest]: is guy who's a smoker and somebody comes to him and asks him, how many cigarettes do you

02:49:38.060 --> 02:49:39.060
[Guest]: smoke a day?

02:49:39.060 --> 02:49:40.060
[Guest]: He says, 20.

02:49:40.060 --> 02:49:44.420
[Guest]: And then there's 20 cigarettes a day.

02:49:44.420 --> 02:49:46.060
[Guest]: How many years have you been smoking?

02:49:46.060 --> 02:49:47.340
[Guest]: 30 years.

02:49:47.340 --> 02:49:53.300
[Guest]: So 30 years into 365 into 20, my God, that's some 85 lakh rupees, you could have bought

02:49:53.300 --> 02:49:55.300
[Guest]: a Ferrari by now.

02:49:55.300 --> 02:49:58.300
[Guest]: So this guy looks at the person and says, well, do you smoke?

02:49:58.300 --> 02:49:59.300
[Guest]: No, come on.

02:49:59.300 --> 02:50:00.300
[Guest]: Where's your Ferrari?

02:50:00.300 --> 02:50:05.900
[Guest]: That's the point, right, in the end, I can rail about these products all I want.

02:50:05.900 --> 02:50:12.140
[Guest]: But even if it's doing that little iota of service of saying that you could in the end

02:50:12.140 --> 02:50:16.380
[Guest]: have a bunch of money that came out of nowhere, I tell you this, I felt this myself.

02:50:16.380 --> 02:50:22.660
[Guest]: I had an insurance policy I had bought in 2000 or something like that, which was a horrible

02:50:22.660 --> 02:50:23.660
[Guest]: insurance product.

02:50:23.660 --> 02:50:29.460
[Guest]: But given the way I am, I always look at this sunk cost fallacy and every point in time,

02:50:29.460 --> 02:50:34.140
[Guest]: I'm going to shift or I'm going to look at this as a, should I get out?

02:50:34.140 --> 02:50:35.140
[Guest]: Should I stay in?

02:50:35.140 --> 02:50:36.140
[Guest]: What's better?

02:50:36.140 --> 02:50:37.140
[Guest]: We forget what's happened in the past.

02:50:37.140 --> 02:50:39.060
[Guest]: It was always better to stay in.

02:50:39.060 --> 02:50:44.500
[Guest]: I got this money this year, I went and bought my son a piano.

02:50:44.500 --> 02:50:46.460
[Guest]: This gives me immense amount of joy.

02:50:46.460 --> 02:50:53.940
[Guest]: I tell you, just getting that money, it was a decent sum of money, but just getting that

02:50:53.940 --> 02:50:59.020
[Guest]: money made me feel that, dude, you know what, I know it is a shitty product.

02:50:59.020 --> 02:51:05.300
[Guest]: But just in the middle of a lockdown, getting this nice little check or this money coming

02:51:05.300 --> 02:51:08.060
[Guest]: into your bank account, that is awesome.

02:51:08.060 --> 02:51:14.500
[Guest]: And I want to say this, all my bullshit about you learning to be a better investor is just

02:51:14.500 --> 02:51:18.540
[Guest]: throw it out if you're not doing anything to save.

02:51:18.540 --> 02:51:21.620
[Guest]: If you're saving money and it's sitting in your bank account and you're not spending

02:51:21.620 --> 02:51:26.740
[Guest]: too much of it, even sometimes that is enough, you don't have to invest.

02:51:26.740 --> 02:51:33.580
[Guest]: Actually, this simplification of investing is glorifying investing more than perhaps

02:51:33.580 --> 02:51:34.580
[Guest]: what is really required.

02:51:34.580 --> 02:51:37.780
[Guest]: It's just save and you'll make out all right.

02:51:37.780 --> 02:51:38.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:51:38.780 --> 02:51:40.580
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it can be as simple as that.

02:51:40.580 --> 02:51:41.580
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

02:51:41.580 --> 02:51:45.700
[Amit Varma]: Of course, in previous interviews, you've done this really nice episode, I think episode

02:51:45.700 --> 02:51:49.540
[Amit Varma]: four of the Capital Mind podcast, which I'll link from the show notes, where you spoke

02:51:49.540 --> 02:51:55.020
[Amit Varma]: about these kinds of intermediaries and people who will, you know, sell an insurance product

02:51:55.020 --> 02:51:58.380
[Amit Varma]: to a 65 year old pensioner and not let him know that there's no liquidity.

02:51:58.380 --> 02:51:59.580
[Amit Varma]: So he has no escape.

02:51:59.580 --> 02:52:03.700
[Amit Varma]: His money is just blocked for five years and stuff like that just sounds like horrendous

02:52:03.700 --> 02:52:07.460
[Amit Varma]: to me, which is why my advice would be that if you do not understand something completely,

02:52:07.460 --> 02:52:12.100
[Amit Varma]: do not do it, you know, beware of the Dunning-Kruger effect, have some humility about the limits

02:52:12.100 --> 02:52:15.260
[Amit Varma]: of your own knowledge, which is why my money is in a savings account.

02:52:15.260 --> 02:52:18.300
[Amit Varma]: I am saving whatever little there is of it.

02:52:18.300 --> 02:52:22.460
[Amit Varma]: But you know, let's let's kind of move on to, you know, people would have wondered,

02:52:22.460 --> 02:52:29.780
[Amit Varma]: Amit hasn't asked Deepak the one thing we want him to ask, right, which is the economy

02:52:29.780 --> 02:52:33.460
[Amit Varma]: is going down, down, down, stock market is going up, up, up.

02:52:33.460 --> 02:52:34.620
[Amit Varma]: Now, why is this?

02:52:34.620 --> 02:52:38.580
[Amit Varma]: You have of course written, you wrote a column about this in June, which I love where you

02:52:38.580 --> 02:52:43.900
[Amit Varma]: spoke about how in 1958, US industrial production fell 10% in less than a year, stock market

02:52:43.900 --> 02:52:45.420
[Amit Varma]: went up 30%.

02:52:45.420 --> 02:52:48.780
[Amit Varma]: You've quoted John Templeton's explanation of that and all of that.

02:52:48.780 --> 02:52:53.140
[Amit Varma]: But in simple terms, for all the janta who sat through patiently for three hours to wait

02:52:53.140 --> 02:52:56.460
[Amit Varma]: for me to ask you this question, ki bhai ho kya raha hai?

02:52:56.460 --> 02:52:58.140
[Amit Varma]: Is this all a big scam?

02:52:58.140 --> 02:52:59.140
[Guest]: Kindly explain.

02:52:59.140 --> 02:53:03.820
[Guest]: Well, everything's a big scam, if you ask me, but then it doesn't, you know, at that

02:53:03.820 --> 02:53:08.460
[Guest]: level, it doesn't matter on a long enough timeline, the chances of survival of anything

02:53:08.460 --> 02:53:09.540
[Guest]: goes to zero, right?

02:53:09.540 --> 02:53:14.700
[Guest]: So the problem at some point is that we are trying to justify this market.

02:53:14.700 --> 02:53:15.700
[Guest]: It's not justifiable.

02:53:15.700 --> 02:53:20.780
[Guest]: This is a very, very interesting situation where you've had, I will not try to justify

02:53:20.780 --> 02:53:21.780
[Guest]: stock market.

02:53:21.780 --> 02:53:22.780
[Guest]: Now, don't get me wrong here.

02:53:22.780 --> 02:53:27.060
[Guest]: I will not say that this is a great market, but something has changed.

02:53:27.060 --> 02:53:30.220
[Guest]: And what that something is, is this glut of liquidity.

02:53:30.220 --> 02:53:35.740
[Guest]: To give you an example of how crazy it has been, the amount of money that's been printed

02:53:35.740 --> 02:53:40.860
[Guest]: in the last one year, perhaps, you know, is greater than money printed in the last 10.

02:53:40.860 --> 02:53:43.780
[Guest]: And the money printed in the last 10 was greater than the last 30.

02:53:43.780 --> 02:53:50.980
[Guest]: The idea that the central bankers have decided is that I will not let stock prices fall specifically

02:53:50.980 --> 02:53:51.980
[Guest]: stock price.

02:53:51.980 --> 02:53:53.100
[Guest]: I don't know why.

02:53:53.100 --> 02:53:58.540
[Guest]: And one of the reasons in the US is very clear is that people's when they've made interest

02:53:58.540 --> 02:54:05.420
[Guest]: rate zero, they have literally told us that there will be no interest that you will receive

02:54:05.420 --> 02:54:07.860
[Guest]: on the money that you place inside a bank.

02:54:07.860 --> 02:54:11.020
[Guest]: And therefore, you have to take risk in your investments.

02:54:11.020 --> 02:54:13.920
[Guest]: And they have taken that risk by putting their money into stocks.

02:54:13.920 --> 02:54:17.800
[Guest]: Since people's retirement money is now almost entirely into stocks, you can't ruin the stock

02:54:17.800 --> 02:54:18.800
[Guest]: market.

02:54:18.800 --> 02:54:21.940
[Guest]: It has political ramifications because you're killing people's retirements.

02:54:21.940 --> 02:54:25.580
[Guest]: And when you do that, you say that I will protect the stock market at any cost.

02:54:25.580 --> 02:54:28.340
[Guest]: The answer to doing that is to print money.

02:54:28.340 --> 02:54:33.340
[Guest]: When you print money, a lot of it, what has happened really is that companies like Google,

02:54:33.340 --> 02:54:39.060
[Guest]: Facebook, which otherwise in an interest bearing economy would have taken years and years and

02:54:39.060 --> 02:54:45.660
[Guest]: years to get profitable, suddenly become not well not to get profitable to get attractive.

02:54:45.660 --> 02:54:46.660
[Guest]: And they would have died.

02:54:46.660 --> 02:54:49.620
[Guest]: Because if you had invested, let's say, in a Facebook in the early years, you might have

02:54:49.620 --> 02:54:54.740
[Guest]: said, look, I mean, why am I investing in a Facebook, it's not making any money.

02:54:54.740 --> 02:54:57.500
[Guest]: And you know, it's interesting technology.

02:54:57.500 --> 02:54:59.900
[Guest]: But what's the point of it?

02:54:59.900 --> 02:55:03.700
[Guest]: The other side of that equation is, dude, where else will you put your money?

02:55:03.700 --> 02:55:04.700
[Guest]: Nowhere else is that interested.

02:55:04.700 --> 02:55:06.100
[Guest]: Okay, okay, let's keep it here.

02:55:06.100 --> 02:55:10.260
[Guest]: So Facebook gets that amount of time like Uber has, like Swiggy has, they may be making

02:55:10.260 --> 02:55:11.260
[Guest]: losses.

02:55:11.260 --> 02:55:15.700
[Guest]: But people are forgiving those losses, specifically foreign investors, who are saying, listen,

02:55:15.700 --> 02:55:20.100
[Guest]: go ahead, build a big industry, kill all the delivery boys, you become the delivery boy

02:55:20.100 --> 02:55:21.900
[Guest]: network of India.

02:55:21.900 --> 02:55:26.460
[Guest]: And though, you know, nobody else can compete with you, because everybody else has an interest

02:55:26.460 --> 02:55:27.900
[Guest]: rate to fight against.

02:55:27.900 --> 02:55:32.540
[Guest]: So when you do that, you create a different set of incentives.

02:55:32.540 --> 02:55:37.060
[Guest]: Same way in stock markets, people have been incentivized to invest, when they've invested,

02:55:37.060 --> 02:55:40.740
[Guest]: the stock market's gone up, and around the world, it's not just in India.

02:55:40.740 --> 02:55:43.940
[Guest]: So around the world, also, they have discovered, oh, India is an interesting phenomenon, let's

02:55:43.940 --> 02:55:44.940
[Guest]: invest there.

02:55:44.940 --> 02:55:48.420
[Guest]: They invest into a fund that invests in India, that money comes to India.

02:55:48.420 --> 02:55:54.980
[Guest]: In the last two months, that's November and December of 2020, 1,20,000 crores has come

02:55:54.980 --> 02:56:00.740
[Guest]: into the Indian stock markets from abroad, forget from India, 1,20,000 crores has come.

02:56:00.740 --> 02:56:07.820
[Guest]: And that massive 30% fall you saw in April, in March of 2020, during the COVID crisis,

02:56:07.820 --> 02:56:11.020
[Guest]: saw only 60,000 crores exit.

02:56:11.020 --> 02:56:13.780
[Guest]: So literally, twice that has come.

02:56:13.780 --> 02:56:19.300
[Guest]: And that is not even, okay, to give you an example of what 120,000 crores is, today,

02:56:19.300 --> 02:56:27.700
[Guest]: it's about maybe $16 billion, $16 billion is in a whole two month cycle, is nothing.

02:56:27.700 --> 02:56:35.620
[Guest]: And I say nothing because what the U.S. has printed in March or April together is $5 trillion

02:56:35.620 --> 02:56:37.620
[Guest]: or something like that.

02:56:37.620 --> 02:56:44.460
[Guest]: Their first stimulus was $2 trillion, that is nearly 100 times more than what India received

02:56:44.460 --> 02:56:48.820
[Guest]: as foreign investment in the stock markets in the last two months.

02:56:48.820 --> 02:56:55.460
[Guest]: So the scale of things is that India is so tiny that even if you throw it what are crumbs

02:56:55.460 --> 02:57:00.100
[Guest]: from outside, now India gets about 1% of worldwide capital, okay?

02:57:00.100 --> 02:57:03.700
[Guest]: So if new capital that has been printed, money that has been printed is $5 trillion, India

02:57:03.700 --> 02:57:08.660
[Guest]: should get a $50 billion check at some point, I mean, together, added up, out of which only

02:57:08.660 --> 02:57:09.660
[Guest]: 16 has come.

02:57:09.660 --> 02:57:13.860
[Guest]: So you can imagine that if they've printed $5 trillion already, and they're promising

02:57:13.860 --> 02:57:19.780
[Guest]: to print more because there's a stimulus coming in the U.S., in Europe, in Britain, in Japan,

02:57:19.780 --> 02:57:22.780
[Guest]: there's always a stimulus that's like permanently stimulated.

02:57:22.780 --> 02:57:27.660
[Guest]: And then you've got all that money, 1% of that makes its way to India, just that 1%.

02:57:27.660 --> 02:57:31.740
[Guest]: Forget India being a big economy or whatever, just 1%.

02:57:31.740 --> 02:57:36.980
[Guest]: That would be 2 or 3x what India would receive in any great year.

02:57:36.980 --> 02:57:41.660
[Guest]: And that's going to keep these stock markets irrationally buoyant for a long time.

02:57:41.660 --> 02:57:46.100
[Guest]: So looking at it from a primarily, oh my God, we're trading at 40 times earnings and 50

02:57:46.100 --> 02:57:48.860
[Guest]: times earnings is one way to think about it.

02:57:48.860 --> 02:57:55.700
[Guest]: But the other way to think about it is to say, these guys keep printing this money.

02:57:55.700 --> 02:57:58.180
[Guest]: And whenever there's a crisis, they print more money.

02:57:58.180 --> 02:58:01.380
[Guest]: So at what point are you going to fight them?

02:58:01.380 --> 02:58:06.660
[Guest]: Maybe they'll keep printing it until I die, at which point my fight will be useless, right?

02:58:06.660 --> 02:58:13.340
[Guest]: So at some point, if your savings bank account gave you 0% returns, you would also be like,

02:58:13.340 --> 02:58:18.340
[Guest]: dude, put a little bit in stocks, and you'll watch it go up and you'll be happy about it.

02:58:18.340 --> 02:58:22.460
[Guest]: And when it goes down, of course, everybody curses the world.

02:58:22.460 --> 02:58:26.500
[Guest]: But nowadays, those down cycles last two months before central banks come together and say,

02:58:26.500 --> 02:58:28.420
[Guest]: dude, let's print our ass off and get.

02:58:28.420 --> 02:58:35.120
[Guest]: So I think that is a true explanation of where we are today.

02:58:35.120 --> 02:58:40.500
[Guest]: But I would hesitate to say that this is in any form permanent.

02:58:40.500 --> 02:58:44.900
[Guest]: Life changes very fast, very often, and more when you least expect it.

02:58:44.900 --> 02:58:49.140
[Guest]: So today, if you want to invest, I would say, just be careful.

02:58:49.140 --> 02:58:53.220
[Guest]: The music's playing, but you've got to be standing near the door.

02:58:53.220 --> 02:59:00.460
[Guest]: At some point in time, you know, I mean, it's easier, okay, let's put it this way.

02:59:00.460 --> 02:59:05.220
[Guest]: You would walk more carefully if you knew you were walking on eggs.

02:59:05.220 --> 02:59:10.180
[Guest]: So if you don't know that you're walking on eggs, you're in for surprise at some point,

02:59:10.180 --> 02:59:13.160
[Guest]: because they're hard boiled today, and the tomorrow's ones are not.

02:59:13.160 --> 02:59:17.940
[Guest]: So the questions that sometimes, and you know, Warren Buffett has this fantastic scene.

02:59:17.940 --> 02:59:22.140
[Guest]: I mean, I'm a big fan of his persona.

02:59:22.140 --> 02:59:25.980
[Guest]: Not so much of his investing philosophy, but from his persona itself.

02:59:25.980 --> 02:59:30.300
[Guest]: And the persona is great, because he makes these pithy one liners, which kind of embody

02:59:30.300 --> 02:59:33.980
[Guest]: so many things in that one sentence that you say, dude, I couldn't have done it myself.

02:59:33.980 --> 02:59:38.700
[Guest]: So he says, oh, it's only when the tide runs out that you find out who's swimming naked,

02:59:38.700 --> 02:59:39.700
[Guest]: right?

02:59:39.700 --> 02:59:42.220
[Guest]: So it's true in the stock market.

02:59:42.220 --> 02:59:46.980
[Guest]: You know, everybody's making money today, a jet airways, which hasn't flown off three

02:59:46.980 --> 02:59:52.100
[Guest]: years, two years, is still making new highs in the stock market today.

02:59:52.100 --> 02:59:56.260
[Guest]: And people are buying smoke, not necessarily mirrors.

02:59:56.260 --> 03:00:01.660
[Guest]: And I say, you know, today, even a pulse is optional, jet airways does not have a pulse.

03:00:01.660 --> 03:00:02.980
[Guest]: And it's making new highs.

03:00:02.980 --> 03:00:06.060
[Guest]: And in that kind of a market, you got to be careful.

03:00:06.060 --> 03:00:08.580
[Guest]: So things can break down at any point.

03:00:08.580 --> 03:00:14.660
[Guest]: And when it's going to be, but what I know is this is forever going to be interesting

03:00:14.660 --> 03:00:17.820
[Guest]: and perplexing at the same time.

03:00:17.820 --> 03:00:23.760
[Guest]: So you, you know, somebody told me this, naak bandh karke invest karo.

03:00:23.760 --> 03:00:29.580
[Guest]: This is one of those times when the only person who can do it is going to successfully close

03:00:29.580 --> 03:00:36.580
[Guest]: his nose and be aware that he's going to take his money out with a loss when he has to.

03:00:36.580 --> 03:00:41.020
[Guest]: But that the more irrational this market gets, it can get even more.

03:00:41.020 --> 03:00:47.540
[Guest]: Alan Greenspan had this saying that he said this, if stock prices are increasingly irrational,

03:00:47.540 --> 03:00:53.140
[Guest]: and I put out a tweet thread about this, which is that when he said it, the price was X,

03:00:53.140 --> 03:00:57.700
[Guest]: it went on to some 30% more, and then dropped 20%.

03:00:57.700 --> 03:01:03.740
[Guest]: The lowest point of the after that drop was still 10% higher than when he said it, then

03:01:03.740 --> 03:01:08.900
[Guest]: it went on to make another 50% higher, you imagine the frustration of this guy who's,

03:01:08.900 --> 03:01:13.540
[Guest]: I mean, who's looking at Greenspan and said, he's saying it irrational, it must be irrational.

03:01:13.540 --> 03:01:17.980
[Guest]: And for six years did not see prices come down to anywhere close to his level.

03:01:17.980 --> 03:01:22.940
[Guest]: So that's what I say that this is irrational as a market, it's happening because of the

03:01:22.940 --> 03:01:27.380
[Guest]: glut of liquidity, you're fighting the central bankers by saying I won't invest when the

03:01:27.380 --> 03:01:34.220
[Guest]: market valuations are so high, and therefore, your strategy should be a completely different

03:01:34.220 --> 03:01:35.220
[Guest]: one.

03:01:35.220 --> 03:01:36.220
[Guest]: Be careful.

03:01:36.220 --> 03:01:37.220
[Guest]: That's what I would say.

03:01:37.220 --> 03:01:40.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, there's also that other pithy one liner about how the market can stay irrational

03:01:40.980 --> 03:01:43.260
[Amit Varma]: longer than you can stay solvent.

03:01:43.260 --> 03:01:47.860
[Amit Varma]: So if you're planning to kind of fight the irrationality, let me kind of process this

03:01:47.860 --> 03:01:49.540
[Amit Varma]: consequence of printing money.

03:01:49.540 --> 03:01:54.340
[Amit Varma]: Now, typically, what we are taught in microeconomics and is broadly true is that if you increase

03:01:54.340 --> 03:01:57.780
[Amit Varma]: the money supply, inflation happens.

03:01:57.780 --> 03:02:00.780
[Amit Varma]: Because if you're just going to print money, money supply goes up relative to the goods

03:02:00.780 --> 03:02:02.500
[Amit Varma]: and services that are available.

03:02:02.500 --> 03:02:06.940
[Amit Varma]: So inflation happen and inflation is, of course, a tax on the poor, because the poor are having

03:02:06.940 --> 03:02:07.940
[Amit Varma]: to pay more.

03:02:07.940 --> 03:02:12.220
[Amit Varma]: Now, as you've pointed out in the real world, over the last 10 years, printing money hasn't

03:02:12.220 --> 03:02:17.780
[Amit Varma]: really led to that kind of real world inflation, possibly because of factors like growing productivity

03:02:17.780 --> 03:02:20.980
[Amit Varma]: and technology making things cheaper at the same time, and so on.

03:02:20.980 --> 03:02:26.860
[Amit Varma]: So you could say that, given that in the counterfactual, things would possibly have been even cheaper,

03:02:26.860 --> 03:02:31.940
[Amit Varma]: that this is an unseen kind of inflation, that, you know, doesn't result in prices necessarily

03:02:31.940 --> 03:02:35.340
[Amit Varma]: moving up, but in being higher than they otherwise would be.

03:02:35.340 --> 03:02:41.580
[Amit Varma]: So a lot of this is entering, sort of keeping the stock market going, that is possibly sort

03:02:41.580 --> 03:02:47.620
[Amit Varma]: of the scene inflation, as it were, you know, what are, you know, and it just, again, strikes

03:02:47.620 --> 03:02:51.140
[Amit Varma]: me and, you know, I don't know the subject in much depth, so I'm asking you, but it seems

03:02:51.140 --> 03:02:54.900
[Amit Varma]: to me that at some point, something's got to give, or is it the case that governments

03:02:54.900 --> 03:02:59.220
[Amit Varma]: can just keep printing money every time there's a crisis, they'll get together, lower the

03:02:59.220 --> 03:03:03.820
[Amit Varma]: interest rate, print more money and keep the dance going on, as it were, or do you think

03:03:03.820 --> 03:03:04.820
[Amit Varma]: something's got to give?

03:03:04.820 --> 03:03:06.180
[Guest]: What is your sense of what's happening?

03:03:06.180 --> 03:03:13.140
[Guest]: So interestingly, I have a very, very slightly different take on this, or explanatory ways.

03:03:13.140 --> 03:03:17.380
[Guest]: Printing money tends to end rent seeking.

03:03:17.380 --> 03:03:22.780
[Guest]: It's interesting because when you have a situation where, let's say, Uber, I'll give you an example.

03:03:22.780 --> 03:03:25.940
[Guest]: Uber would never have come up any other way.

03:03:25.940 --> 03:03:31.980
[Guest]: If I had to buy all of these cars and provide a decent return to my investors, I would not

03:03:31.980 --> 03:03:32.980
[Guest]: be running an Uber.

03:03:32.980 --> 03:03:34.740
[Guest]: It's just not possible.

03:03:34.740 --> 03:03:41.660
[Guest]: What does Uber do is promises drivers an extremely high return, promises taxi takers or people

03:03:41.660 --> 03:03:47.460
[Guest]: like us an extremely low price, and bridges the gap by making losses, funded by people

03:03:47.460 --> 03:03:52.900
[Guest]: who say, listen, just go ahead and do this until people realize that they can't live

03:03:52.900 --> 03:03:53.900
[Guest]: without the service.

03:03:53.900 --> 03:03:56.340
[Guest]: They sell their own cars and survive on you.

03:03:56.340 --> 03:04:00.860
[Guest]: So now your marginal cost of revenue, so you can reduce the amount you give your drivers

03:04:00.860 --> 03:04:04.740
[Guest]: a little bit, increase the fares a little bit, and you reach this extreme profitability

03:04:04.740 --> 03:04:08.780
[Guest]: because you have the market size that you wanted.

03:04:08.780 --> 03:04:11.020
[Guest]: This would never have been possible with a high interest rate economy.

03:04:11.020 --> 03:04:15.620
[Guest]: And you have money printing of this magnitude simply by saying that people have to invest

03:04:15.620 --> 03:04:16.620
[Guest]: in risky avenues.

03:04:16.620 --> 03:04:19.100
[Guest]: You make such businesses possible.

03:04:19.100 --> 03:04:23.580
[Guest]: You increase productivity effectively because what you've done is introduced a far more

03:04:23.580 --> 03:04:29.460
[Guest]: productive layer called the Uber taxi than the old taxi, which did not have any.

03:04:29.460 --> 03:04:33.500
[Guest]: So in Bombay, you had to go out and stick a finger out and you'd get a taxi.

03:04:33.500 --> 03:04:36.500
[Guest]: In Bangalore, your finger would be stuck there forever.

03:04:36.500 --> 03:04:38.540
[Guest]: It would, there's just no way to, you know.

03:04:38.540 --> 03:04:42.580
[Guest]: So now Uber's evened out things for places that didn't have the Bombay taxis.

03:04:42.580 --> 03:04:47.940
[Guest]: And even the Bombay taxis, you had those old Fiat cars because they gave the taxi license

03:04:47.940 --> 03:04:50.600
[Guest]: according to the car, not according to the driver.

03:04:50.600 --> 03:04:52.620
[Guest]: So you can't get rid of those cars.

03:04:52.620 --> 03:04:57.060
[Guest]: And those people are like, because they have the license, they can't give it up.

03:04:57.060 --> 03:04:58.420
[Guest]: They can't get a new car.

03:04:58.420 --> 03:04:59.740
[Guest]: So what they do is they keep the car on.

03:04:59.740 --> 03:05:04.580
[Guest]: So you get a car where you have the stick shift, which nobody has seen since 1977.

03:05:04.580 --> 03:05:07.500
[Guest]: And those are the cars you continue to have in Bombay.

03:05:07.500 --> 03:05:13.100
[Guest]: That's because of a screwed up rule that allows a municipality to give power to one agency,

03:05:13.100 --> 03:05:17.780
[Guest]: which is that whatever the taxi giving agency is, license giving, to determine a rule that

03:05:17.780 --> 03:05:18.780
[Guest]: said.

03:05:18.780 --> 03:05:23.820
[Guest]: So I was saying that the taxi network that we saw automated in this fashion was all in

03:05:23.820 --> 03:05:26.380
[Guest]: some way, the result of cheap money.

03:05:26.380 --> 03:05:31.020
[Guest]: Cheap money has resulted in the largest companies in the world being debt free.

03:05:31.020 --> 03:05:32.860
[Guest]: Can you imagine what that means?

03:05:32.860 --> 03:05:35.100
[Guest]: We made debt cheap.

03:05:35.100 --> 03:05:40.700
[Guest]: And today, Apple, Amazon, Microsoft, Google have no borrowings, or Apple has some because

03:05:40.700 --> 03:05:42.220
[Guest]: of some tax bullshit.

03:05:42.220 --> 03:05:46.240
[Guest]: But net net, they have $140 billion in cash or something like that.

03:05:46.240 --> 03:05:50.060
[Guest]: So it's unimaginable, because this is that counterintuitive thing.

03:05:50.060 --> 03:05:54.420
[Guest]: How can you make debt almost zero cost?

03:05:54.420 --> 03:05:57.700
[Guest]: And yet the largest companies in the world, our companies are debt free.

03:05:57.700 --> 03:06:03.100
[Guest]: Reliance in India used this opportunity to make itself net debt free.

03:06:03.100 --> 03:06:07.220
[Guest]: It owes banks money because the banks needed to owe them money.

03:06:07.220 --> 03:06:11.220
[Guest]: Because if you take away Reliance's debt, the banking system is in bad shape and they

03:06:11.220 --> 03:06:16.180
[Guest]: want the companies like Reliance not to give back their loans.

03:06:16.180 --> 03:06:22.900
[Guest]: So Reliance has, you know, 150,000 crores in cash, 150,000 crores in loans and net zero.

03:06:22.900 --> 03:06:28.340
[Guest]: The printing of money has actually made companies less dependent on debt.

03:06:28.340 --> 03:06:29.340
[Guest]: And that also makes sense.

03:06:29.340 --> 03:06:34.000
[Guest]: To give you an example, if you have an economy with 10 people owing each other money.

03:06:34.000 --> 03:06:38.500
[Guest]: So I use a hairdresser, I owe him money, the hairdresser owes a cyclist, owes him money

03:06:38.500 --> 03:06:41.860
[Guest]: and the cyclist owes the shop, owes him money and the shop owes me money.

03:06:41.860 --> 03:06:43.640
[Guest]: Technically, all of us are in debt.

03:06:43.640 --> 03:06:47.940
[Guest]: If one person were to get paid, they pay back their loans to everybody else, suddenly the

03:06:47.940 --> 03:06:49.460
[Guest]: economy is net debt free.

03:06:49.460 --> 03:06:51.740
[Guest]: So that does not happen.

03:06:51.740 --> 03:06:56.380
[Guest]: The governments have absorbed a bulk of the debt, countries still have or people still

03:06:56.380 --> 03:07:01.220
[Guest]: have a large amount of debt, which is why this phenomenon of cutting out the messenger,

03:07:01.220 --> 03:07:07.500
[Guest]: cutting out the middleman, cutting out the rent seeker is what the cheap money is doing.

03:07:07.500 --> 03:07:10.340
[Guest]: This is also why inflation is not coming up.

03:07:10.340 --> 03:07:14.020
[Guest]: Because every time you cut a middleman, you improve productivity.

03:07:14.020 --> 03:07:18.460
[Guest]: That productivity increase corresponds to a slightly higher.

03:07:18.460 --> 03:07:23.220
[Guest]: So to give you the analogy, let's say there was a place with only one bank, there were

03:07:23.220 --> 03:07:29.340
[Guest]: 100 people making widgets of some sort, there are 100 widgets, and each widget costs one

03:07:29.340 --> 03:07:30.340
[Guest]: rupee.

03:07:30.340 --> 03:07:32.380
[Guest]: So there's 100 rupees in the system.

03:07:32.380 --> 03:07:37.180
[Guest]: Somebody finds a way to make everybody produce two widgets instead.

03:07:37.180 --> 03:07:42.180
[Guest]: Now there's 200 widgets, there is no 200 rupees to pay for it.

03:07:42.180 --> 03:07:44.860
[Guest]: So the price of the widget falls to 50 paisa.

03:07:44.860 --> 03:07:49.340
[Guest]: So the price comes down because of the increase in productivity.

03:07:49.340 --> 03:07:51.940
[Guest]: So that's what they call real GDP growth, right?

03:07:51.940 --> 03:07:55.780
[Guest]: When they say real GDP growth is the fact that your productivity has increased from

03:07:55.780 --> 03:07:56.780
[Guest]: 100 to 200.

03:07:56.780 --> 03:08:00.060
[Guest]: So you're 100% real GDP growth.

03:08:00.060 --> 03:08:05.700
[Guest]: The nominal growth is zero in this case, because the prices went down to half.

03:08:05.700 --> 03:08:08.720
[Guest]: What if I printed another 100 rupees?

03:08:08.720 --> 03:08:12.820
[Guest]: Now I would have 200 rupees for 200 widgets, and the price would remain the same.

03:08:12.820 --> 03:08:15.660
[Guest]: Okay, what if I printed 300 rupees instead?

03:08:15.660 --> 03:08:18.600
[Guest]: Now I would have 400 rupees and 200 widgets.

03:08:18.600 --> 03:08:21.720
[Guest]: And therefore the price has increased from one rupee to two rupees per widget.

03:08:21.720 --> 03:08:27.260
[Guest]: So this is the various macroeconomic factors playing over here, productivity and increase

03:08:27.260 --> 03:08:28.260
[Guest]: in money supply.

03:08:28.260 --> 03:08:31.980
[Guest]: Right now what's happened is they've increased money supply in a way that hasn't made its

03:08:31.980 --> 03:08:34.060
[Guest]: way to the economy.

03:08:34.060 --> 03:08:38.220
[Guest]: So a lot of money sits in the banks and with the central banks.

03:08:38.220 --> 03:08:41.780
[Guest]: What has made its way to the economy is getting offset by the productivity benefits of cheap

03:08:41.780 --> 03:08:43.220
[Guest]: money.

03:08:43.220 --> 03:08:48.100
[Guest]: So the inflation that we expected to see is simply not there.

03:08:48.100 --> 03:08:54.760
[Guest]: But it has resulted in, so the one place that it is not coming is in asset prices, which

03:08:54.760 --> 03:09:03.340
[Guest]: means that real estate prices went up when you first reduced money supply, and that was

03:09:03.340 --> 03:09:05.860
[Guest]: a big bubble and that thing went bust.

03:09:05.860 --> 03:09:08.560
[Guest]: You had then stock prices.

03:09:08.560 --> 03:09:13.880
[Guest]: Stock prices went up, they went down because of COVID, not because of an extreme amount

03:09:13.880 --> 03:09:16.220
[Guest]: of these things, an external event to do it.

03:09:16.220 --> 03:09:18.700
[Guest]: They printed more money, stock prices are back up.

03:09:18.700 --> 03:09:23.380
[Guest]: So asset prices have not seen any productivity benefits because there's only positive feedback

03:09:23.380 --> 03:09:24.380
[Guest]: loops, unfortunately.

03:09:24.380 --> 03:09:25.860
[Guest]: There's no negative feedback loops.

03:09:25.860 --> 03:09:30.360
[Guest]: It's like when everybody is listing their own companies and making them go public is

03:09:30.360 --> 03:09:33.860
[Guest]: when you might actually see some kind of correction to this phenomenon.

03:09:33.860 --> 03:09:36.660
[Guest]: But as I said, people watch the stock market.

03:09:36.660 --> 03:09:40.100
[Guest]: So earlier the stock markets were the barometer.

03:09:40.100 --> 03:09:42.360
[Guest]: Now you want to influence the barometer.

03:09:42.360 --> 03:09:47.140
[Guest]: So I want the temperature to read 90 degrees because earlier you were measuring 90 degrees

03:09:47.140 --> 03:09:48.140
[Guest]: and telling me I was healthy.

03:09:48.140 --> 03:09:52.900
[Guest]: So I won't let it go below 90 degrees.

03:09:52.900 --> 03:10:00.340
[Guest]: So it's like in India, this current government tells us the data that we want to see.

03:10:00.340 --> 03:10:03.060
[Guest]: And it's true of past governments as well in different ways.

03:10:03.060 --> 03:10:07.140
[Guest]: But suddenly you know that a lot of the data is not really trustworthy.

03:10:07.140 --> 03:10:09.220
[Guest]: That's because it's a flexibility at work.

03:10:09.220 --> 03:10:12.540
[Guest]: And the same thing with asset prices, they're not letting it come down because it will make

03:10:12.540 --> 03:10:13.540
[Guest]: them look bad.

03:10:13.540 --> 03:10:14.540
[Guest]: And they have the power to do this.

03:10:14.540 --> 03:10:16.020
[Guest]: At one point, they will not.

03:10:16.020 --> 03:10:21.380
[Guest]: Bitcoin is perhaps the geek answer to this, saying if you increase the price of everything,

03:10:21.380 --> 03:10:24.460
[Guest]: I will buy something that, you know, protects me.

03:10:24.460 --> 03:10:26.140
[Guest]: But protects you from what?

03:10:26.140 --> 03:10:27.140
[Guest]: It protects you from nothing.

03:10:27.140 --> 03:10:33.180
[Guest]: It's just basically another invention of human beings that is currently not controlled by

03:10:33.180 --> 03:10:34.180
[Guest]: anybody.

03:10:34.180 --> 03:10:37.180
[Guest]: When I say currently, I mean that there are plans for people to control it.

03:10:37.180 --> 03:10:39.300
[Guest]: There's technology that allows people to control it.

03:10:39.300 --> 03:10:44.380
[Guest]: But when you have asset price inflation like this, so to give you an idea of what happened

03:10:44.380 --> 03:10:49.980
[Guest]: in hyperinflation, in Russia once there was, for a short period of time in 2014, before

03:10:49.980 --> 03:10:54.820
[Guest]: that we used to see that in Zimbabwe, when you had hyperinflation, people went and bought

03:10:54.820 --> 03:10:55.820
[Guest]: real assets.

03:10:55.820 --> 03:11:01.980
[Guest]: When I say real asset, I mean cars, iPhones, pens, expensive pens, because they retained

03:11:01.980 --> 03:11:05.540
[Guest]: value even through the inflationary scenario.

03:11:05.540 --> 03:11:09.820
[Guest]: That aspect is just translate that into, boss, they're printing money like crazy, let's just

03:11:09.820 --> 03:11:11.660
[Guest]: go buy stocks.

03:11:11.660 --> 03:11:12.660
[Guest]: That's what is happening.

03:11:12.660 --> 03:11:17.780
[Guest]: There is hyperinflation in asset prices, but we don't care because we don't have to consume

03:11:17.780 --> 03:11:18.780
[Amit Varma]: asset prices.

03:11:18.780 --> 03:11:23.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, what kind of strikes me here is that politics gets into this and therefore

03:11:23.780 --> 03:11:27.900
[Amit Varma]: narratives get into this because like you said, once it becomes a barometer, like anything

03:11:27.900 --> 03:11:29.900
[Amit Varma]: that becomes a metric can be gamed.

03:11:29.900 --> 03:11:32.620
[Amit Varma]: For example, at one point, the GDP became a metric.

03:11:32.620 --> 03:11:37.020
[Amit Varma]: The economy is a economy doing well, and therefore it is in the government's interest to game

03:11:37.020 --> 03:11:38.020
[Amit Varma]: the GDP.

03:11:38.020 --> 03:11:41.020
[Amit Varma]: And it's easy for the government to gain the GDP because government spending is a part

03:11:41.020 --> 03:11:42.020
[Amit Varma]: of GDP.

03:11:42.020 --> 03:11:46.300
[Amit Varma]: So it can dig up a million ditches and fill them up and your GDP goes up.

03:11:46.300 --> 03:11:48.460
[Amit Varma]: And there are various other ways to gain the GDP.

03:11:48.460 --> 03:11:53.100
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, it seems to me that if people are looking at stock market prices, as a metric

03:11:53.100 --> 03:11:57.100
[Amit Varma]: by which you sort of judge how well the economy is doing, that's also easy to game, just print

03:11:57.100 --> 03:11:58.100
[Amit Varma]: more money, boom.

03:11:58.100 --> 03:12:01.900
[Amit Varma]: And you know, because of all of these other factors and these positive feedback loops

03:12:01.900 --> 03:12:06.540
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, it isn't actually reflecting on the ground and there's no hyperinflation

03:12:06.540 --> 03:12:07.540
[Amit Varma]: as of yet.

03:12:07.540 --> 03:12:13.020
[Amit Varma]: But who knows what unintended consequences and unseen effects lie waiting for us down

03:12:13.020 --> 03:12:14.020
[Amit Varma]: the road.

03:12:14.020 --> 03:12:18.220
[Amit Varma]: Maybe 10 years later, if we do an episode, we can discuss, yeah, if only we were known

03:12:18.220 --> 03:12:19.460
[Amit Varma]: at the time.

03:12:19.460 --> 03:12:21.180
[Amit Varma]: A few final questions.

03:12:21.180 --> 03:12:22.660
[Amit Varma]: And here's the thing.

03:12:22.660 --> 03:12:29.580
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I did an episode a few weeks back with the advertising guru Ambi Parmeswaran,

03:12:29.580 --> 03:12:31.860
[Amit Varma]: who's written a bunch of books on advertising.

03:12:31.860 --> 03:12:35.820
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I realized talking with him and talking earlier with Santosh Desai,

03:12:35.820 --> 03:12:41.820
[Amit Varma]: another advertising giant I had done an episode with, is that following the advertising of

03:12:41.820 --> 03:12:46.260
[Amit Varma]: the country, you can actually get a lot of insights into our society and our culture

03:12:46.260 --> 03:12:47.260
[Amit Varma]: and our economy.

03:12:47.260 --> 03:12:51.540
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, while talking to you, it strikes me that for someone who follows the stock

03:12:51.540 --> 03:12:56.980
[Amit Varma]: market as closely as you do, which is not just the world of perceptions and all of the

03:12:56.980 --> 03:13:01.460
[Amit Varma]: feedback loops that happen within, but a lot of it, you know, feeds down into the real

03:13:01.460 --> 03:13:02.460
[Amit Varma]: world.

03:13:02.460 --> 03:13:05.700
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the most obvious example of that was, you know, it's almost a quiz question where

03:13:05.700 --> 03:13:09.860
[Amit Varma]: three months ago, there was this chart which showed one company shares plunging down and

03:13:09.860 --> 03:13:12.000
[Amit Varma]: the other one plunging up on the same day.

03:13:12.000 --> 03:13:13.940
[Amit Varma]: And that was the day the vaccine was announced.

03:13:13.940 --> 03:13:16.780
[Amit Varma]: So one was Zoom and the other was some airline.

03:13:16.780 --> 03:13:19.900
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so that the real world is involved here.

03:13:19.900 --> 03:13:26.120
[Amit Varma]: And you're looking at investing and stock market so closely must have also given you

03:13:26.120 --> 03:13:30.540
[Amit Varma]: interesting bits of insight about our nation and our society.

03:13:30.540 --> 03:13:31.540
[Amit Varma]: Is that the case?

03:13:31.540 --> 03:13:33.140
[Guest]: And you know, would you like to share some of that?

03:13:33.140 --> 03:13:34.140
[Guest]: Oh, yes.

03:13:34.140 --> 03:13:41.560
[Guest]: I mean, if you think about the softwares we're using right now, we're looking at the operating

03:13:41.560 --> 03:13:46.140
[Guest]: systems on our cell phones, almost none of them have any listings in India.

03:13:46.140 --> 03:13:53.700
[Guest]: I mean, we, if you think about the early 2000s or late 1990s, the time that every product

03:13:53.700 --> 03:13:57.740
[Guest]: you use, you could buy it off the stock market, you could buy Hindustan Unilever, the soaps

03:13:57.740 --> 03:14:02.260
[Guest]: you use, you could buy, you know, so almost everything that you use was listed.

03:14:02.260 --> 03:14:05.320
[Guest]: Today, a lot of the stuff that you use is not listed in India.

03:14:05.320 --> 03:14:11.060
[Guest]: What do you get in Indian markets is a stark contrast to anything that you get in foreign

03:14:11.060 --> 03:14:12.060
[Guest]: markets.

03:14:12.060 --> 03:14:17.160
[Guest]: That means the best, the companies that we use today are almost all exclusively listed

03:14:17.160 --> 03:14:18.580
[Guest]: in the US.

03:14:18.580 --> 03:14:23.340
[Guest]: The companies that are listed in India are companies who you know about, but you, for

03:14:23.340 --> 03:14:27.260
[Guest]: instance, if I told you Tata Steel is a great company, yes, yes.

03:14:27.260 --> 03:14:30.860
[Guest]: But if I gave you 10 steel bars, I'm telling you, there is no way you would have figured

03:14:30.860 --> 03:14:34.420
[Guest]: out which one is from Tata Steel and which one is from GSW Steel.

03:14:34.420 --> 03:14:38.340
[Guest]: And of course, they try to print their names on it just to show the difference.

03:14:38.340 --> 03:14:40.460
[Guest]: But they behave exactly the same.

03:14:40.460 --> 03:14:46.460
[Guest]: The commodity products that drive a lot of the Indian top companies is coal, cement,

03:14:46.460 --> 03:14:49.180
[Guest]: oil and gas, and a bunch of things.

03:14:49.180 --> 03:14:53.420
[Guest]: One few companies are trying to break out of that loop has been something like Reliance,

03:14:53.420 --> 03:14:58.500
[Guest]: who's gone and done a Jio and a bunch of startup level investments.

03:14:58.500 --> 03:15:00.820
[Guest]: So there are few and far between.

03:15:00.820 --> 03:15:07.060
[Guest]: And to a very large extent, I say this quite often, perhaps you should go and go to a company's

03:15:07.060 --> 03:15:12.460
[Guest]: website and the number of companies website on which you can actually do a transaction

03:15:12.460 --> 03:15:18.100
[Guest]: to buy that company's products indicates the level of technology that has permeated into

03:15:18.100 --> 03:15:19.700
[Guest]: an economy.

03:15:19.700 --> 03:15:23.700
[Guest]: In the last 10 years, perhaps that ratio in India has improved 10%.

03:15:23.700 --> 03:15:26.780
[Guest]: In the US, it's probably 90%.

03:15:26.780 --> 03:15:30.780
[Guest]: And that's quite amazing, because you could go to Zoom and buy Zoom as a product.

03:15:30.780 --> 03:15:34.380
[Guest]: In Reliance, of course, I think one of their website, many websites, you could actually

03:15:34.380 --> 03:15:37.580
[Guest]: buy stuff, but hardly any.

03:15:37.580 --> 03:15:40.780
[Guest]: So many of the others, you simply can't, they just give you information about who they are

03:15:40.780 --> 03:15:41.780
[Guest]: as a company.

03:15:41.780 --> 03:15:48.740
[Guest]: You could even go and visit a TCS or HCL tech company and at best, they'll tell you to contact

03:15:48.740 --> 03:15:49.740
[Guest]: them.

03:15:49.740 --> 03:15:53.820
[Guest]: But you couldn't download or use any of their products, even though they are tech companies.

03:15:53.820 --> 03:15:57.980
[Guest]: Even the technology savvy of them are not for you.

03:15:57.980 --> 03:16:01.980
[Guest]: So in a way, they're not reflective of the economy.

03:16:01.980 --> 03:16:03.980
[Guest]: The stock market is not for sure.

03:16:03.980 --> 03:16:07.720
[Guest]: That's why there's a dichotomy between the stock market and the real economy.

03:16:07.720 --> 03:16:11.460
[Guest]: Because a lot of the products that people use on a regular basis, even the Indian ones

03:16:11.460 --> 03:16:12.460
[Guest]: are not listed.

03:16:12.460 --> 03:16:18.740
[Guest]: We use Zomato, Swiggy, BTM, I don't know, there are a bunch of things that we do.

03:16:18.740 --> 03:16:20.220
[Guest]: None of them are listed in India.

03:16:20.220 --> 03:16:23.900
[Guest]: Some of them don't want to be listed in India, some of them can't because of our rules.

03:16:23.900 --> 03:16:31.220
[Guest]: So our stock market really determines the kind of influence technology has had in our

03:16:31.220 --> 03:16:32.220
[Guest]: lives.

03:16:32.220 --> 03:16:36.140
[Guest]: I have a lot of hope, because I feel that the next era is going to be where technology

03:16:36.140 --> 03:16:37.860
[Guest]: companies take over the Indian economy.

03:16:37.860 --> 03:16:44.860
[Guest]: But you can see the level of sophistication in that economy by just looking at how evolved

03:16:44.860 --> 03:16:47.900
[Guest]: the companies are from a tech basis, even if they're not tech companies.

03:16:47.900 --> 03:16:49.620
[Guest]: I mean, Zomato is not a tech company.

03:16:49.620 --> 03:16:53.780
[Guest]: They're a company that has an app, but that primarily does delivery, right?

03:16:53.780 --> 03:17:00.220
[Guest]: So Tesla, on the other hand, is a technology company that also sells cars, which is such

03:17:00.220 --> 03:17:06.060
[Guest]: a difference, because you can't say that of almost any company in India, original R&D

03:17:06.060 --> 03:17:09.300
[Guest]: and stuff like that, it's not like we don't have the brains.

03:17:09.300 --> 03:17:12.980
[Guest]: It's just that for some reason, we haven't gotten there yet.

03:17:12.980 --> 03:17:18.180
[Guest]: And maybe that happens when India becomes a bigger economy, $5 trillion.

03:17:18.180 --> 03:17:22.140
[Amit Varma]: I mean, is India being, you know, low down the value chain and the kind of things that

03:17:22.140 --> 03:17:25.780
[Amit Varma]: we do so much of commodity and not enough innovation?

03:17:25.780 --> 03:17:30.980
[Amit Varma]: Is that partly because of cultural factors like risk aversion and all that?

03:17:30.980 --> 03:17:34.700
[Amit Varma]: Or is it because of regulatory environment or governance?

03:17:34.700 --> 03:17:36.420
[Amit Varma]: What do you think are the reasons behind it?

03:17:36.420 --> 03:17:38.060
[Amit Varma]: And is that something that you see changing?

03:17:38.060 --> 03:17:40.020
[Guest]: Yes, I think the reason is simple.

03:17:40.020 --> 03:17:41.500
[Guest]: It's high interest rates.

03:17:41.500 --> 03:17:45.340
[Guest]: Today, informal interest rates are still 24% a year.

03:17:45.340 --> 03:17:47.420
[Guest]: Of course, credit cards worldwide jib people.

03:17:47.420 --> 03:17:50.220
[Guest]: So that's a that's a horrible metric to look at.

03:17:50.220 --> 03:17:54.260
[Guest]: But you go to a bank, they don't want to give you a loan less than 12%.

03:17:54.260 --> 03:17:57.260
[Guest]: Now they're saying, okay, home loans at six and a half percent.

03:17:57.260 --> 03:17:59.460
[Guest]: Somebody recently talked about some other loans at 8%.

03:17:59.460 --> 03:18:03.020
[Guest]: But the first time I'm starting to hear of them, and these banks are borrowing it, you

03:18:03.020 --> 03:18:07.420
[Guest]: know, 3% or 4%, there's no competition in that banking sector.

03:18:07.420 --> 03:18:12.420
[Guest]: And until now, it has not been prudent for people to actually try to take risks.

03:18:12.420 --> 03:18:14.420
[Guest]: I wrote a blog post in 2006.

03:18:14.420 --> 03:18:21.260
[Guest]: I had no idea this would happen, that my expenses would inflate at roughly 6% a year.

03:18:21.260 --> 03:18:25.220
[Guest]: I looked at that blog post yesterday, I said, shit, let me see how much my expenses are

03:18:25.220 --> 03:18:26.220
[Guest]: today.

03:18:26.220 --> 03:18:29.220
[Guest]: And you know what, it's it's inflated 5.1% a year.

03:18:29.220 --> 03:18:30.220
[Guest]: Not not bad.

03:18:30.220 --> 03:18:35.700
[Guest]: Which is, and at that time, when I wrote 6% a year, people told me doesn't 6% too less

03:18:35.700 --> 03:18:37.020
[Guest]: India's inflation is 10.

03:18:37.020 --> 03:18:41.780
[Guest]: I said, No, but my inflation is different from India's inflation, because the product

03:18:41.780 --> 03:18:43.480
[Guest]: basket I use is different.

03:18:43.480 --> 03:18:47.220
[Guest]: So I think my core inflation, I mean, not count, I didn't have kids at the time.

03:18:47.220 --> 03:18:52.340
[Guest]: So I said, not counting kids school expenses, have you factored in the piano, piano came

03:18:52.340 --> 03:18:57.780
[Guest]: free, I bought it in 2000, remember.

03:18:57.780 --> 03:19:03.340
[Guest]: So so but interestingly, the inflation that I have, I mean, I'm talking minus school fees

03:19:03.340 --> 03:19:10.300
[Guest]: is so your with inflation being at 5%, I was able to get eight to 9% interest rates at

03:19:10.300 --> 03:19:14.220
[Guest]: that time, till two years ago, I think it was eight to 9%, maybe two, three years, seven

03:19:14.220 --> 03:19:15.220
[Guest]: or eight percent.

03:19:15.220 --> 03:19:18.700
[Guest]: So my inflation on a personal level is 5%.

03:19:18.700 --> 03:19:19.700
[Guest]: And I'm getting 7%.

03:19:19.700 --> 03:19:21.580
[Guest]: Why do I need to take risks?

03:19:21.580 --> 03:19:27.420
[Guest]: If that were to change, and you're fighting against somebody else, who has to compete,

03:19:27.420 --> 03:19:32.940
[Guest]: not against a 12% interest rate, but against a 5% interest rate, which is perhaps China

03:19:32.940 --> 03:19:38.180
[Guest]: or America or things like that, it's no wonder they'll win, because they have to earn lesser

03:19:38.180 --> 03:19:41.020
[Guest]: profits and they can beat you on price.

03:19:41.020 --> 03:19:46.420
[Guest]: So we then stop imports, because come on, how can they have cheaper products than ours?

03:19:46.420 --> 03:19:50.140
[Guest]: But the answer is, you know, they have cheaper products by the lower interest rates, we've

03:19:50.140 --> 03:19:54.420
[Guest]: screwed up, and we've managed to control inflation to a very large extent till last year, but

03:19:54.420 --> 03:19:57.380
[Guest]: we steadfastly kept our rates too high.

03:19:57.380 --> 03:20:02.220
[Guest]: And that has resulted, according to me, in us being extremely non-competitive.

03:20:02.220 --> 03:20:03.220
[Guest]: It's one of the factors.

03:20:03.220 --> 03:20:07.380
[Guest]: There are hundreds of other factors, regulatory overload, you can't start an investment company

03:20:07.380 --> 03:20:08.380
[Guest]: in India.

03:20:08.380 --> 03:20:13.260
[Guest]: I can't invest in Amit Verma without you perhaps even getting an income tax notice saying how

03:20:13.260 --> 03:20:17.980
[Guest]: the hell did Deepak Sinha invest in you at a high valuation, because you're doing fraud.

03:20:17.980 --> 03:20:22.520
[Guest]: This is how the regulatory and tax situations in India are.

03:20:22.520 --> 03:20:26.020
[Guest]: So that also contributes to this lack of this thing.

03:20:26.020 --> 03:20:31.780
[Guest]: But we are an extremely entrepreneurial country, and formal credit is available to very few

03:20:31.780 --> 03:20:36.060
[Guest]: people in order to start their businesses, and it's available at a very high cost.

03:20:36.060 --> 03:20:42.940
[Guest]: And these factors together, according to me, is why India loves the coal companies and

03:20:42.940 --> 03:20:44.420
[Guest]: just the large business.

03:20:44.420 --> 03:20:47.420
[Guest]: We still want big employers.

03:20:47.420 --> 03:20:48.420
[Guest]: Why?

03:20:48.420 --> 03:20:52.580
[Guest]: I mean, why can't we just exercise more of this?

03:20:52.580 --> 03:20:57.420
[Guest]: I mean, the reason Swiggy works is because each person thinks he's its own boss, because

03:20:57.420 --> 03:21:00.900
[Guest]: he's actually a rider, he's a consultant.

03:21:00.900 --> 03:21:03.100
[Guest]: He's not actually employed by Swiggy.

03:21:03.100 --> 03:21:08.140
[Guest]: And like this, we could create a billion or zillion different kinds of models.

03:21:08.140 --> 03:21:11.860
[Guest]: But we still love the fact that in one factory, there will be a thousand people, and a thousand

03:21:11.860 --> 03:21:14.140
[Guest]: people will get jobs.

03:21:14.140 --> 03:21:20.220
[Guest]: But that philosophy is why I think we continue to like our top players.

03:21:20.220 --> 03:21:23.460
[Guest]: And in a way, we have become a little bit more like Korea and Japan.

03:21:23.460 --> 03:21:28.460
[Guest]: We will rescue the top corporates and not let them go down.

03:21:28.460 --> 03:21:31.620
[Guest]: Japan did that with the top six Japanese companies.

03:21:31.620 --> 03:21:33.260
[Guest]: The Korean Chai Ball is famous.

03:21:33.260 --> 03:21:39.340
[Guest]: Samsung and LG continue to be the top kind of players in Korea.

03:21:39.340 --> 03:21:43.380
[Guest]: That's because those countries have said these guys are too big to fail, and we will bail

03:21:43.380 --> 03:21:45.020
[Guest]: them out at all costs.

03:21:45.020 --> 03:21:50.500
[Guest]: India has done it to all its banks, and to a lot of large corporates as well, which causes

03:21:50.500 --> 03:21:51.500
[Guest]: resentment.

03:21:51.500 --> 03:21:57.460
[Guest]: But more like they hate people who come and disrupt those people's businesses as well.

03:21:57.460 --> 03:22:09.860
[Guest]: So that is the philosophy of the thought process.

03:22:09.860 --> 03:22:16.820
[Guest]: And I use Hindi there for a reason, because it's almost become Indian, in the sense that

03:22:16.820 --> 03:22:18.740
[Guest]: the philosophy is more Indian.

03:22:18.740 --> 03:22:23.180
[Guest]: Because in America, you would let companies, I mean, till last year, you would have let

03:22:23.180 --> 03:22:24.180
[Guest]: companies fail.

03:22:24.180 --> 03:22:26.620
[Guest]: Now there also, they don't let companies fail.

03:22:26.620 --> 03:22:31.020
[Guest]: But failure, unfortunately, is considered.

03:22:31.020 --> 03:22:37.340
[Guest]: So these companies will go down because some companies will have to come and become better

03:22:37.340 --> 03:22:39.940
[Guest]: than them, not that these companies will fail.

03:22:39.940 --> 03:22:41.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, it's tragic.

03:22:41.300 --> 03:22:44.700
[Amit Varma]: And when you talk about rescuing these big companies, what is happening is that their

03:22:44.700 --> 03:22:48.640
[Amit Varma]: profits are being privatized, but their losses are being socialized, which basically means

03:22:48.640 --> 03:22:53.380
[Amit Varma]: it comes down on us and on our taxes, which remember is part-time slavery, instead of

03:22:53.380 --> 03:22:58.220
[Amit Varma]: working from January to March, you'll have to work for a few days of April for the government

03:22:58.220 --> 03:22:59.220
[Amit Varma]: for free also.

03:22:59.220 --> 03:23:01.140
[Amit Varma]: That is what gulami is, my good friend.

03:23:01.140 --> 03:23:02.780
[Amit Varma]: You think you're a free person?

03:23:02.780 --> 03:23:03.780
[Amit Varma]: No, you aren't.

03:23:03.780 --> 03:23:07.460
[Amit Varma]: So I have sort of three final questions for you before I let you go.

03:23:07.460 --> 03:23:09.300
[Amit Varma]: You've been very generous with your time.

03:23:09.300 --> 03:23:13.340
[Amit Varma]: And as both of us know enough economics to know that this has an opportunity cost.

03:23:13.340 --> 03:23:16.900
[Amit Varma]: So I'm very grateful that you're, you know, hanging out and chatting with me, though,

03:23:16.900 --> 03:23:21.080
[Amit Varma]: we could also point out that it's a positive sum game and we are both having fun.

03:23:21.080 --> 03:23:27.060
[Amit Varma]: So my third last question for you is basically this, that if the Deepak Chinnoy of 2021 could

03:23:27.060 --> 03:23:32.580
[Amit Varma]: meet the Deepak Chinnoy of 2001, and give him advice about these are my TILs over the

03:23:32.580 --> 03:23:38.340
[Amit Varma]: last 20 years, which will help you in your journey, both your investing journey and your

03:23:38.340 --> 03:23:40.460
[Amit Varma]: journey in general.

03:23:40.460 --> 03:23:42.820
[Amit Varma]: What would you tell young Deepak?

03:23:42.820 --> 03:23:48.380
[Guest]: Perhaps one thing that I mean, of course, my first feeling is to tell him all the stocks

03:23:48.380 --> 03:23:49.380
[Guest]: to buy.

03:23:49.380 --> 03:23:54.020
[Amit Varma]: So that, you know, by 2003, you can't be specific, just meta level stuff.

03:23:54.020 --> 03:23:56.380
[Guest]: But I mean, this is my problem, right?

03:23:56.380 --> 03:24:01.540
[Guest]: This is the stock market problem of people going from the future back to the past.

03:24:01.540 --> 03:24:08.580
[Guest]: But one of the things that I think people will, I mean, I would tell that person is

03:24:08.580 --> 03:24:14.260
[Guest]: I changed careers completely, I was a tech guy, I moved to finance, and it was a long

03:24:14.260 --> 03:24:17.900
[Guest]: period of fighting with myself before I changed it.

03:24:17.900 --> 03:24:24.620
[Guest]: And that period of that fight was very useless, because I could use my skills on the tech

03:24:24.620 --> 03:24:26.960
[Guest]: level in the finance world.

03:24:26.960 --> 03:24:32.980
[Guest]: And tech skills by themselves have a use in that they're only useful in some world that

03:24:32.980 --> 03:24:33.980
[Guest]: they build.

03:24:33.980 --> 03:24:38.220
[Guest]: It's only recently that tech can be useful by itself.

03:24:38.220 --> 03:24:40.420
[Guest]: But usually it helps some other industry.

03:24:40.420 --> 03:24:45.860
[Guest]: So to that extent, I think the person that I would say that I should become is to stop

03:24:45.860 --> 03:24:50.420
[Guest]: fighting those battles about what is the right way to proceed in the future.

03:24:50.420 --> 03:24:53.340
[Guest]: Now, in 2001, I was running a business.

03:24:53.340 --> 03:24:57.260
[Guest]: And that business was actually doing well, even though there was a downturn in the economy.

03:24:57.260 --> 03:25:03.740
[Guest]: And I believed at that point, a lot of those things that I thought would come true, just

03:25:03.740 --> 03:25:06.100
[Guest]: if I gave it time, it would.

03:25:06.100 --> 03:25:10.180
[Guest]: I think the new me would just say, listen, always set up a time frame.

03:25:10.180 --> 03:25:15.340
[Guest]: If things don't work out on those time frames, you're out, you need to be out, you need to.

03:25:15.340 --> 03:25:19.340
[Guest]: And maybe trading and markets have taught me that, that, you know, set up a stop loss.

03:25:19.340 --> 03:25:23.420
[Guest]: And if things don't work out by that time, you're out, that's the learning I would take

03:25:23.420 --> 03:25:25.520
[Guest]: to that time, because it was not intuitive.

03:25:25.520 --> 03:25:29.620
[Guest]: Because at that time, I thought, dude, I'm an engineer, I'm a smart guy, I can figure

03:25:29.620 --> 03:25:30.620
[Guest]: out anything.

03:25:30.620 --> 03:25:37.300
[Guest]: The role of luck is perhaps, you know, this is Uncle Me talking to Younger Me.

03:25:37.300 --> 03:25:41.900
[Guest]: And Younger Me would never listen to an Uncle Me.

03:25:41.900 --> 03:25:46.220
[Guest]: But really, it's like, appreciate the role of luck and create more opportunities for

03:25:46.220 --> 03:25:48.220
[Guest]: luck.

03:25:48.220 --> 03:25:52.140
[Guest]: So at some point in the middle, I had stopped that opportunity.

03:25:52.140 --> 03:25:57.860
[Guest]: And that landed up in a situation where in 2005, I was, you know, for a small period

03:25:57.860 --> 03:25:58.860
[Guest]: of time, bankrupt.

03:25:58.860 --> 03:26:03.300
[Guest]: When I say bankrupt, not really, I didn't owe anybody money, but I didn't have any money

03:26:03.300 --> 03:26:09.940
[Guest]: after seven years of working, I was a temporary phase, I borrowed money from my wife to kind

03:26:09.940 --> 03:26:11.860
[Guest]: of pay for a few things.

03:26:11.860 --> 03:26:17.300
[Guest]: But I don't think I kept that in mind when I was running the business that there is something

03:26:17.300 --> 03:26:18.300
[Guest]: beyond.

03:26:18.300 --> 03:26:21.700
[Guest]: For a guy who talks about personal finance and investing, I was a horrible investor.

03:26:21.700 --> 03:26:23.300
[Guest]: I'm the opposite of a lot of things.

03:26:23.300 --> 03:26:25.140
[Guest]: I tell people to save all the time.

03:26:25.140 --> 03:26:32.140
[Guest]: My entire future is dependent on the company I've built, or I've helped build, and which

03:26:32.140 --> 03:26:38.060
[Guest]: is that all of my bets are there, I tell people to diversify, but my bets are there, for the

03:26:38.060 --> 03:26:39.060
[Guest]: most part.

03:26:39.060 --> 03:26:44.940
[Guest]: So similarly, I think the learnings of what I'm doing right now, is that you got to build

03:26:44.940 --> 03:26:48.860
[Guest]: yourself a little bit more of a saving and a kitty, that you could have done more of

03:26:48.860 --> 03:26:53.340
[Guest]: your stuff that you want to do for passion, or that you stuff you really like, that can

03:26:53.340 --> 03:26:57.860
[Guest]: build you a great asset in the future, can happen earlier than you thought.

03:26:57.860 --> 03:27:02.980
[Guest]: You don't slavery to the government for four months, sometimes it's slavery to something

03:27:02.980 --> 03:27:04.620
[Guest]: else for 12 months.

03:27:04.620 --> 03:27:07.580
[Guest]: And to a lot of people, it's like, dude, I'm slaving off anyway, might as well slave for

03:27:07.580 --> 03:27:08.860
[Guest]: the government at the same time.

03:27:08.860 --> 03:27:14.740
[Guest]: So that was the philosophy that drove me to entrepreneurship multiple times.

03:27:14.740 --> 03:27:18.540
[Guest]: And perhaps in hindsight, I didn't have to go through, to be honest, like I said, the

03:27:18.540 --> 03:27:20.540
[Guest]: young me would just not listen to the old me.

03:27:20.540 --> 03:27:24.060
[Guest]: So whatever I say, I do it.

03:27:24.060 --> 03:27:31.420
[Guest]: I think more or less, you know, it's just sad, but that's perhaps I see that in my children

03:27:31.420 --> 03:27:33.980
[Guest]: now and I kind of admire them for it.

03:27:33.980 --> 03:27:39.140
[Guest]: Although I'm very frustrated sometimes, why not, why not, no dad, YouTube channel manager

03:27:39.140 --> 03:27:40.140
[Guest]: is a job.

03:27:40.140 --> 03:27:45.540
[Guest]: Okay, no, but yes, okay, it is perhaps because he shows me these numbers that these people

03:27:45.540 --> 03:27:46.540
[Guest]: make.

03:27:46.540 --> 03:27:52.140
[Guest]: And I'm like, that's not a job, but that's a lot of money, where, you know, I mean, that's

03:27:52.140 --> 03:27:58.980
[Guest]: just me being the same, but I tell you, sometimes not listening to people like me is a good

03:27:58.980 --> 03:27:59.980
[Amit Varma]: thing.

03:27:59.980 --> 03:28:00.980
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

03:28:00.980 --> 03:28:06.220
[Amit Varma]: So your uncle use advice to the younger you is don't listen to me, which is fantastically

03:28:06.220 --> 03:28:15.380
[Amit Varma]: meta in ways I can't even begin to describe a second last piece of advice.

03:28:15.380 --> 03:28:19.340
[Amit Varma]: Listeners of the show always want to know what books to read to learn more about a subject.

03:28:19.340 --> 03:28:24.300
[Amit Varma]: So if you are, say someone like me, intelligent lay person, I hope I can describe myself as

03:28:24.300 --> 03:28:28.180
[Amit Varma]: that intelligent lay person want to learn more about a subject.

03:28:28.180 --> 03:28:31.420
[Amit Varma]: You know, what are my first go to is not necessarily just books.

03:28:31.420 --> 03:28:33.100
[Amit Varma]: Maybe there's a YouTube series out there.

03:28:33.100 --> 03:28:34.100
[Amit Varma]: Maybe there's a MOOC somewhere.

03:28:34.100 --> 03:28:35.100
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

03:28:35.100 --> 03:28:39.940
[Amit Varma]: But if someone wants to learn about investing, what are the first steps that they should

03:28:39.940 --> 03:28:40.940
[Amit Varma]: take in your view?

03:28:40.940 --> 03:28:43.460
[Amit Varma]: Or what are the books that shaped you?

03:28:43.460 --> 03:28:49.060
[Guest]: This is actually incredibly difficult to answer, because I think I have both been led and misled

03:28:49.060 --> 03:28:52.180
[Guest]: by books.

03:28:52.180 --> 03:28:57.860
[Guest]: The unfortunate problem that you have with authority in this industry is that they do

03:28:57.860 --> 03:29:02.700
[Guest]: not accept that there are many right ways to solve the same problem and that money printing

03:29:02.700 --> 03:29:07.860
[Guest]: creates inflation and money printing does not create inflation are both correct at the

03:29:07.860 --> 03:29:10.920
[Guest]: same time, perhaps at the same place.

03:29:10.920 --> 03:29:16.340
[Guest]: So a lot of the theory is wrong in the sense that you don't have, I mean, not much of this

03:29:16.340 --> 03:29:17.340
[Guest]: is known.

03:29:17.340 --> 03:29:21.740
[Guest]: Sometimes you take some time to understand, but what I would say is my reading or my entire

03:29:21.740 --> 03:29:26.540
[Guest]: series of reading that's the stuff that started it, some of it no longer exists.

03:29:26.540 --> 03:29:33.460
[Guest]: So there was this lady, her name was Doris Dungy, she was called Tanta or Tanta, I don't

03:29:33.460 --> 03:29:39.060
[Guest]: know how it's pronounced, but there's a blog called calculatedriskblog.com.

03:29:39.060 --> 03:29:44.300
[Guest]: And to be honest, a lot of the stuff I learned around about things like mortgages and economic

03:29:44.300 --> 03:29:47.340
[Guest]: fundamentals were from that blog at that time.

03:29:47.340 --> 03:29:51.140
[Guest]: She unfortunately passed away from cancer and her writing, although survives in the

03:29:51.140 --> 03:29:55.940
[Guest]: blog is probably no longer relevant in a way that it used to be at the time.

03:29:55.940 --> 03:29:59.140
[Guest]: And she talked about the housing crisis before there was a housing crisis.

03:29:59.140 --> 03:30:04.520
[Guest]: She talked about mortgages and, you know, a lot of the understanding of my understanding

03:30:04.520 --> 03:30:07.180
[Guest]: of that field at that time was from there.

03:30:07.180 --> 03:30:13.620
[Guest]: Another thing that I learned was that you read interviews and podcasts like ours, perhaps

03:30:13.620 --> 03:30:17.740
[Guest]: to get these little nuggets of information that you would otherwise find difficult for

03:30:17.740 --> 03:30:19.460
[Guest]: someone to paraphrase into a book.

03:30:19.460 --> 03:30:28.620
[Guest]: And there is a podcast called simply invest like the best by Patrick O'Shaughnessy.

03:30:28.620 --> 03:30:34.420
[Guest]: So it's a very interesting podcast on people investing nowadays, a lot of topics may not

03:30:34.420 --> 03:30:37.160
[Amit Varma]: be a book is by James O'Shaughnessy.

03:30:37.160 --> 03:30:40.620
[Guest]: Maybe this is his dad, I don't know.

03:30:40.620 --> 03:30:42.960
[Guest]: Of course, his dad is also a legendary investor.

03:30:42.960 --> 03:30:46.980
[Guest]: So he's also an investor, he runs a fund, but he also takes these podcasts with very

03:30:46.980 --> 03:30:50.620
[Guest]: interesting people and that I think has very interesting analysis.

03:30:50.620 --> 03:30:54.580
[Guest]: Now, the more you look at that podcast, the more you realize how different investing has

03:30:54.580 --> 03:31:00.180
[Guest]: become because a lot of the topics there are private company investing, Bitcoin, real estate,

03:31:00.180 --> 03:31:02.380
[Guest]: stocks, different kinds of stocks and so on.

03:31:02.380 --> 03:31:06.420
[Guest]: There's another set of books by a guy called Jack Schwager.

03:31:06.420 --> 03:31:12.100
[Guest]: These are books that actually initially attracted me to investing algorithmically.

03:31:12.100 --> 03:31:15.580
[Guest]: The book that I read about these turtles, the phenomenon that I talked to you about

03:31:15.580 --> 03:31:17.500
[Guest]: was written in 1990.

03:31:17.500 --> 03:31:20.740
[Guest]: This book, the first series, it's called Market Wizards.

03:31:20.740 --> 03:31:24.820
[Guest]: And there are about four or five hedge fund market wizards, stock market wizards.

03:31:24.820 --> 03:31:29.380
[Guest]: The first two in that book, Market Wizards and the New Market Wizards, talk about investing

03:31:29.380 --> 03:31:34.820
[Guest]: as a career and people who built their investing out of it is just purely interviews of them.

03:31:34.820 --> 03:31:38.820
[Guest]: If you want to learn about the history of the stock market in the US, and it's very

03:31:38.820 --> 03:31:43.820
[Guest]: interesting because India has parallels and India does not have a similar book, is a book

03:31:43.820 --> 03:31:46.060
[Guest]: called What Goes Up.

03:31:46.060 --> 03:31:47.460
[Guest]: It's a beautiful book.

03:31:47.460 --> 03:31:52.020
[Guest]: It just contains a lot of sayings and quotes by a lot of people through the various series.

03:31:52.020 --> 03:31:58.380
[Guest]: So right from 1929, just post 1929, to the start of Merrill Lynch in 1930, of course,

03:31:58.380 --> 03:32:03.100
[Guest]: it stops before Merrill Lynch was eliminated from history, but it's a very interesting

03:32:03.100 --> 03:32:05.740
[Guest]: history of the time of the US stock market.

03:32:05.740 --> 03:32:10.540
[Guest]: In India, there's a book called The Scam by Sucheta Dalal and Devashish Basu, which is

03:32:10.540 --> 03:32:11.540
[Guest]: phenomenal.

03:32:11.540 --> 03:32:17.420
[Guest]: I mean, you might have seen the series on Sony Life, but if you like economics, it may

03:32:17.420 --> 03:32:22.980
[Guest]: be a little daunting, but the amount of data in that is spectacular.

03:32:22.980 --> 03:32:27.060
[Guest]: It talks about so many things that I didn't know about in 1992.

03:32:27.060 --> 03:32:33.540
[Guest]: I now understand that subject a little bit more, but I think lots of credit to Sucheta

03:32:33.540 --> 03:32:38.660
[Guest]: and Devashish for actually simplifying going through and looking through all of that in

03:32:38.660 --> 03:32:39.660
[Guest]: that angle.

03:32:39.660 --> 03:32:43.820
[Guest]: So these are educational books from the perspective of, in the end of it, I could ask you five

03:32:43.820 --> 03:32:48.500
[Guest]: questions and you can answer them, but they put things across in a perspective that'll

03:32:48.500 --> 03:32:49.980
[Guest]: shape the way you are.

03:32:49.980 --> 03:32:55.300
[Guest]: So if you want purely, like the Benjamin Graham book you mentioned, which I have, I have tried

03:32:55.300 --> 03:32:56.300
[Guest]: seven times.

03:32:56.300 --> 03:32:58.580
[Guest]: I have not been able to go past at least 30 pages.

03:32:58.580 --> 03:33:02.580
[Guest]: This is my problem with Atlas Shrugged as well, so I'm sorry to Ayn Rand.

03:33:02.580 --> 03:33:06.460
[Guest]: I have not been able to go past 30 pages and it is my problem.

03:33:06.460 --> 03:33:11.340
[Guest]: Like Nasim Taleb's second book, Black Swan, that's the book, I haven't been able to get

03:33:11.340 --> 03:33:15.420
[Guest]: just past the book because at some point there are some things which I just can't read.

03:33:15.420 --> 03:33:18.900
[Guest]: But the interesting thing about those books is that the thought process is, I mean, it

03:33:18.900 --> 03:33:22.900
[Guest]: may not tell you what to invest in or why and all that stuff, but it'll give you an

03:33:22.900 --> 03:33:23.900
[Guest]: interesting thought process.

03:33:23.900 --> 03:33:27.340
[Guest]: So for instance, I don't agree with one book at all.

03:33:27.340 --> 03:33:34.860
[Guest]: Like there's this book by Robert Kiyosaki called, you know, Rich Dad, Poor Dad.

03:33:34.860 --> 03:33:39.660
[Guest]: I don't agree with a lot of concepts of that book, but one point which he makes, which

03:33:39.660 --> 03:33:44.860
[Guest]: is passive income and how it can change your life, that's worth carrying home.

03:33:44.860 --> 03:33:49.620
[Guest]: Sometimes you want to read people who do different things from what you say or what you think.

03:33:49.620 --> 03:33:54.540
[Guest]: So for instance, I may not like Warren Buffett's philosophies quite as much as, you know, as

03:33:54.540 --> 03:33:59.820
[Guest]: in his investing style, I'm not a value investor by the face of it.

03:33:59.820 --> 03:34:03.740
[Guest]: But I think a lot of his sayings have a lot of very interesting answers.

03:34:03.740 --> 03:34:07.780
[Guest]: So one of the statements that he says, and you should read this book by Warren Buffett,

03:34:07.780 --> 03:34:09.500
[Guest]: which is not a glorifying book.

03:34:09.500 --> 03:34:15.660
[Guest]: It's by a book guy called Roger Lovenstein called Buffett, as unimaginative as that,

03:34:15.660 --> 03:34:19.700
[Guest]: but it's a brilliant book because it goes through his life in a different way.

03:34:19.700 --> 03:34:24.620
[Guest]: There's another book which he's written called When Genius Failed, which talks about why

03:34:24.620 --> 03:34:29.900
[Guest]: this algorithmic trading thing, when people think that they're too intelligent, what happens?

03:34:29.900 --> 03:34:35.260
[Guest]: It was a book, it's a story of think or long term capital management run by Nobel laureates.

03:34:35.260 --> 03:34:38.100
[Guest]: So they brought down the whole economic system.

03:34:38.100 --> 03:34:43.860
[Guest]: And you know what, to this date, their formula continues to be followed religiously by everybody,

03:34:43.860 --> 03:34:48.140
[Guest]: including regulators, saying this is the only formula that exists because in spite of his

03:34:48.140 --> 03:34:53.020
[Guest]: dramatic failure, we don't have an alternative, got to have something to believe in, man.

03:34:53.020 --> 03:35:00.220
[Guest]: So you know, that's unfortunately the, I won't recommend too many books because you know,

03:35:00.220 --> 03:35:03.060
[Guest]: you don't have to have something to believe in, you don't have to have another hero.

03:35:03.060 --> 03:35:04.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:35:04.060 --> 03:35:05.060
[Amit Varma]: No, When Genius Failed is great.

03:35:05.060 --> 03:35:10.940
[Amit Varma]: And I have read No Rand, a little bit of Graham, all of Talib, though I find him very entertaining

03:35:10.940 --> 03:35:12.300
[Amit Varma]: on Twitter.

03:35:12.300 --> 03:35:15.140
[Amit Varma]: He keeps fighting with all my favorite public intellectuals.

03:35:15.140 --> 03:35:21.180
[Amit Varma]: So that's really, he's blocked me, he's blocked you, oh, you actually interacted with him.

03:35:21.180 --> 03:35:22.180
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:35:22.180 --> 03:35:23.180
[Amit Varma]: There you go.

03:35:23.180 --> 03:35:27.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, he's extremely acerbic in an entertaining way, but he's fought with a lot of people

03:35:27.980 --> 03:35:33.180
[Amit Varma]: I admire on Twitter, like Steven Pinker, Philip Tetlock, Per Ballon, Nate Silver, he just

03:35:33.180 --> 03:35:34.780
[Amit Varma]: shits on all of them all the time.

03:35:34.780 --> 03:35:36.300
[Amit Varma]: So that's good fun.

03:35:36.300 --> 03:35:38.300
[Amit Varma]: No, this is this is like a fabulous list.

03:35:38.300 --> 03:35:43.700
[Amit Varma]: And I'm kind of reminded of how you know, when poker began evolving, like around circa

03:35:43.700 --> 03:35:46.100
[Amit Varma]: 2002, you could have bought books on poker.

03:35:46.100 --> 03:35:49.500
[Amit Varma]: But what has happened over the last 10 years is that there is no book which is really up

03:35:49.500 --> 03:35:50.500
[Amit Varma]: to date.

03:35:50.500 --> 03:35:51.500
[Amit Varma]: It's changing really fast.

03:35:51.500 --> 03:35:53.980
[Amit Varma]: All you have is nuggets of wisdom here and there.

03:35:53.980 --> 03:35:56.940
[Amit Varma]: People who really know shit are not going to share it randomly.

03:35:56.940 --> 03:35:59.180
[Amit Varma]: Because obviously, they're still making money off it.

03:35:59.180 --> 03:36:03.020
[Amit Varma]: So you know, there was a period of time of about five years coinciding with the years

03:36:03.020 --> 03:36:07.540
[Amit Varma]: when I was a pro that you basically had to pick up nuggets from here and there.

03:36:07.540 --> 03:36:09.100
[Amit Varma]: And all the books were outdated.

03:36:09.100 --> 03:36:12.920
[Amit Varma]: And basically, they would lead you down the wrong track.

